<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica-Hangings 1stLd-Writethru a0721 03-14 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa-Hangings, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0721,0513</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Sharpeville Six' To Be Executed Friday, Lawyer Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERT 5 grafs after 7th graf pvs, Theresa Ramashamola ...
UPDATING with British government, Amnesty asking hangings be called
off. Pick up 8th graf pvs, Dlamini's killing ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ``Sharpeville Six,'' a
group of blacks whose murder convictions have drawn protest at home
and abroad, are scheduled to be hanged Friday, one of their lawyers
said Monday.
   Attorney Prakash Diar said an appeal for clemency was denied and
the five men and one woman were notified they will be executed
Friday morning.
   The six were convicted in connection with the killing of black
township councilor Jacob Dlamini in Sharpeville, about 40 miles
south of Johannesburg, on Sept. 3, 1984.
   Evidence at their trial showed the six were not among those who
actually hacked and burned Dlamini to death.
   They were convicted under the doctrine of ``common purpose,''
which holds they were responsible for the killing by being part of
the mob that gathered outside Dlamini's home with the intent to
kill him.
   Human rights groups and government officials, both in South
Africa and internationally, have called for clemency.
   Theresa Ramashamola, 26, is the only woman on death row in South
Africa for what activists consider a politically motivated offense.
   Britain's Conservative Party government expressed hope Monday
night that South Africa will call off the hangings.
   Lynda Chalker, minister of state at the Foreign Office, told the
House of Commons, ``Even at this late stage we sincerely and
earnestly hope that the South African government will heed the
united call of everyone for clemency in these cases.''
   She said Britain backed a United Nations Security Council call
for the sentences to be commuted.
   About 100 lawmakers of Britain's opposition Labor Party signed a
statement expressing ``total condemnation'' of the planned
executions.
   Amnesty International, the London-based human rights
organization, appealed to South African President P.W. Botha to
spare the lives of the six.
   Dlamini's killing came during riots which began a two-year
outbreak of nationwide anti-apartheid protests that left more than
2,000 blacks dead.
   Black activists frequently targeted black township councilors,
considering them collaborators with the white-led government.
   The Media Workers Association of South Africa appealed to the
government Monday to ``demonstrate good will to the people of South
Africa in particular and mankind at large by sparing the lives of
the Sharpeville Six.''
   The scheduled execution date is three days before the
anniversary of the Sharpeville riots of March 21, 1960.
   Sixty-nine blacks were killed when police fired on peaceful
protesters demonstrating against the pass laws, which required
blacks to carry identification documents while in white areas. The
laws have since been repealed.
   The 1960 shootings raised an international storm of protest.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
