<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Panama-Canal     03-14 0630</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama-Canal,0648</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Canal Operated Despite Unrest</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALBOA, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Panama Canal, still one of the
hemisphere's most important pieces of real estate, has allowed
ships to move between the Atlantic and Pacific without interruption
through nine months of political unrest.
   Nearly 13,000 vessels a year avoid the long voyage around Cape
Horn, the southern tip of South America, by traveling 50 miles from
sea to sea through the ``Big Ditch'' that opened in 1914. More than
140 million tons of cargo move through it every year.
   The Panama Canal Treaties signed in 1977 commit the United
States to turn over complete control of the canal and military
installations to Panama by midnight Dec. 31, 1999.
   Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, commander of the Defense Forces and
the man in charge in Panama, claims Washington wants to renege on
the treaties and continue ``occupying'' the canal indefinitely.
   He says the Reagan administration is waging a smear campaign to
try to replace him with an administration it can manipulate.
Noriega was indicted in Florida last month on charges of
involvement in smuggling Colombian cocaine into the United States.
   Although the canal remains an emotional topic of debate, its
strategic importance has declined in the past 30 years.
   Dennis McAuliffe, administrator of the Panama Canal Commission,
says that is because the United States has improved and extended
its military forces.
   ``During and after World War II, through the 1950s, the major
port system was New York and sealift through the canal was about
the only way to reinforce presence in the Pacific, but now there
are major U.S. naval forces in both oceans and major ports on the
West Coast,'' he said.
   ``There is less of a need to transport capital ships through the
canal, and airlift capacity has increased tremendously.''
   Traffic through the canal brings the commission about $320
million a year in tolls.
   Supertankers and the largest bulk carriers are too big for the
three sets of locks that raise and lower vessels 85 feet, but 93
percent of the world's ships can get through, said Richard Wainio,
chief of the commission's Economic and Marketing Division.
   ``The Panamax is still the world's most popular cargo
shipbuilding design,'' he said, referring to the largest vessel the
canal can handle. A Panamax vessel has a beam width of 106 feet.
The locks are 110 feet wide.
   Nor is the canal concept outdated. The United States, Japan and
Panama began a study last year of the feasibility of building
another. Its conclusions are expected in 1992 at the earliest.
   For the United States, the strategic value of what used to be
the Panama Canal Zone is enhanced by the presence of the Southern
Command, involving about 10,000 American soldiers and 20,000
dependents, which is responsible for U.S. military operations in
Latin America.
   It operates half a dozen bases along the canal and has its
headquarters in Quarry Heights, adjacent to Balboa.
   During their long tenure, the Americans built replicas of their
own towns. Communities of white wooden houses on tree-lined streets
named in English still can be found in the 10-mile-wide area that
had been the Canal Zone.
   McAuliffe said this week that day-to-day coordination between
his commission and Panamanian port authorities is ``easy, fluid and
very effective.''
   This month, there had been several bomb threats, which he called
``an irritant,'' and the commision flew in large quantities of cash
because of Panama's banking crisis to cover the paychecks of canal
employees. The latest checks were handed out Monday.
   Under sanctions imposed last week, the Reagan administration is
withholding monthly payments to Panama of about $6.6 million for
canal operations and putting the money in escrow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
