<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HondaShip     03-14 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Honda Ship,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ship Carrying Japan-Bound Hondas Returns To U.S.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cracked fuel line threw a metric wrench
into a plan by Honda to become the first Japanese automaker to
transport its U.S.-built cars back to Japan for sale.
   The auto carrier Green Bay, built in Japan last year, was
examined by repair crews Monday, a day after it slipped quietly
back into port here with its cargo of 540 U.S.-built Accords and
100 Honda motorcyles.
   The ship's owner, Central Gulf Lines of New Orleans, declined to
comment, but Honda spokesman Shin Tanaka in Detroit said a fuel
line crack forced the ship's return.
   He said Honda Motor Co. Ltd. was postponing from March 22 to
April 8 a gala reception to welcome the vessel at Narashino Port,
east of Tokyo. If necessary, he said, the cargo will be moved to
another ship from the Green Bay, which has made several successful
trips for Honda since it was completed Oct. 29 by Mitsui
Engineering & Shipbuilding Ltd.
   The ship departed March 7 with much fanfare, after Tetsuo Chino,
president of Honda North America Inc., drove the first car on board
and held a news conference with Sen. Bob Packwood, R-Ore.
   Francois L. Elmealeh of the Port of Portland's marine marketing
department said the problems with the ship didn't threaten the
cargo or crew.
   ``I think it's an embarrassment more than anything,'' Elmealeh
said.
</TEXT>
