<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Simon 1stLd-Writethru a0794 03-14 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Simon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0794,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Simon Shrugs Off Poll Suggesting He's Losing Ground In Illinois</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS grafs 8-9 pvs, `Simon still ... he said,' with 3 grafs
to UPDATE with Washington Post-ABC News poll showing Simon with
strong lead; PICKS UP 10th graf pvs bgng, `I would'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Paul Simon shrugged off new poll results
suggesting his lead in his home state had diminished to a tie with
Jesse Jackson, but conceded Sunday that his Democratic campaign was
hampered by not having the money to buy television ads in Illinois.
   ``Obviously, not to have paid media hampers me in Illinois,''
Simon said as he campaigned in the city's Chinatown neighborhood.
``But the only way I could have paid media would be to use up the
resources and obligate the matching funds that are coming.''
   That would have left Simon unable to afford television
advertising in Wisconsin, New York and other states with contests
upcoming, he said.
   ``Frankly, I'm not in it just for Illinois _ otherwise I'd go on
paid media. ... I want to win the nomination _ not buy the
nomination,'' he added.
   But the results of a Chicago Tribune poll to be published in
Monday's editions suggested Simon's campaign was faltering in
Illinois, despite his record as a state representative and U.S.
senator.
   The poll of 500 registered Democrats indicated 32 percent
supported Jackson, 29 percent backed Simon and 20 percent favored
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis. However, the poll, taken for
the Tribune by Peter D. Hart and Associates, has a margin of error
of plus or minus five percentage points, making the race a dead
heat.
   The poll, taken Friday and Saturday, updates one taken earlier
last week that showed Simon leading with 35 percent, followed by
Jackson with 30 percent and Dukakis with 18 percent.
   Simon still insisted he would carry his home state on Tuesday,
saying, ``I think the people of Illinois are going to make a sound
decision.''
   And his optimism appeared to be supported by a poll for The
Washington Post and ABC News which was published in Monday's
editions of the newspaper.
   That poll showed Simon holding a strong lead with 42 percent,
Jackson 33 percent, Dukakis 14 percent, Sen. Gore of Tennessee 4
percent, Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri 3 percent and others and
undecided, 4 percent. The poll was based on telephone interviews
Friday night and Saturday with 287 Illinois Democratic voters who
were likely to cast ballots. The margin of error was 6 percent.
   ``I would add that four years ago there wasn't a single poll
that showed me ahead and I won,'' Simon said, referring to his
upset victory in a U.S. Senate race against Republican incumbent
Charles Percy.
   Meanwhile, Dukakis, who has assaulted Simon's campaign with a
blitz of last-minute television advertising, accused Simon of
``doing a disservice to the Democratic Party'' by talking up the
likelihood of a brokered presidential convention in Atlanta.
   ``I think the notion of a brokered convention would be an
absolute disaster,'' Dukakis said Sunday.
   ``The reality is we're not going to have a first-ballot
nominee,'' Simon countered. ``And those brokered conventions have
produced candidates ... like Franklin Roosevelt, Harry Truman and
John F. Kennedy, and it turned out quite well for the American
people.''
</TEXT>
