<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-88 0021EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ChildSexAbuse     03-14 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Child Sex Abuse,0587</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trial Of Former Day Care Teacher Nearing End</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JULIA DOLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's been nearly three years since a
toddler's visit to a doctor sparked what has become the marathon
trial of Margaret Kelly Michaels, a former day-care teacher accused
of sexually abusing her students.
   Ms. Michaels, 26, resigned from the Wee Care Day Nursery in
Maplewood in April 1985 after working for six months. A few days
later, a boy, now 7, told a nurse taking his temperature rectally
that Ms. Michaels did the same to him.
   The school was closed soon afterward, and by December 1985, Ms.
Michaels had been indicted on 235 counts of sexually abusing 31
3-to 5-year-old students.
   The charges have since been reduced to 20 students. Closing
arguments in the trial, which began nine months ago in Superior
Court in Newark, are expected to begin Tuesday.
   The prosecution contends Ms. Michaels performed sexual acts on
the children, forced them to perform sexual acts on her, engaged
them in nude sex play and threatened further harm if they told of
the abuse.
   Ms. Michaels, who once aspired to be an actress, has been free
on $25,000 bail and living with her family in Pittsburgh since
January 1986.
   All but 128 charges of abuse have been dropped because of lack
of evidence and recent higher court rulings that clarified what
testimony is admissible in child sex abuse cases.
   ``We'll all be glad when it's over,'' Ms. Michaels' attorney,
Harvey Meltzer, said last week. ``We are very, very optimistic
she'll be acquitted on all charges.''
   Assistant Prosecutor Glenn D. Goldberg said, ``We feel there is
no reason to disbelieve the children's testimony about what
happened.''
   The boy who went to the doctor three years ago testified via
closed-circuit television last June that Ms. Michaels once took his
temperature and that of two friends using a rectal thermometer.
   The boy's mother testified earlier he told her in April 1985
that Ms. Michaels used a rectal thermometer daily on children.
   The mother and son were among about 120 prosecution witnesses.
In all, 19 children testified via closed-circuit television from
Judge William F. Harth's chambers. Ms. Michaels took the stand
earlier this month, and was one of 22 defense witnesses.
   The defense has argued there was not ``the time, space or
opportunity'' in the bustling environment of the school for Ms.
Michaels to commit the alleged offenses.
   But the prosecution said Ms. Michaels, whose duties included
supervising napping children, created opportunities. They contend
she sometimes took children, without permission, to a remote music
room and played the piano during sex games.
   The defense also says the children were prompted in their
allegations by investigators, psychologists and prosecutors.
Experts for the prosecution testified children cannot be
``brainwashed'' and could not have made up the stories.
   The prosecution also said Ms. Michaels' presented a false image
of herself.
   ``As a four-year drama student, a lot of what she was doing on
the witness stand was an attempt to appear spontaneous when in fact
it was not spontaneous,'' Goldberg said.
   But Metzler said: ``What we have is a very, very large jigsaw
puzzle that the jury must complete. ... We are going to show there
are pieces missing from the puzzle. Then it's up to the jury to
determine if the missing pieces amount to a reasonable doubt.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
