<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Rudofsky     03-14 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Rudofsky,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rudofsky, Architect and Social Commentator, Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bernard Rudofsky, an architect and social
commentator, has died at age 82.
   Rudofsky died of cancer Saturday at New York University Hospital.
   He wrote on a variety of subjects, ranging from the relationship
between the body and clothes to how streets are used in cities.
   Rudofsky's books and museum exhibitions influenced not only
architecture but fashion, interior design, urban planning and food.
   ``He was our most perceptive and outspoken critic of human
habits and habitations,'' said the chief editor of Interior Design
magazine, Stanley Abercrombie.
   Rudofsky first made waves in 1944 with an exhibition at the
Museum of Modern Art entitled ``Are Clothes Modern?''
   The exhibition, which examined the incompatibility of the human
body and clothing, showed one of his contributions to fashion, the
``Bernardo Sandal,'' a curved piece of leather with straps.
   Twenty years later, Rudofsky had an exhibit at the Museum of
Modern Art called ``Architecture Without Architects'' on vernacular
architecture _ the design of buildings built in societies,
sometimes ancient or primitive, that he believed were without
pretensions.
   Rudofsky, who was born and educated in Vienna, received a
master's degree in architecture and engineering and a doctorate in
technical sciences at the Technical University. He practiced
architecture for several years in Italy.
   He has lived in New York since 1935.
   His books included ``Streets for People,'' in which he examined
how streets are used in cities around the world, and ``The
Unfashionable Human Body,'' which looked at the relationship
between the body and clothing.
   Rudofsky taught at Yale University, the Massachusetts Institute
of Technology, the Royal Academy of Fine Arts in Copenhagen and
Waseda University in Tokyo.
   He is survived by his wife, Berta.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
