<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDSBenefit 2ndLd-Writethru a0412 03-14 0632</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Benefit, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0412,0641</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AIDS Benefit With Elizabeth Taylor Raises $2 Million</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 4th graf pvs to add background on
Taylor's role in evening's events, picking up 5th graf pvs, `As
the...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SANDRA WALEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amid the glitter and glamour of
Elizabeth Taylor and a parade of other celebrities, a gala benefit
Sunday raised $2 million for AIDS, which organizers said made it
the largest private fund-raiser for the disease ever.
   ``That's so much money ... I mean that's so incredibly much
money, and the things that money will do!'' said Ms. Taylor.
``We're talking about living or dying. And it's getting closer and
closer to all of us. ... We want to do something about it.
   ``The government can help to a certain point. Dollars can help
to a certain point,'' she said.
   The evening's total was about $2 million, said James Figetakis,
an associate of Ms. Taylor's publicist, Chen Sam.
   Ms. Taylor chairs the American Foundation for AIDS Research,
which will receive part of the funds. She served as hostess and
chief drawing card at the gala.
   As the finale swung into full force Sunday night, a steady
stream of stars in sparkling jewels and dresses began arriving at
the Fontainebleau Hilton Hotel here. They expressed gratitude they
could contribute in the battle against AIDS.
   ``It's really an honor for me to be here,'' actor Matt Dillon
said. ``It's a real problem everywhere, not just in America, but
all over the world. Anything I can do to help is why I'm here.''
   ``I think it's about time South Florida got involved in the
fight against AIDS,'' said Miami Vice star Saundra Santiago. ``I'm
very happy to be here to support this.''
   Other stars on hand included Lauren Hutton, Cheryl Tiegs, Ben
Vereen, Marlee Matlin, Donna Summers, Grace Jones, Margaux
Hemingway, Eddie Albert, Susan Anton and Van Johnson. Organizers
say they hope the benefit will serve as a model for similar
fund-raising efforts elsewhere.
   ``We've had the most private funds raised (for acquired immune
deficiency syndrome) at this one function than any other place in
the country,'' said event spokesman Charles Cinnamon. ``We want it
to be the prototype for the rest of the country.''
   Despite a lack of corporate sponsorships, which had been
expected to raise some $500,000 of the initial $3 million goal,
tickets to the ``grand finale'' at the hotel here sold out and
private donations were giving the fund drive an added boost,
organizers said.
   Stars and guests were invited Sunday to attend about a dozen
black-tie parties from Miami to Palm Beach, being held at the homes
of local celebrities and prominent community leaders for $2,500 a
plate, before converging in Miami Beach for the finale.
   The AIDS benefit was spearheaded by the Community Alliance
Against AIDS, a fund-raising arm of the University of Miami School
of Medicine. Proceeds from the event were being split between the
university's AIDS programs and the American Foundation for AIDS
Research, a non-profit group chaired by Ms. Taylor, which supports
research and education.
   In Palm Beach, Celia Lipton Farris raised at least $137,000 in
advance ticket sales for a private party being held in her home
with Ms. Taylor and some 300 guests. During the event, Ms. Farris,
a former child star and widow of a wealthy industrialist, announced
she was giving an additional $1.1 million, Figetakis said.
   Funds raised in Palm Beach will go toward the Comprehensive AIDS
Program, an organization in West Palm Beach and Belle Glade that
cares for AIDS victims.
   Other private dinner parties were being held in the homes of
singer Julio Iglesias, theatrical producer Zev Bufman and David
Paul, chief executive officer of Centrust Bank, among others.
</TEXT>
