<DOCNO> AP880314-0021 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-88 0146EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CandidateGore Bjt   03-14 0830</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Candidate Gore, Bjt,830</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gore Draws On Disparate Background To Appeal To Different Groups</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Standing before an only mildly interested
crowd at a county fair in Florida last week, Democratic
presidential candidate Albert Gore Jr. introduced himself.
   ``I am the only active farmer in this race for president,'' he
said, stirring as good an applause as he got for the rest of his
speech.
   The 39-year-old Harvard-educated senator from Tennessee,
perpetually clad in a blue suit, could be accused of stretching it
a bit with that statement.
   True, home is a modest farmhouse hard by the Caney Fork River at
rural Carthage, Tenn., set amid the Gore family farm operation.
Gore, though, has hardly made his living working its soil.
   But his statement, often repeated, is emblematic of Gore as a
man of varying backgrounds and worlds who has so far been able to
balance them all.
   Gore made the leap to the top tier of Democratic presidential
candidates last week in the Super Tuesday primaries. He won six
states, five in the South plus Nevada, and accomplished his aim: to
use the biggest ever regional primary to jump-start a presidential
campaign.
   He faces the task now of backing up his claim of being more than
a regional candidate.
   While he is competing in the Illinois primary Tuesday, his hope
is to advance as the primaries move across the North, arguing that
he is the white alternative to Gov. Michael Dukakis, the delegate
leader. He depicts Dukakis as a Massachusetts liberal who, if
nominated, could cause another landslide Democratic loss.
   Now that the campaign has moved out of the South, Gore can be
expected to rely less on his rural background than on his urban
background. He has one of each.
   Gore is the son of a veteran Tennessee politician. Albert Gore
Sr. spent 32 years in Congress, first in the House and later in the
Senate, before losing his seat in 1970.
   Gore Jr. was born and educated in Washington, D.C., and attended
the elite St. Albans prep school in Washington and then Harvard.
His wife, Mary Elizabeth or ``Tipper'' as she is better known, was
a high school sweetheart in Washington.
   He was the all-American boy: bright, honors student, played
basketball and football. He was accustomed to seeing the powerful
of Washington and can tell stories as a youngster of John Kennedy
and then-Vice President Richard Nixon.
   Yet like the congressman he would become, Gore kept up his ties
back home.
   As his father faced his final battle for re-election, and his
opposition to the Vietnam War threatened his seat, Gore Jr. joined
the Army and was sent to Vietnam. He served as an Army journalist.
   He returned to Tennessee and a reporter's job at the Nashville
Tennessean, hired by the publisher himself. He entered both
divinity school and law school, not completing either. He quit law
school after two years when the House seat his father once held
came open.
   Returning to Washington as a House member himself, in 1976, and
as a senator in 1984, Gore's Eastern background served him well.
   He was singled out early on by some monied, establishment
Democrats as a young man on the move, a potential presidential
candidate.
   He was well connected and worked hard. He immersed himself in
the arcane, technical ins-and-outs of issues such as arms control,
medical technology and the space program.
   As a campaigner, Gore draws on his various backgrounds. In the
South he told country-lawyer jokes and talked about hypnotizing
chickens _ one of the rural arts he claims to have mastered.
   But he also won the endorsement of the New Republic magazine,
whose editor was a former teacher of his at Harvard.
   Gore has also moved among Nashville's country music crowd. He
campaigned with country singer Johnny Cash, and rubbed elbows with
hard-living country rebel Hank Williams Jr. Yet his wife Tipper has
led a campaign against raw lyrics in rock music, a campaign that
has stirred opposition from some parts of the entertainment and
music industry.
   The Gores have four children, ages 5 through 14, who live and go
to school in suburban Washington. Gore sometimes brings along one
or more of his children on campaign trips, without their mother,
including 5-year-old Albert.
   Gore will turn 40 on March 31. If elected, he would be the
youngest president ever, following the oldest. He often makes the
comparison to young John Kennedy following the elderly Dwight
Eisenhower in 1960.
   Despite a voting record decidedly more liberal than some of
Tennessee's other representatives, Gore won election to the Senate
overwhelmingly four years ago when Republican Howard Baker declined
to run again.
   Whenever a questioner challenge's Gore's claim to be a moderate,
or his credentials as a son of the South, Gore recalls that 1984
election. Gore won 61 percent of the vote, running ahead of even
Ronald Reagan, who got 58 percent of Tennessee's vote.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880314-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-88 0153EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Salvador-Elections Bjt   03-14 0782</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Salvador-Elections, Bjt,0808</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thieves Or Murderers: Salvadorans Slinging Mud In Election
Campaign</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To judge from the vitriolic
campaign, Salvadorans have a choice between thieves and murderers
when they cast their ballots in legislative and municipal elections
next Sunday.
   Tough campaigning has been common in El Salvador in the years
when civilian politics has prevailed over the exercise of power by
force of arms.
   But this time around the denigration of opposing parties'
candidates and institutions has eclipsed most attempts to inform
the electorate of proposals for resolving this tiny Central
American country's tremendous problems.
   At stake are all 60 seats in the Legislative Assembly and the
mayorships and councils of 262 municipalities nationwide. About 1.9
million of the country's 5 million people are eligible to vote.
   The governing Christian Democrats are expected to lose their
majority in the assembly and such a defeat would turn President
Jose Napoleon Duarte's last year in office into an uphill climb.
   ``The election campaign is poisoning the country, deepening
resentment and hate and putting even farther off the reconciliation
of a divided people,'' said Rafael Moreno Guillen in his column in
La Prensa Grafica, the nation's most widely read paper.
   Monsignor Gregorio Rosa Chavez, auxiliary bishop of San
Salvador, said in his homily Sunday: ``We would like to be able to
say that the politicians offer a clear alternative to the violent
methods that affect innocent people. But the political forum has
likewise been converted into a war of insults.''
   The party expected to make the biggest gains is the Republican
Nationalist Alliance, or Arena, an ultra-rightist group. Prominent
Christian Democrats have conceded they have little chance of
retaining their majority.
   Adolfo Rey Prendes, the front-runner for the Christian
Democratic presidential nomination, predicted at a recent news
conference that his party would lose eight of its current 33 seats
in the assembly. Presidential elections are scheduled for next year.
   Rey Prendes attributed the decline to ``the natural erosion of
support experienced by a party that governs in difficult times.''
   El Salvador is suffering in its eighth year of a civil war that
has killed about 65,000 people, displaced 500,000 and ravaged its
economy.
   The leftist guerrilla alliance battling the U.S.-supported
government has denounced the elections as a farce and declared the
voting will not be allowed to proceed in the northern and eastern
regions under rebel control.
   El Salvador receives more U.S. aid than any country in the
Western hemisphere. Economic and military aid last year was more
than $500 million.
   The military said last week it could guarantee voting in 244 of
the 262 municipalities. Defense Minister Gen. Carlos Vides Casanova
said 40,000 troops will be deployed to guard against any guerrilla
attempts to disrupt the voting.
   Eight parties _ all centrist or rightist _ are presenting
candidates, but only three are competing nationwide. Left-of-center
parties declined to participate, citing lack of security for their
candidates.
   Rightist death squads killed several thousand leftist union and
political activists in El Salvador in the early 1980s. Human rights
groups say the squads remain intact, and the Roman Catholic Church
recently denounced what it said was an increase in the number of
politically motivated murders.
   Arena and its founder, retired army Maj. Roberto d'Aubuisson,
have been linked to the death squads since the party's formation in
1982.
   At a recent Christian Democratic campaign rally in Panchimalco,
six miles south of San Salvador, speakers repeatedly referred to
D'Aubuisson's group as ``torturers'' and ``killers.''
   Arena, for its part, calls the PDC _ the Christian Democratic
Party's initials in Spanish _ the party of the corrupt.
   Arena, which has 13 legislators in the current assembly, is not
expected to win an outright majority. But most observers believe it
will win almost as many seats as the Christian Democratic Party.
   That could leave the National Conciliation Party _ the third
group competing nationwide _ with the balance of power.
   The rightist National Conciliation Party was formed by the
military and governed for nearly 20 years before a 1979 coup. It
formed an alliance with Arena in the 1985 legislative elections.
   But the National Conciliation Party, in an effort to portray
itself as moderate, eschewed the alliance this time around.
``Against the death squads and the thieves, PCN,'' has been its
slogan in this campaign.
   The Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, which groups five
rebel organizations, said in a communique last month:
   ``The country has lost its sovereignty (to the United States)
and democracy does not exist. Rather there is a new kind of
military dictatorship with a civilian facade. Without independence,
no election is legitimate.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
