<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Close Lower In Tokyo</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with closing market figures. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks closed lower and the dollar fell against the
Japanese yen in Tokyo on Monday as dealers' expectations for U.S.
trade figures due out on Thursday grew more pessimistic.
   The dollar closed at 127.23 yen, down 0.57 yen from Friday's
close of 127.80 yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues closed at 25,433.51 points, down 110.22 points, or
0.43 percent, from Friday's close.
   Dealers said the dollar fell due to speculation that figures for
the United States' trade deficit for January would be higher than
previously expected.
   Traders on the stock market were also waiting for the U.S. trade
figures, according to an analyst with a major brokerage who spoke
on condition of anonymity. ``Trading was not so heavy in the first
section, aside from some heavy industrials, steel and
electricals,'' the analyst said.
</TEXT>
