<1ST_LINE>r w PM-PLO-Congress     03-14 0721</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PLO-Congress,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressional Aides Hold Secret Meeting with Arafat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some lawmakers say they think a group of
congressional aides used bad judgment in attending a secret meeting
in January with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
   ``It was very foolish,'' Rep. Larry Smith, D-Fla., said last
week after the meeting became public. ``That was the wrong thing to
do.''
   The two-hour meeting with Arafat, arranged by the National
Council on U.S.-Arab Relations, took place in Baghdad, Iraq, a few
weeks after Congress passed legislation closing the Palestine
Liberation Organization offices in the United States on the grounds
the PLO supports terrorism. Arafat heads the PLO.
   Ronald W. Cathell, executive director of the council, said the
meeting was constructive because it gave the congressional aides a
chance to see Arafat in the flesh and conduct a ``candid,
forthright'' discussion with him.
   In response to a question from one Capitol Hill staff member,
Arafat told the group the man he admired most in history was Saint
Peter because the disciple of Jesus ``conquered Rome by winning the
hearts'' of f the staffers. He said
they could be subjected to reprisals.
   People with knowledge of the free trip said those who went to
Iraq worked for Sens. Mark Hatfield, R-Ore.; John Heinz, R-Pa.; J.
Bennett Johnston, D-La., David Karnes, R-Neb; and Reps. Edward F.
Feighan, D-Ohio; Robert Torricelli, D-N.J.; Helen Bentley, R-Md.;
Douglas Bereuter, R-Neb.; William Clay, D-Mo.; James Inhofe,
R-Okla., and Robert Lagomarsino, R-Calif.
   All but one of the aides on the trip attended the Arafat
meeting, a State Department official said, speaking on condition he
remain anonymous.
   Several aides who traveled to Iraq refused to talk about what
happened in the meeting, and would only discuss the trip if their
names were not used. After the Arafat meeting, group members
realized the significance of their action and made a pact to keep
it secret, one said.
   Rep. Robert G. Torricelli, D-N.J., said he was upset when he
learned an aide had seen Arafat without his permission.
   ``She acted independently, and I had no knowledge of this
meeting nor would I have approved it, and I remain very disturbed
about it.'' The staffer no longer works for Torricelli, but left
for personal reasons unrelated to the meeting.
   Feighan, however, was unconcerned. He said his assistant ``was
not on any official trip and he was traveling in a personal
capacity.''
   But several Capitol Hill staffers who deal exclusively with
foreign policy _ the Middle East in particular _ said they never
would have accepted the invitation in view of U.S. policy.
   The meeting was ``extremely unwise when as a matter of law
American officials are not supposed to negotiate with the PLO,''
said Michael Van Dusen, staff director of the House Foreign Affairs
subcommittee on Europe and the Middle East.
   The policy _ imposed by Congress _ prohibits officials in the
executive branch from negotiating with the PLO until the group
recognizes Israel's right to exist.
   But the policy does not apply to Congress, and a few lawmakers
as well as staff members have met openly with Arafat in the past.
Rep. Nick Rahall, D-W.Va., for example, saw Arafat in a bunker in
West Beirut in Lebanon in 1982.
   Torricelli complained that the U.S. Embassy in Baghdad failed to
advise his aide about U.S. policy on the PLO. But a State
Department official, refusing to be identified by name, said the
U.S. ambassador had tried to dissuade the Americans from meeting
with Arafat. No embassy personnel went to the session.
   The original agenda did not list an Arafat meeting. Once the
group arrived in Baghdad, Cathell said he learned the PLO leader
was in town and broached the possibility of a meeting with the
congressional aides.
   The staffers were never pressured to attend the meeting, Cathell
said. Instead they were told, ``It's totally up to you,'' he said.
   One aide, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the group was
given less than an hour's notice that a face-to-face meeting with
Arafat had been set.
   The national council seeks to promote understanding between
Americans and Arabs, and receives its money from grants and private
and corporate contributions.
</TEXT>
