<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Anderson-Hometown     03-14 0543</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Anderson-Hometown,0558</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hometown Marks Fourth Anniversary Of Newsman's Capture</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Anderson Anniversary, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARREN DOPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATAVIA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It comes as a small but meaningful reward
to Peggy Say that the people in her hometown are rallying behind
her call to remember the hostages in Lebanon.
   There were many times when it seemed people didn't want to hear
about how her brother, journalist Terry Anderson, was still being
held. There was the stinging criticism that maybe she was somehow
to blame for his prolonged captivity.
   It's different now. Her brother's defiant expression is seen on
posters in the stores and restaurants of this rural upstate town 40
miles east of Buffalo.
   The posters say: ``Remember Terry Anderson on the anniversary of
his captivity, March 16, 1988. Please wear a yellow ribbon and pray
for the hostages in Lebanon.''
   Prayer services, a rally and a candlelight march down main
street are scheduled to mark the beginning of the fourth year of
captivity for the 40-year-old Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press.
   ``This is the first time we've gotten this kind of support,''
said Mrs. Say. ``People just assumed that the government's quiet
diplomacy was the answer. Now, I think they realize it isn't
working.''
   Many of this week's activities in Batavia, where Anderson grew
up, have been organized by the Rev. Thomas Vickers, pastor and
friend of the Say family. Vickers asked florists to donate ribbon
to decorate downtown. While most of the town's seven florists
agreed, one shop provided more than 2 miles of yellow ribbon.
   Inside John Hamel's flower shop are thousands of yellow bows,
hung on garlands, that are being handed out to residents who
request them. Hamel said that it was ``just a small thing'' he
could do to help.
   A nun at Notre Dame High School has made a huge greeting card
that will be on display at the Genesee Country Mall beginning
Saturday so that residents can sign it. It will be sent to Lebanon.
   Mrs. Say's daughter, Melody Brewington, said the turnout for an
observance of the anniversary last year was disappointing. This
time the response has been overwhelming, she said.
   Mrs. Say will not be here, but at the Holy Trinity Church in
Washington, D.C., for a service for hostage family members.
   ``I wish I could be here, too,'' she said. ``There has been such
an outpouring of concern. It would please Terry so much to know
that people really haven't forgotten him.''
   There are 22 foreigners, including nine Americans, missing and
believed held by Moslem fundamentalists in Lebanon. Anderson has
been held the longest.
   From ex-hostages and other sources, Mrs. Say has learned that
her brother is being held alone in a windowless room, fighting the
boredom and loneliness of his solitary existence. He is often
blindfolded and has been beaten and harassed.
   Mrs. Say has been tireless in calling for more to be done for
the hostages.
   ``If they (the hostages) are no longer important to the people
of America or this administration, then (the captors) will think
they have to make a political statement by executing them. That's
what waits for them if all of us don't keep them alive in the
public eye.''
</TEXT>
