<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson-Money     03-14 0717</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson-Money,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Campaign Could Move Into Financial Big Leagues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson likes to say he has the ``poor
campaign with a rich message,'' but he may have to alter that
slogan a bit if his fund-raising trends continue.
   Jackson's mail consultant Mal Warwick said that while Jackson is
not in the league of other multi-million-dollar presidential
contenders, the response to his mail solicitations is so
overwhelming that Warwick has had to increase his 12-person
money-counting staff to 30 over the past two months.
   It is too early to tell how Jackson's strong showing in the
Super Tuesday states will affect his contributions, Warwick said.
But he added, ``Money has been coming in so far ahead of
projections that we are struggling to keep up with it.''
   The mail results have grown steadily since last fall, when about
$150,000 per month was coming in, said campaign treasurer Howard
Renzi. That increased to about $270,000 in January.
   And in February, the month when primaries and caucuses began,
$400,000 of the $750,000 the campaign raised came in through the
mail, Renzi said.
   ``We're starting to approach the time where we'll have the
financial wherewithal to be more competitive,'' he said, adding
that a good part of the money raised by mail is going back into the
mail program to develop a bigger base of contributors.
   Jackson still has a long way to go to catch up with Democratic
money leader Michael Dukakis, who had raised some $15 million by
the end of January, including federal matching funds, to Jackson's
$3.3 million.
   Jackson has made much of the fact that he has done well despite
being outspent by as much as 30 times in states where his opponents
put on heavy media campaigns.
   But his sophisticated mail program is producing results that
were unheard of in Jackson's 1984 campaign, when taking a
collection at revival-style rallies was his most frequent
fund-raising approach.
   Warwick runs a state-of-the-art direct mail and telemarketing
operation, utilizing lists of names purchased from other mail
soliciters to determine which categories of people would be most
likely to give to Jackson.
   ``We're using every technique in the book,'' he said, and
sending mail to a broad spectrum of progressive Democrats. The mail
includes everything from postcards to sophisticated packets and
questionnaires through first-class mail.
   In addition to the mail, Jackson's campaign chairman Willie
Brown, influential speaker of the California state assembly, said
there will be a series of concerts to raise money in the weeks to
come. Brown, one of the most successful fund-raisers in California
politics, also said this week he will try to extract $1 million
from the state's ``bleeding hearts'' whom he said should be giving
money to Jackson.
   Warwick said about one mailing per week goes out, ranging in
size from 5,000 pieces to previous contributors, to 400,000 pieces
in a search for new donors.
   ``The results we are obtaining are as strong as anything I've
ever witnessed in all my time of direct mail fund-raising,''
Warwick said.
   Warwick's Berkeley, Calif., firm, Changing America, Inc.,
handled direct mail for the presidential campaign of Gary Hart last
year before Hart dropped out of the race the first time, and has
several liberal organizations as clients.
   One ``Dear Fellow American Citizen'' letter from Jackson was
sent to white liberal Democratics in affluent West Los Angeles. In
what the industry calls the ``involvement'' approach, it included
an ``issues survey'' asking the reader's opinion on Jackson's key
issues.
   Another mailing that went out after the Feb. 8 Iowa caucuses
highlighted Jackson's 8 percent showing in a state with a 1.4
percent black population as evidence that he has support outside
the black community, contrary to what ``so called political
experts'' had claimed.
   Warwick said that since names on his mailing lists are
``overwhelmingly non-black,'' white people obviously are
contributing to Jackson.
   ``For us to get the results we are getting means he has very
substantial support among white mail donors,'' he said.
   Warwick would not be specific on the rate of return for the
amount of mail sent out, but said it was ``much better'' than the 1
percent to 1.5 percent return that is typical for so-called
prospecting mail, in which new donors are sought out.
</TEXT>
