<HEAD>North Dakota Democrats Begin District Conventions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Dakota Democrats have begun a
two-week process of picking the delegates who will attend the state
convention and eventually cast ballots for president.
   Rep. Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., and Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis have maintained the most active campaign offices in the
state, said George Gaukler, chairman of the state Democratic Party.
   Democrats in the state hold 53 district conventions, which began
Sunday and will continue until March 27, to select delegates to the
state convention in Fargo. Convention-goers will cast their ballots
for president on April 16, the third day of their four-day
convention.
   Delegates to the national convention in Atlanta will be chosen
based on their presidential preference. Straw polls of the
presidential race will be taken at each district convention,
according to the party.
   State Sen. Allen Richard, Gephardt's state campaign coordinator,
said, ``We'll be working hard at creating Gephardt preference
caucuses at the district conventions.''
   ``We feel his moderate message on agriculture and trade is more
in line with the thinking of North Dakotans,'' he added.
   Ellen Austin, state coordinator of the Dukakis campaign, said
Dukakis volunteers will also attend district conventions.
   ``Our committee has felt all along that he was leading in this
state, and we still feel he's the leader,'' she said.
</TEXT>
