<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson-Neighborhood     03-14 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson-Neighborhood,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chicago's Chatham Neighborhood Pulling for Jesse Jackson</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In Chatham, a middle-class black neighborhood of
brick bungalows and neat lawns, people like Clevie Williams are
pulling for Jesse Jackson and proud of his Democratic presidential
bid.
   ``You can't talk to nobody in Chatham unless it's about Jesse,''
said Williams, 66, a retired Army master sergeant. ``They have a
belief they can help him become the Democratic nominee for
president.''
   On the tree-lined streets of Chatham on the predominantly black
South Side, Jackson's strong showing in the Super Tuesday primaries
filled many with hope that maybe, just maybe, a black could be
elected president of the United States of America.
   Most people who paused to talk about Jackson's chances said they
would vote for him and his slated convention delegates in Tuesday's
Illinois primary election.
   ``Every vote counts,'' Williams said. ``All I can say is he's
got a chance. He's got as good a chance as he'll ever have.''
   Like many black neighborhoods across the financial spectrum,
Chatham is Jesse Jackson country. It's a community of about 40,000
people where the median family income was nearly $19,000 in the
1980 census. Most people have jobs and many own their homes, mainly
one- and two-story brick bungalows with an average value of
$39,200, the census found.
   ``I would describe Chatham as a rock-solid black middle-income
community and one that has been that way for probably 20 years,''
said Martin Goldsmith, Chicago's director of community development
planning.
   Jackson's work over the years with Operation PUSH, the
civil-rights group he founded, and his two presidential campaigns
have won the respect of many residents, said housewife Jessie
Blissitt, 50.
   ``He's done a lot for black people,'' she said. ``He's someone
we look up to. He speaks out for what really concerns black people.
We've sort of been shoved aside by all the other candidates.
   ``Because we are a minority, I don't know if he actually could
make it to the presidency,'' Ms. Blissitt said. ``But I'm glad he's
running if for nothing more than to show black kids they can do it,
to give them a goal to strive for.''
   Several people shared her pessimism about whether the nation's
white majority would elect a black president.
   ``People I talk to say he won't make it, due to the fact of his
color,'' said Donald Crawford, 47, an apartment-building janitor.
   Crawford said he planned to vote for Jackson because he likes
his background as a preacher and thinks his bid for the presidency
shows ``guts.''
   ``One thing about him being black, he wasn't born with a silver
spoon in his mouth,'' he added. ``He knows the feeling.''
   Garrett Manuel, also a janitor, paused as he weeded shrubbery in
front of an apartment building and grinned as he thought about
Jackson's Super Tuesday success.
   ``I was surprised, but I really liked that. It made me feel
good,'' said Manuel, 61. ``Most people I've talked to _ they really
think he's going to win. And everybody I've talked to said they
were going to vote for him.''
   But Elizabeth Jones, 66, a retired tax examiner, said she was
torn between Jackson and Sen. Paul Simon, the state's other
favorite son.
   Both candidates seem honest, straightforward and committed to
their principles now, she said, but ``all of them are full of you
know what.''
   ``They promise you one thing and do another when they get in,''
she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
