<1ST_LINE>r p PM-SouthCarolinaDemocrats     03-14 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Carolina Democrats,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Wins Big In South Carolina</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson made an impressive showing
in Democratic caucuses in his native South Carolina over the
weekend and now takes aim at Tuesday's primary in his adopted
Illinois.
   A record turnout estimated at 45,000 people attended the South
Carolina precinct caucuses Saturday. When the meetings were over,
it appeared the Greenville native would collect 23 of the state's
48 national convention delegates.
   Fifteen of the delegates apparently will be uncommitted while
six will go to Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore. The state also has four
super delegates which were not at stake in Saturday's meetings.
   ``We the people have won South Carolina,'' Jackson told a crowd
of about 400 supporters gathered Saturday night at Greenville
Technical College. ``This is a campaign of hope. Each victory adds
another to win.''
   On Sunday, campaigning in Chicago, Jackson said he expected his
South Carolina victory would give him momentum going into the
Tuesday primary in Illinois.
   The South Carolina delegate estimates were based on reports from
93 percent of the state's 1,788 precincts. Carol Kahre of the state
Democratic Party said it could be a couple of days before all the
numbers are in.
   ``The problem now becomes the county party priorities are
preparing for their county conventions,'' she said. State officials
must ``beg a lot'' to get the numbers in, she said.
   Jackson, Gore and Gephardt all campaigned in the state in the
days before the caucuses.
   ``Clearly Jesse Jackson and the undecided are the big winners in
South Carolina,'' Gephardt said while campaigning in Detroit.
   Gore's state campaign chairman, state Rep. Bob Sheheen,
D-Kershaw, claimed that Gore's finish above Dukakis and Gephardt
``is a significant victory.''
   ``I thought if we ran neck and neck with the uncommitted that
would be a great achievement,'' he said, adding he expects the
Gephardt campaign to fold before the state convention giving Gore a
chance to pick up more uncommitted delegates.
   The state organizer for Dukakis, Belton Zeigler, said the
campaign didn't spend much money in the state and ``whatever we get
is gravy in the caucus campaign.''
   Bill Prince, the state campaign coordinator for Gephardt said
``we're going to make our stand in Michigan.''
   He expressed hope that a strong showing there later this month
would allow the congressman to pick up some uncommitted delegates
at the South Carolina state convention next month.
   Earl Black, a University of South Carolina political scientist,
said the record turnout was due to Jackson's organizing and Gore's
strong showing on Super Tuesday.
   ``With South Carolina Jesse Jackson's home state, there was a
very strong incentive in the black community,'' he said.
   ``Some of it was due to Gore's showing on Super Tuesday,'' Black
added. ``Some Democrats felt there was a candidate out there they
could support.''
   Before Super Tuesday, Gore was way back in polls in the state
and he covered a lot of ground in just a few days, Black said.
   ``But it's hard for him to claim a victory when he comes in
behind the undecided,'' Black added.
</TEXT>
