<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BandSurprise     03-14 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Band Surprise,0547</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Michigan High School Band Serenades Young Cancer Patient</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By F.N. D'ALESSIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The high road to Dublin for a 130-member high
school band from Michigan led through a Chicago hospital, where a
schoolmate is recovering from bone cancer surgery.
   The Belding High School band members, who raised $1,000 apiece
to march in Dublin's St. Patrick's Day parade and celebrate the
Irish capital's 1,000th anniversary, traveled 200 miles by bus
Sunday to O'Hare International Airport. Before departing, though,
they made a side trip to serenade 17-year-old Eddie Mikek.
   Their instruments were being packed aboard the plane, so the
musicians who gathered in the lobby of the University of Chicago's
Wyler Children's Hospital and sang.
   Because Eddie is fighting cancer, they sang the Belding fight
song, and because he is their friend, they sang the band's theme
song, ``Friends.''
   ``Eddie's not a band member but he is a good friend,'' said band
director Bob Stiles. ``We just want to remind him that he's one of
us and show our love and concern.''
   About 95 Belding parents also were on hand to surprise Eddie as
he emerged from an elevator in his wheelchair.
   ``There wasn't a dry eye in the whole building,'' said Eddie's
mother, Janice. ``He didn't know they were coming, and it took him
a minute or two to figure out what was happening. Then he started
crying like all the rest of us.''
   ``That's the kind of town Belding is,'' she said of the small
apple-growing community 30 miles east of Grand Rapids. ``We know
almost everyone there and we consider them all friends.''
   Eddie was diagnosed as having bone cancer Dec. 10, a day after
his 17th birthday, Mrs. Mikek said. Before his illness, he had been
an active high school junior, too busy helping at his parents'
grocery store and working a part-time job at a hardware store to
have time for extracurricular activities like athletics or the band.
   For a while after his diagnosis, he was able to attend school
several days a week between chemotherapy treatments, Mrs. Mikek
said, but schoolwork had to stop when he came here for surgery.
   The family had to sell their store, ``because we knew we
wouldn't have time to run it with all the trips to Chicago,'' said
Mrs. Mikek in a telephone interview from the Ronald McDonald House,
where she stays when she is visiting Eddie.
   ``Everybody was here for the serenade,'' said Mrs. Mikek. ``My
husband, Edward, our 18-year-old son, our 7-year-old daughter, our
5-month-old baby and even John and Val Rayborn, who run the
hardware store where Eddie worked. Seeing them is what really got
to him.''
   On March 4, doctors at the hospital removed a tumor from Eddie's
left leg and implanted part of a femur. They also installed a
mechanical knee joint. The relatively new surgical technique,
called limb salvage, avoids amputation, and should allow Eddie to
walk normally in the future, Mrs. Mikek said.
   ``He'll be in the hospital about another two weeks, and then
will begin physical therapy,'' she said. ``All he wants right now
is to be able to walk again, and everything's on hold until he
does.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
