<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Meese-Pipeline     03-14 0671</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Meese-Pipeline,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meese Defends Wallach, Brushes Aside Latest Disclosures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Edwin Meese III says he still
regards as a friend the man whose memos have made him a target of a
criminal investigation into a $1 billion Iraqi oil pipeline project.
   Meese also denies that he untruthfully played down his
involvement in promoting the project with then-Israeli Prime
Minister Shimon Peres.
   A memo by longtime Meese friend E. Robert Wallach says that on
Oct. 16, 1985, Meese, Peres and Wallach had a ``three-way
discussion'' of the project at the Israeli Embassy in Washington.
   On Sunday, James Rocap, one of Meese's lawyers, said ``Wallach's
account totally exaggerates'' the discussion ``in order to impress
his client,'' Swiss oilman Bruce Rappaport, a partner in the
pipeline project.
   Rocap said it is a ``cheap shot'' and ``stupid'' to suggest that
the memo contradicts Meese's earlier portrayals of his contacts
with Peres as limited.
   In a statement issued Feb. 1, Meese said that his total
involvement with Peres on the pipeline consisted of ``only two
contacts ... Each was brief, limited, and neither was initiated by
me.''
   Meese said that The Washington Post, which first disclosed the
memo in its Sunday editions, is ``taking a small fact that's well
known and trying to blow it up into a new news story.''
   The memo discussing the meeting had not been previously reported
prior to the Post article.
   Wallach was paid $150,000 by Rappaport and when Wallach went to
Meese about the project, the attorney general referred him to the
National Security Council.
   ``He is my friend,'' Meese said of Wallach in remarks Sunday on
ABC-TV's ``This Week with David Brinkley.''
   ``Mr. Wallach has never asked me to do anything that was
wrong,'' Meese said. He said ``a lot of people are taking a very
simple situation'' and ``they're trying to make a big deal out of
it.''
   Independent counsel James Mckay is investigating Meese's role in
the pipeline as a result of a memo written to Meese by Wallach
mentioning planned payments to the Israeli Labor Party in a bid to
protect the project in Iraq from Israeli attack.
   Meese says he doesn't recall the portion of the memo dealing
with the planned payments.
   Wallach directed that the $150,000 he received from Rappaport be
placed in an account under the control of W. Franklyn Chinn, an
investment adviser for both Meese and Wallach. The $150,000 ended
up being pooled with funds from Meese in several stock trades.
   Meese's initial $50,000 investment grew to $95,000 with profits
from the stock deals, but the attorney general denied in his
television appearance that he profited from the $150,000. He said
he was not aware at the time of the payment from Rappaport to
Wallach.
   Meese predicted that he would be exonerated in McKay's probe and
said ``I shouldn't step aside because if honest public officials
can be hounded out of office by partisan political attacks ... then
no one as a public official is safe.''
   Another memo by Wallach, also described in Sunday's Post,
recounts a meeting in New York involving Peres, Wallach, the
Israeli ambassador to the United States and then-National Security
Council aide David Wigg. Wallach said the meeting lasted about 15
minutes and that the four discussed two proposed letters for Peres
to sign, the first committing Israel not to disrupt the Iraqi
pipeline and the second dealing with the possibility of using U.S.
foreign aid to Israel as insurance.
   Peres has said in the past that he recalls having met Wallach
only twice, on social occasions with others present.
   Peres eventually signed a later version of the first letter, but
he said he could not act on the second letter without additional
consultations in Israel. The pipeline project collapsed shortly
thereafter, for want of an insurance package which the Iraqis
demanded in the event Israel destroyed the pipeline.
   The Justice Department saw legal obstacles to using Israeli aid
money as part of an insurance package.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
