<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-88 0340EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Gulf-Silkworms     03-14 0810</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf-Silkworms,0832</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Missile Installation Would Extend `Overrated' Threat</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reports that Iran may be planning to
install Silkworm anti-ship missiles on a tiny island in the
southern Persian Gulf add a new element to a much-publicized threat
that some U.S. naval officers say has been greatly overrated.
   Military sources in Washington said surveillance had detected
evidence that crude missile launch pads were being built on Abu
Musa, an outcropping long used as a base for armed speedboat
attacks on gulf shipping by Iran's Revolutionary Guards.
   The sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said there was
still no sign of the missiles being installed. Nor did they
speculate on what purpose the Chinese-built weapons might serve if
located there.
   But missiles on Abu Musa would extend the so-called ``Silkworm
envelope'' along Iran's coast bordering the Strait of Hormuz by
about 100 miles, ``doubling the arc'' of the present threat, a U.S.
source said.
   It would put the missiles, which have a maximum range of 50 to
60 miles, within easy reach of the main shipping channel leading to
and from the Hormuz passage, as well as a populated stretch of the
Arab coast.
   Five of the seven United Arab Emirates port cities _ Dubai,
Sharjah, Ajman, Umm Al Qaiwain and Ras Al-Khaimah _ are 50 miles or
less from Abu Musa.
   Gulf-area diplomats and shipping executives expressed alarm
early last year when it was disclosed that Tehran was deploying
mobile Silkworm batteries along the Hormuz, the only outlet from
the oil-rich gulf to the open sea.
   Iran was said to have successfully test-fired several of the
missiles at an old ship's hulk. Subsequent reports have said Iran
possessed as many as 100 Silkworms, apparently supplied by China,
although Beijing has publicly denied the sales.
   Senior American officials made it clear from the outset that any
Iranian use of the weapon would be met with swift retaliation.
   Then-Defense Secretary Caspar Weinberger said that while
Washington did not contemplate ``pre-emptive strikes,'' even the
activation of a Silkworm's target-tracking radar would be seen as a
hostile act, to which the U.S. Navy would respond.
   Iran's subsequent reluctance to even threaten to use the
missiles in the strategic Hormuz has caused U.S. naval officers to
view the threat with increasing skepticism.
   The convoys of U.S.-flagged Kuwaiti tankers continue to have
protective air cover while passing through the ``envelope,'' but
some warships now sail with crews at less than a full ``battle
stations'' alert status, de rigeur when the operation began last
July.
   ``Of course we can't rule the Silkworms out as a potential
threat, but in my opinion it's been overrated _ right from the
start,'' a U.S. Navy intelligence officer said several months ago.
   Other American officers have said the Silkworms in the Hormuz
are probably the least of their worries in sailing through the gulf.
   More imminent concerns include Iranian speedboats and most of
all, another mistaken Iraqi air strike such as that which wrecked
the missile frigate Stark, killing 37 Americans, last May 17.
   One senior officer said he would not discount the idea of some
``crazies'' firing a Silkworm in defiance of orders, but believed
the danger from a planned attack was virtually nil.
   ``As long as we maintain our retaliatory assets in the Arabian
Sea, that isn't going to occur,'' he said, referring to the U.S.
aircraft carrier _ currently the nuclear-powered Enterprise _
permanently stationed outside the gulf.
   ``The Iranians aren't about to fire one of those things
(Silkworms) at a warship or a ship under navy escort. They know
what would happen if they did. They'd be taken out in minutes,'' he
said.
   Friday's report of Silkworm-related activity on Abu Musa came
just as the only U.S.-flagged ship ever hit by a Silkworm was
sailing past the island.
   The 81,283-ton Sea Isle City, one of the 11 Kuwait-owned tankers
reflagged with the Stars and Stripes for protection from Iranian
attack, was heading out of the gulf in a navy convoy.
   It was the first trip for the ship since it was devastated by a
Silkworm last Oct. 16 while anchored at Kuwait's main offshore oil
terminal. That missile, and a handful of others launched from
Iran-held territory in Iraq's Faw peninsula, are the only ones that
Tehran's forces are known to have fired.
   The Silkworm, officially designated HY-2 by the Chinese, is a
variant of the 30-year-old Soviet Styx missile. The cumbersome,
20-foot-long projectile flies just above the water at subsonic
speed, homing on its target by radar.
   Although the weapon is crude by modern standards, its
1,000-pound warhead can cause severe damage. U.S. naval officials
called the hit on the Sea Isle City a lucky shot, but the tanker
was out of service for nearly five months.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
