<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protesters Rally in Nation's Capital For and Against Israeli
Policy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In anticipation of Israeli Prime Minsister
Yitzhak Shamir's visit today, more than 3,300 people marched to the
White House and rallied near the offices of ABC News for two
opposing causes.
   More than 3,000 people carrying Palestinian flags and chanting
slogans marched to the White House on Sunday to protest Israeli
policies in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   They condemned U.S. policy toward Israel, chanting, ``Reagan,
Shultz, you will see _ Palestine will be free.''
   The demonstrators called on the White House to freeze U.S. aid
to Israel and asked for a moratorium on military aid to Israel
until the Israeli government supports and participates in the peace
process.
   Shamir, who strongly opposes a U.S. peace plan for the Middle
East, is due to arrive in Washington today for talks with President
Reagan and Secretary of State George P. Shultz.
   Meanwhile, about 300 pro-Israel demonstrators rallied near the
offices of ABC News to protest the network's coverage of the
clashes between Israeli soldiers and Arabs in the occupied
territories.
   Speakers urged the crowd to write or call the network to protest
the coverage, while organizers sought signatures on petitions
calling upon the media ``to report the entire story.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>__</HEAD>
<HEAD>British Producer Lines Up Witnesses Against Waldheim For TV Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British producer says he has lined up 70
witnesses, including some who served with Kurt Waldheim in World
War II, to give evidence at a televised ``trial'' of allegations
the Austrian president was involved in Nazi atrocities.
   The list includes some of Waldheim's subordinates and superiors
when he was an officer in the German army from 1939 to 1945, says
Jack Saltman, who is producing the show for broadcast on U.S. and
overseas television in June.
   ``It took a lot of persuasion to get some of them to do it,``
Saltman said in a recent interview.
   The production will be the of result nine days, beginning April
13, of filming lawyers as they examine witnesses as if they were in
a court of law, before a panel of retired jurists, including
Shirley Hufstedler, a former U.S. education secretary and federal
Appeals Court judge.
   The program, which will run four hours, will end with the
judges' decision on whether there is probable cause that Waldheim
acted contrary to the international laws of war.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Aspin Blames Air Force For MX Problems, Service Defends Its
Accuracy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Les Aspin plans to deliver a speech on
the floor of the U.S. House today that says the Air Force is ``part
of the problem'' in the guidance system for the MX missile, but the
service maintains the weapon is reliable and accurate.
   The text of the speech by the Wisconsin Democrat, who is
chairman of the House Armed Services Committee, was made available
Sunday.
   Aspins says his panel's investigation of the 10-warhead weapon
shows there are still problems in producing the missile's inertial
measurement unit (IMU), or guidance system.
   Aspin has previously criticized Northrop, which is building the
IMUs at a Hawthorne, Calif., plant.
   ``Documents recently received by the House Armed Services
Committee show that while Northrop is undeniably having its
difficulties, the Air Force is part of the problem,'' according to
the congressman's latest criticism of the MX.
   He says the document, obtained from persons whom he did not
identify, show that the service considered accepting one IMU
without inspecting it, and also protested the use of a process
exempting small componentns from testing.
   An Air Force spokesman, Capt. Jay Defrank, said, ``We stand by
the IMU's reliability and accuracy. We've answered many of the
charges in his statement. There is nothing new there.''
</TEXT>
