<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Arafat-Globe     03-14 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arafat-Globe,0418</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PLO Leader Says U.S. Peace Plan Doomed</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Israel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yasser Arafat, chairman of the Palestine
Liberation Organization, says the U.S. closing of the PLO's
observer mission at the United Nations would negatively affect
American credibility and U.S. interests.
   Arafat, in an hour-long Boston Globe interview published today,
also said the first casualty of the decision by the U.S. Congress
and the Reagan administration to close the mission will be
Secretary of State George P. Shultz's Middle East peace plan.
   Arafat, speaking mostly in English, said in the interview Sunday
that ouster of the PLO from the United Nations is against
international law. He also said it will teach every nation that
they ``may face the same treatment if they have a difference of
opinion between their country and the American administration.''
   The PLO leader, wearing a military-style uniform and a winter
hat, is in Algeria for a two-day meeting with President Chadli
Bendjedid, the newspaper said.
   The interview came one day before Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir was arriving in Washington on a four-day visit. Shultz was
hoping Shamir would agree to attend an international conference to
arrange self-rule for Palestinian Arabs on the West Bank and Gaza
and then an overall settlement.
   However, Shamir was quoted last week as saying the U.S. proposal
was ``fraught with danger'' and incapable of bringing peace to the
region.
   ``The only word I agree with in the U.S. plan is the name
Shultz,'' Shamir said, according to an account Friday in the
Israeli daily newspaper Haaretz.
   Arafat said in the interview that Shamir was ``giving this hard
line because he wants a high price from the American
administration'' (and) ``the first item on the list has been
offered already,'' referring to the closing of the PLO mission.
   Arafat predicted that Israel next will demand more weapons, more
financial help and ``who knows, more agreements'' before conceding
to talk about peace.
   Arafat said he and Bendjedid were discussing the Algerian
leader's call for a summit meeting of Arab nations on the Middle
East peace issue. Arafat said he expects the conference to be held
the first week in April.
   Asked about Palestinian resistance to Israel's occupation of the
West Bank and the Gaza Strip, Arafat said, ``This is one of the
most important positive signals in the Palestinian revolution.
Grandfather, father, grandson _ all of them are in a revolution,
and we are proud of them.''
</TEXT>
