<DOCNO> AP880314-0048 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-88 0527EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DarrowRemembered     03-14 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Darrow Remembered,0478</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Clarence Darrow Admirers Commemorate 50th Anniversay Of His Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH SHOGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Admirers of Clarence Darrow marked the 50th
anniversary of the death of ``the attorney of the damned'' by
tossing a wreath into the lagoon where his ashes are scattered and
pledging to live by his example.
   About 100 people huddled together against the snow Sunday on a
bridge in a park on Chicago's South Side.
   Darrow, a skeptic on matters of religion and the afterlife, said
if there was anything to the spiritual world, he would return at 10
in the morning on each anniversary of his death, according to Leon
Despres, a former alderman of the 5th Ward, where Darrow lived.
   For years after Darrow's death, magicians and spiritualists
gathered at the bridge to conjure up the lawyer's spirit _ but year
after year they went away disappointed.
   Those gathered at the bridge departed with a renewed sense of
commitment to the ideals Darrow stood for: justice and equality.
   ``For those of you who question life after death ... Clarence is
here in spirit today as we commit ourselves to follow the example
of his life,'' said U.S. District Judge Prentice Marshall.
   About a dozen attorneys, politicians, judges and ministers
addressed the crowd in Jackson Park, a few blocks from Darrow's
home.
   In his 50 years as a lawyer, Darrow defended ``the preconvicted,
the powerless, those damned before they had a chance to have a fair
trial,'' said Herb Kraus, a co-chairman of the Clarence Darrow
Commemorative Committee.
   One of Darrow's most famous clients was Tennessee teacher John
T. Scopes, whom he aided in 1925 in what became known as the
``Monkey Trial.'' Darrow, representing the American Civil Liberties
Union, defended the right for evolution to be taught in Tennessee
schools. Though Scopes was found guilty, his conviction was later
reversed on a technicality.
   Darrow also gained fame during the 1924 Chicago murder case of
Nathan Leopold and Richard Loeb, millionaires' sons accused of the
thrill killing of 14-year-old Bobby Franks. Darrow persuaded them
to plead guilty and saved them from death sentences.
   Darrow, who was born in Kinsman, Ohio, but spent most of his
legal career in Chicago, was one of the first to be called a labor
lawyer.
   He resigned as the attorney for the Chicago and Northwestern
Railroad to represent labor's side of an 1893 railroad strike led
by Eugene Debs.
   For the past 31 years, the commemorative committee has marked
Darrow's death on March 13, 1938, by throwing a wreath into the
lagoon under the Darrow Bridge.
   ``Darrow was and is a folk hero,'' said Arthur Weinberg, who
recently published a biography on the lawyer. ``He was always a
defender of the damned and a defender of the unpopular.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
