<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PoliticalBriefs     03-14 0561</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Briefs,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Disagreement Splits Jackson Campaign Effort In Northern Indiana</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GARY, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A disagreement among supporters of Jesse
Jackson has split the Democrat's presidential campaign effort in
northern Indiana.
   Jackson now has two campaign headquarters, both located in the
same block of the same downtown street in Gary. And although the
campaign workers in each office are working toward the same goal _
the election of Jackson in the May 3 primary _ they are functioning
under different local campaign directors.
   The dispute boiled over late last week when Jackson's state
coordinator, the Rev. Thomas Robinson of Anderson, appointed the
Rev. F. Brannan Jackson of Gary as campaign coordinator for
northern Indiana.
   Robinson said he made the appointment because the man named by
Jackson's national campaign office to head the northern Indiana
effort, Carlos Tolliver of Gary, had refused to communicate with
Robinson and could not reach out to other elected officials and
voters.
   ``I did not appoint him and I am not going to unappoint him. But
I'm appointing someone to get some things done,'' Robinson said,
adding that Tolliver no longer spoke for the local campaign.
   However, Tolliver insists that Robinson has acted beyond his
authority, and claims that he is the only authorized Jackson
representative in Gary.
   Top officials of the Jackson campaign's national and state
offices confirm that Tolliver is the authorized head of the
campaign in the 1st Congressional District.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Reagan Labels `Pork' One Of Dukakis' Favorite Home Projects</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan has labeled federal funding
for a planned biotechnology research park in central Massachusetts
that Gov. Michael S. Dukakis often points to while campaigning for
president a prime example of waste.
   Reagan listed the $100,000 for the Worcester, Mass., project
among $1.15 billion in ``pork'' he would have cut out if allowed to
single-out projects from last year's massive congressional spending
package.
   But Dukakis aides defended the center, which is part of the
governor's ``Centers of Excellence'' program designed to develop
technologies of the future like photovoltaics, polymers and
biotechnology.
   ``The Centers of Excellence program is another example of an
innovative experiment hatched at the state level,'' said Dukakis
campaign spokesman Steve Akey. ``For too long Washington has turned
its back on these innovative approaches.''
   In his campaign speeches Dukakis has praised the state-supported
centers as places where ``the best minds of industry, government
and academia are coming together to chart the frontiers of science
and technology and spawn new industries and new opportunities for
good jobs and economic growth.''
</TEXT>
