<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-88 0559EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-SouthAfrica-Office     03-14 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa-Office,280</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department has quietly disbanded the
group it set up more than two years ago to sell the Reagan
administration's widely criticized policy towards South Africa.
   William ``Jake`` Jacobsen, the most recent director of the
Working Group on South And Southern Africa, said the office
effectively closed at the end of 1987.
   The decision not to continue the office resulted in part because
South Africa has waned as an issue attracting daily headlines in
the United States, Jacobsen said.
   ``By 1987 there were other issues,'' he said. ``There was the
(Persian) Gulf, the Middle East in general, the controversy
involving Iran,'' he said.
   The office, which at one point had a staff of about 20, was
created in late 1985 as the administration pursued its policy of
``constructive engagement,'' _ attempting to pressure the white
government in Pretoria into eliminating racial segregation through
diplomacy rather than sanctions.
   But Congress _ against the administration's will _ approved
sanctions in 1986, thereby undercutting ``constructive engagement.''
   House members are preparing to consider a measure later this
month that would impose a full economic embargo on South Africa.
   Jacobsen said the working group did a good job explaining the
department's South Africa policy. ``We got out the message ...
People were much better informed in 1987 than in 1985.''
   When the group was set up, it was never intended to be a
permanent fixture, he said.
   He said the working group's staff traveled to over 45 states and
gave more than 1,000 speeches to civic and business groups and met
with reporters and editors from television stations and newspapers.
   The group was modeled after the department's Office of Public
Diplomacy for Latin American and the Caribbean. That operation was
also shut down.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
