<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--Patrick'sParade     03-14 0140</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Patrick's Parade,0143</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scottish Tune Opens St. Patrick's Day Parade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Irish eyes were smiling a bit more than
usual as the city's marching Hibernians celebrated St. Patrick's
Day with a inside-joke.
   Dressed in kilts and playing bagpipes, the Irish Pipers started
off the annual parade Sunday with a lively tune: ``Scotland the
Brave.''
   ``We do it to fool the guys who think we're Scottish,'' said
piper John Flynn, who marched in a green jacket and gold kilt at
the front of the parade.
   Some spectators asked why bagpipes appeared at the Irish
celebration. Piper, Patrick O'Shea, explained the Irish war pipes
are an old tradition.
   Unlike the Scots, the Irish were kept from playing the pipes
before most of Ireland was freed from British rule, said O'Shea,
who has played the pipes for 45 years.
</TEXT>
