<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     03-14 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0585</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Below-Normal Temperatures In Most Of Nation As Winter Lingers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Winter lingered with below-normal temperatures covering most of
the nation early today, and snow was predicted in many sections
even though spring's only a week away.
   At 1 a.m. EST, freezing temperatures were reported as far south
as San Angelo, Texas, and in Fort Smith, Ark., and Crossville,
Tenn. Late-night temperatures were mostly in the single digits and
teens from Wyoming and Colorado across the northern and central
Plains to the upper Great Lakes region.
   Snow showers, mostly light, extended Sunday night from the upper
and middle Mississippi Valley across the Great Lakes region and
northern sections of the Ohio Valley to the northern and central
Appalachians. Heavier snow was falling along the shores of Lake
Superior and Lake Erie.
   A heavy snow warning was posted through today in northeast Ohio.
Three to 4 inches fell Sunday evening at Thompson, Ohio. An
advisory for 1 to 3 inches of snow was in effect this morning over
northwest Pennsylvania.
   Four inches of new snow fell Sunday night near Marquette, Mich.
   Heavy snow was forecast today over the northern Rockies. Winter
storm watches were posted for this afternoon and tonight over
western and central Montana and northwest Wyoming. Up to a foot of
snow was possible by Tuesday morning in the mountains of Montana
and Wyoming.
   Rain showers fell in southern Florida, where a downpour dumped
more than an inch of rain on West Palm Beach in an hour early today.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 4 below
zero at Bismarck, N.D., to 76 at Key West Naval Air Station and
Fort Myers Regional Airport, Fla.
   The nation's high Sunday was 87 degrees at Fort Lauderdale,
North Miami Beach and West Palm Beach, Fla.
   For today, snow showers were forecast from the Great Lakes
region and the Ohio Valley across the northern and central
Appalachians; rain or snow showers over southern New England; and
snowshowers across Montana. Sunny skies were expected over the
nation's southern third, but with scattered showers and
thunderstorms in south Florida.
   Much of the nation was expected to have highs in the 30s-50s.
Below-normal temperatures were forecast from the Rockies to the
Atlantic, with highs only in the upper teens and 20s from the
Dakotas across the upper half of the Mississippi Valley, the Great
Lakes region and the Ohio Valley. Highs should reach the 60s and
70s over western Oregon, California, southwest Nevada, southern
Arizona, southern Texas and the Florida peninsula, with readings
near 80 over parts of the desert Southwest and south Florida.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 38 fair; Boston 35 snow; Buffalo 26 snow;
Charleston, S.C. 48 fair; Cincinnati 24 snow; Cleveland 25 partly
cloudy; Detroit 24 cloudy; Miami 75 partly cloudy; New York 40
windy; Philadelphia 35 fair; Pittsburgh 25 snow; Portland, Maine 30
snow; Washington 35 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 6 fair; Chicago 20 cloudy; Dallas-Fort Worth
29 fair; Denver 18 fair; Des Moines 14 fair; Indianapolis 20 snow;
Kansas City 16 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 13 partly cloudy;
Nashville 31 cloudy; New Orleans 49 fair; St. Louis 25 windy.
   _West: Albuquerque 29 fair; Anchorage 34 partly cloudy; Las
Vegas 43 fair; Los Angeles 55 fair; Phoenix 53 fair; Salt Lake City
26 fair; San Diego 54 fair; San Francisco 48 fair; Seattle 39 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 25 cloudy; Toronto 25 snow.
</TEXT>
