<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--China-Execution     03-14 0167</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--China-Execution,0170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Who Embezzled $350,000 Executed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who embezzled $350,000 from a fertilizer
factory in eastern China was executed, an official daily said today.
   The overseas edition of the People's Daily said Jiang Zhengguo,
chief of the finance section of the Wujin Chemical Fertilizer
Factory in Changzhou City, was executed Sunday after an court
rejected his appeal.
   The report said Jiang embezzled the money from March 1983 to
April 1987 by listing false construction expenditures and forging
receipts. He was sentenced to death by a lower court last November.
   The Chinese government in January announced tough new rules for
punishing economic crimes of corruption and bribery. The rules
stated that those who gain more than $13,500 through corruption
should be given prison terms of not less than 10 years, and serious
offenders should be sentenced to death.
   There have been at least four reported cases this year of
embezzlers being executed, usually by a bullet to the back of the
head.
</TEXT>
