<DOCNO> AP880314-0059 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-88 0659EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-US-SouthAfrica     03-14 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-South Africa,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crocker, Botha Meet in Geneva on Southern Africa Settlement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA WATSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   High-level talks began today between the United
States and South Africa on a plan to end fighting in Angola and
Namibia, officials said.
   The talks between U.S. Assistant Secretary of State Chester
Crocker and South African Foreign Minister Roelof ``Pik'' Botha are
open-ended and no details will be released until they end, said
Mari Botha, Botha's press secretary. It is the first meeting
between the leaders in two years.
   State Department spokeswoman Anita Stockman said Saturday in
Washington that the Crocker-Botha meeting will provide an
opportunity ``to reassess South Africa's willingness to proceed
toward a settlement involving total Cuban troop withdrawal from
Angola and Namibian independence.''
   Ms. Stockman also said the meeting would give the United States
a chance to ``register concern'' about recent developments in South
Africa.
   The United States has complained about anti-dissent measures in
South Africa in the past few weeks.
   She said a State Department working group arrived in Angola on
Wednesday to explore the possibility of further talks on getting
the estimated 40,000 Cuban troops out of the country as part of an
overall settlement.
   On Sunday, Angola's foreign ministry said Angola and Cuba
presented proposals to the U.S. officials for a southern Africa
peace accord including a timetable for the withdrawal of Cuban
troops from southern Angola, and an eventual full pullout.
   Since he took office in 1981, Crocker has tried to negotiate a
withdrawal of Cuban troops from Angola in return for South African
withdrawal from neighboring South-West Africa, also known as
Namibia.
   The Cuban troops have been battling a powerful guerrilla force,
the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola, or UNITA.
The guerrillas are supported by South Africa and the United States.
   On Sunday, UNITA leader Jonas Savimbi said South Africa has told
him it will begin direct talks with the Angolan government in a bid
to end Angola's 13-year-old civil war. He gave no indication when
such talks would begin.
</TEXT>
