<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Austria-Avalanches     03-14 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Austria-Avalanches,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Of Skiers Trapped By Avalanches</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INNSBRUCK, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of skiers remained
trapped in three Alpine ski resorts today after avalanches killed
10 people and injured at least 20 over the weekend.
   It was the worst winter-sport death toll for a single weekend in
Austria in decades.
   Roads to the famed resorts of Lech, Zuers and Stuben were snowed
in for a third straight day, and high winds prevented helicopters
from reaching the three high-altitude towns.
   Among those stranded in Lech were the former Dutch queen,
Princess Juliana, and her husband Prince Bernhard.
   ``They were supposed to leave on Saturday, but have been stuck
here since then,'' said a receptionist reached by telephone at the
Hotel Post, where the Dutch royalty were staying.
   ``But they are enjoying the winter sports and taking it all with
good humor like everyone else here,'' she said, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   Officials said thousands of the skiers, most of them vacationing
West Germans and Scandanavians, could remain stranded until Tuesday
because of the heavy snows and continued danger of avalanches.
   ``It is possible roads will be opened this afternoon, but it is
too early to tell,'' Eric Brumer, a local official, told Austrian
radio.
   ``But it is too early to tell whether the danger (of avalanches)
will drop enough,'' he added.
   The road to St. Anton was reopened today after seven people were
killed and at least 20 injured in the resort town on Sunday.
   Five vacationing Swedish skiers and two Austrians were killed in
St. Anton early Sunday when two successive avalanches rolled down
the steep mountains that tower above the resort and buried several
chalets, authorities said.
   Three others were killed in separate avalanches on Saturday,
bringing Austria's weekend winter-sport death toll to 10.
   The accidents followed the death last weekend of a close friend
of Britain's Prince Charles, who was killed in the Swiss resort of
Klosters by a snowslide that narrowly missed Charles.
   The avalanches destroyed four houses, damaged several other
buildings and buried the only train tracks leading into the
mountainous resort.
   Innsbruck police said authorities would not release the names of
victims until their next of kin had been notified.
   The exact number of those injured in the incident was not clear,
but several people were taken by helicopter to hospitals in
Innsbruck and nearby Zams, according to a police official, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Police said the single road that connects St. Anton to the
outside world remained closed, but that the train traffic to the
resort had been resumed.
   St. Anton, set at 4,118 feet in the Arlberg region of Western
Austria, is one of this Alpine nation's oldest and best-known ski
resorts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
