<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Lebanon-Violence     03-14 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Violence,0410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Killed, 8 Wounded In Shootings, Bombings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scattered shootouts and a bombing left
four people dead and eight wounded in Beirut, police said today.
   Police identified the slain as two officers from the Lebanese
Forces, the Christians' main militia, an officer of Druse warlord
Walid Jumblatt's Progressive Socialist Party militia and a
Palestinian guerrilla.
   In the latest violence, a Shiite Moslem attorney was critically
wounded today when a time bomb exploded on a window ledge outside
the bathroom of his west Beirut apartment as he was shaving, police
said.
   Nimeh Hamieh, a former chairman of Lebanon's Bar Association,
was rushed to the Barbir Hospital by neighbors, police said. They
declined to speculate on the motive for the assassination attempt.
   The two Lebanese Forces officers were killed Sunday by
bodyguards of President Amin Gemayel's 18-year-old son, Pierre, in
a quarrel in a traffic-jammed street in the Christian port of
Jounieh, 12 miles north of Beirut, police said.
   Police said the shooting sharpened tension between the Lebanese
Forces and Gemayel's rightist Phalange Party militia, which
controls the Metn province in the Christian heartland northeast of
Beirut.
   The two sides have been vying for dominance of the Christian
community, whose control of the government, army and Parliament
triggered the civil war with Lebanon's Moslem majority that began
in 1975.
   The Druse militia officer was killed Sunday evening in an ambush
by militiamen of Justice Minister Nabih Berri's Shiite Amal
movement in the Rashaya district in the foothills of Mount Hermon
in south Lebanon, police said. They said the Druse officer's
escorts fired at the ambushers, wounding two of them before Syrian
troops drove up to stop the shooting.
   Police said a Palestinian guerrilla from a Syrian-backed group
was killed and another wounded in a midnight shootout Sunday with
supporters of Palestine Liberation Organization Chairman Yasser
Arafat in the Bourj el-Barajneh refugee camp in south Beirut.
   Three Lebanese Army soldiers and a woman were shot and wounded
by a drunken gunman Sunday as they were lunching at a seaside
restaurant in the Christian town of Halat, 25 miles north of
Beirut, police said.
   The Syrians maintain 25,000 troops in north and east Lebanon
under a 1976 Arab League peacekeeping mandate.
   They also have a 7,500-strong force in Moslem west Beirut
seeking to restore law and order after years of militia anarchy.
</TEXT>
