<1ST_LINE>r i PM-UN-Afghanistan     03-14 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Afghanistan,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Talks Resume, Target Date One Day Away</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Afghanistan peace talks resumed today, one day
before a Soviet-set target date for a settlement. There were
unconfirmed reports Pakistan was about to decide whether to sign an
agreement with the Soviet-backed Kabul government.
   ``We will announce something today,'' Pakistan's chief
representative, acting Foreign Minister Zain Noorani, told
reporters as he arrived for a new meeting with U.N. mediator Diego
Cordovez. He did not elaborate.
   There was no confirmation of published reports quoting Prime
Minister Mohammad Khan Junejo of Pakistan as saying his country
will make a final decision today on whether to sign the proposed
settlement.
   The head of the Afghan delegation, Foreign Minister Abdul Wakil,
was scheduled to meet Cordovez today in keeping with the pattern of
the talks held indirectly because Pakistan does not recognize the
Kabul government.
   Pakistan has been speaking for the guerrillas, which are
excluded from the talks and do not formally recognize the
U.N.-sponsored peace process.
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev said last month that Moscow
would bring home its estimated 115,000 troops starting in mid-May
if a settlement was signed March 15 _ Tuesday.
   But sources close to the negotiations have said they do not
consider the date a rigid deadline.
   Soviet troops have been in Afghanistan, helping the government
fight Moslem insurgents, since December 1979.
   Noorani seemed to make plain today that he expected the talks to
continue for at least several more days. He said he wanted to ask
Cordovez what the program would be ``for the next few days to
finalize'' the peace package.
   ``They are a few points remaining'' before the settlement is
ready for signature, he added. Details have not been published.
   The latest round began March 2 and is already the longest since
the negotiations began nearly 6 years ago.
   Pakistan's negotiating position is jeopardized by a reported
rift in the alliance of seven guerrilla groups over plans to send
representatives to Geneva if a transitional government will replace
the existing one.
   Pakistan argues that only a broad-based government can oversee
implementation of the agreements and ensure the safe return of more
than 5 million Afghan refugees from Pakistan and Iran.
   The Soviet Union and Kabul have fiercely rejected that demand,
saying the future government was something to be decided by the
Afghans themselves and was not subject for discussion at Geneva.
</TEXT>
