<HEAD>Condition of Singer Dennis Day Remains Critical</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer Dennis Day remained
hospitalized in critical condition today after injuring his head in
a fall at his home last week, a hospital official said.
   No change was reported in Day's condition during the weekend and
he remained in critical and unstable condition today, said a
nursing supervisor at St. John's Hospital.
   Day, 71, fell at his Bel Air-area home Wednesday and complained
of a severe headache in the emergency room. He underwent surgery
after tests showed bleeding in the brain.
   Day was diagnosed last July as suffering from amyotropic lateral
sclerosis. The progressive nerve disorder, also known as Lou
Gehrig's disease, causes a loss of muscle control.
   Day, who was born Eugene Denis McNulty in New York City, began
his career with comedian Jack Benny in 1939. An accomplished Irish
tenor, Day also was known for playing the innocent foil to Benny's
irascible character on television and radio.
