<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Ireland-IRA     03-14 0449</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ireland-IRA,0463</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bodies Of IRA Guerrillas Headed For Belfast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bodies of three Irish Republican Army
members killed by British troops in Gibraltar were headed to
Northern Ireland today for funeral services and a possible St.
Patrick's Day burial.
   Families members and a Roman Catholic bishop called for calm at
the funerals of the IRA members, who British authorities linked to
a planned car bombing.
   Police on both sides of the border were expected to mount a huge
security operation to prevent paramilitary displays beside the
coffins during today's 100-mile journey by road to Belfast, and at
the funerals later this week.
   Sinn Fein, the legal political wing of the IRA, said a chartered
plane carrying the bodies of Mairead Farrell, 31, Daniel McCann,
30, and Sean Savage, 24, was to fly today from Gibraltar, the
British fortress colony in southern Spain, to Dublin.
   The cortege was to travel directly from Dublin Airport to
British-ruled Northern Ireland, police said.
   Sinn Fein said the IRA members will be buried in Belfast's
Milltown Cemetery on Wednesday or on Saint Patrick's Day on
Thursday, when the funeral processions likely would be swollen by
hundreds of sympathizers.
   St. Patrick's Day, honoring Ireland's patron saint, is
celebrated by Catholics across the island.
   Cahal Daly, a Roman Catholic whose diocese includes Belfast,
said Sunday he hoped both police and mourners will display ``a
desire to avoid confrontation.''
   In a statement, the families of the three dead men appealed to
the security forces ``to permit us the dignity to bury our loved
ones in peace.''
   The three guerrillas were unarmed when they were shot and killed
March 6 by soldiers believed to be members of the Special Air
Services, an elite British regiment.
   The shootings triggered rioting in Catholic districts of Belfast
for much of last week, and provoked protests that the three should
instead have been arrested. The British government said the
soldiers believed their lives were endangered.
   Two days after the shootings, Spanish police discovered a car
packed with 145 pounds of Czech-made explosives in Marbella, 30
miles from Gibraltar. Britain said the guerrillas intended to blow
up the car during a military ceremony in the colony.
   The IRA, outlawed in Britain and Ireland, is fighting to drive
the British out of Northern Ireland and unite the
Protestant-dominated province with the Catholic Irish Republic.
   Since the political and sectarian violence erupted in Northern
Ireland in 1969, at least 2,628 people have been killed.
   IRA funerals have in recent years brought bloody clashes between
nationalists and massed ranks of police seeking to prevent gunmen
firing shots over the coffins, the IRA's traditional salute to its
dead. The practice is banned.
</TEXT>
