<2ND_LINE>PM-Urban Parachutist, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0488,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Urban Parachutist Identified As A Canadian Truck Driver</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf to restore dropped word `not'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who parachuted from a 50-story downtown
building is a member of a group that requires such jumps, police
said.
   The parachutist dropped onto a car a week ago and fled before
police could collar him.
   But since then, he was traced through the license number of a
getaway car and identified as a Canadian, said police Sgt. Gerald
Rogers.
   The man, whose name Rogers would not release, belongs to a group
called Building, Antenna, Span and Earth club, or BASE. Members are
required to parachute from a building, antenna, a bridge and a
cliff or mountain.
   ``They don't live long,'' said Rogers. ``It seems utterly crazy
that someone needs that much excitement in their life.''
   He said it was much safer to parachute from an airplane than
from a fixed object.
   The officer said police traced the license number of the
jumper's getaway car to a South Side Chicago man, who admitted he
helped in the escape. Rogers also refused to identify the
accomplice.
   Rogers said he has not contacted the parachutist, who lives in
Quebec and is a truck driver. But his accomplice told police that
the Canadian wants to reimburse the owner of the BMW, Musiliu
Alagbala of Chicago, for the several hundred dollars worth of
damage to the car, Rogers said.
   Alagbala said Sunday he was amazed and angered by the incident.
   ``I've seen things like that in the movies, but I'd never
thought it would happen to me,'' he said.
   If the parachutist returns to Chicago, he may be charged with
criminal trespass for being on the roof of the Leo Burnett Building
without permission, Rogers said. The suspect also may be charged
with criminal damages for the dents in the car, he said.
   ``We are not going to extradict him. If he doesn't come forward,
ultimately we might put a warrant out on him,'' he said.
</TEXT>
