<HEAD>Anti-Drug Candidate Wins Bogota Mayoral Election</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with alleged drug dealer
failing to get on ballot. CORRECTS number of mayoral elections in
10th graf to 1,008, sted 10,008. PICKS up 12th graf, `Barco, in ..
.'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A young lawyer, who was once kidnapped
because he campaigned against drugs, has been elected mayor of
Bogota in the first mayoral elections in Colombia's history.
   Security at the polls Sunday was tight throughout this country
racked by violence from extremist political factions and from
powerful narcotics traffickers.
   One of the alleged leaders of Colombia's biggest drug
organization even tried to run for city council in the town of
Armenia.
   But Carlos Lehder Rivas failed because Colombian law demands
that candidates sign up in person. Lehder is in jail in
Jacksonville, Fla., facing drug charges there and in Miami.
   Andres Pastrana, 34, the son of former President Misael
Pastrana, became Bogota's mayor and will be one of the youngest men
to take that important political post. Several Bogota mayors have
gone on to become president.
   Pastrana is a rising star in the Conservative Party, and his
election represents a setback for President Virgilio Barco's
governing Liberal Party.
   Pastrana was the only Conservative Party candidate for mayor in
Bogota. The feuding Liberal Party put up three candidates.
   Voters heeded Barco's plea to fight bullets with ballots in the
election, which was called as a concession to leftist guerrillas.
   For the past 169 years, the president, always from either the
Liberal or Conservative parties, had appointed governors who in
turn named mayors.
   There were 1,008 mayors elected Sunday. Colombians also elected
city council, state assemblies and governing bodies for remote
territories without sufficient population to become states.
   In the Bogota race, Juan Caicedo, a former president of the
Colombian Association of Businessmen, came in second place. With
about 50 percent of the vote in Bogota counted, Pastrana had
122,107 votes and Caicedo had 94,322, the National Elections Office
said in a news release Sunday night.
   By late Sunday night the elections office said the Liberal Party
had won 405 of the mayoral races, the Conservative Party 379 and
the leftist Patriotic Union 13. Coalition candidates representing
several parties had won 104 mayoral posts, the elctions office said.
   Barco, in a speech televised nationwide Saturday night, said
voting would be a way to reject the wave of violence that has swept
Colombia.
   More than 1,700 people were killed in the past year in fighting
between leftist guerrillas and government security forces and by
right-wing death squads and drug traffickers.
   On Sunday, soldiers and police guarded voting places and
patrolled cities and towns. The campaign was one of the bloodiest
ever in Colombia, with leftist guerrillas and right-wing death
squads killing five mayoral candidates and 19 city council
candidates. Hundreds of other political activists were slain.
   Leftist guerrillas kidnapped 14 mayors in the two weeks before
the election. The rebels let them go after warning each to do more
for the poor.
   Pastrana, who called for stronger action against the
multibillion-dollar cocaine and marijuana trafficking in Colombia,
was kidnapped by drug traffickers in January. A week later, police
acting on a tip, raided a farmhouse where he was held. Pastrana had
not been harmed.
   Colombian officials sometimes pay with their lives for
challenging drug traffickers, who are among the wealthiest men in
the nation.
   One group, the Medillin Cartel, is said to be responsible for 80
percent of the cocaine smuggled into the United States. Lehder is
charged in Miami with being one of its leaders.
   In 1984, Justice Minister Rodrigo Lara Bonilla was killed, and
in January Attorney General Carlos Mauro Hoyos was gunned down.
Officials suspect drug traffickers in the deaths because both men
fought narcotics.
</TEXT>
