<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DardenExecution 1stLd-Writethru a0461 03-14 0741</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Darden Execution, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0461,0759</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Executions Tuesday, Including Darden</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS two grafs after 3rd pvs and ADDS six grafs at end
with 2nd execution skedded in Louisiana; SUBS 6th graf pvs,
``Darden said xxx, to clarify, note that execution skedded on 7
days notice; Note language in 12th graf ``Authorities say...'' Lead
prospects uncertain.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>STARKE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Convicted killer Willie Jasper Darden again
faces execution this week after outlasting six death warrants and
becoming a symbol of the national conflict over capital punishment.
   His appeal was pending today at the Florida Supreme Court in
Tallahassee in advance of a scheduled Tuesday morning execution at
the state prison here.
   Gov. Bob Martinez, the only official outside the courts who
could intervene, said last week he saw no reason to back off the
death warrant he signed Tuesday.
   Meanwhile, in Angola, La., Wayne Robert Felde was scheduled to
die shortly after midnight for the murder of a Shreveport police
officer 10 years ago.
   Felde had claimed he was suffering from post-war stress syndrome
as a result of his experiences in Vietnam and asked for the death
penalty at his trial, implying he would kill again. His lawyer,
Millard Farmer, refused to say if an appeal was being pursued.
   Darden maintained his innocence in an interview published Sunday.
   ``If I'm executed Tuesday, it won't change the facts one bit,''
he told The New York Times. ``All that will happen is that I will
be an innocent dead person instead of an innocent live person.''
   Darden said he's convinced his latest execution was scheduled
with only seven days' notice ``to keep me from getting too much
public attention.
   ``Since January, I have received close to 2,000 letters from
around the world,'' he said in the interview.
   Soviet dissident Andrei Sakharov and the London-based human
rights organization Amnesty International are among those who have
spoken out in support of Darden.
   Backers have said he has been on death row for 14 years because
of a racist legal system that denied him a fair trial.
   But police in three Florida counties consider him a suspect in
at least five killings in addition to the 1973 death of James
Turman, for which Darden received the death sentence. Those cases
remain unsolved and Darden has never been charged in them.
   According to a report Sunday in The Tampa Tribune, police in
Hillsborough, Pinellas and Polk counties say Darden began his spree
by beating a woman to death with his hands.
   Authorities say he then strangled a woman with her stocking,
battered a woman to death with a tire iron and finally shoot his
victims in the face with a short-barreled .38-caliber revolver
after they had been forced to perform oral sex on him.
   All the slayings police suspect Darden of occurred in 1973 while
he was on furlough from Avon Park Correctional Institution, where
he was serving a six month to 20 year sentence for breaking into
the home of a 70-year-old St. Petersburg woman in 1968, beating her
and attempting to rape her.
   The 54-year-old Darden has outlasted more death warrants than
any other Florida inmate, and has been on Florida's death row, the
nation's largest, longer than all but one inmate.
   The dispute over his case centers on whether Darden has an alibi
as a result of statements from a minister and a woman placing him
away from the scene of the Turman killing. Law enforcement
authorities say evidence shows the killing occurred an hour too
late for Darden to have an alibi.
   In Louisiana, Felde was scheduled to die shortly after midnight
CST.
   In 1978, after being picked up on a drunkeness charge, Felde
pulled a gun as he sat in the back seat of a police car and fired
it into the back of the driver, police officer Glen Tompkins.
   As part of his defense, he claimed he was suffering from post
war stress and exposure to Agent Orange. In his appeals he also
claimed he had inadequate defense counsel during his trial.
   Gov.-elect Buddy Roemer, who was to take office this afternoon,
said he had no plans to stop the execution.
   Hilton Butler, warden of the state penitentiary at Angola, said
Felde's sisters visited with him Sunday and would be back at the
death house today where the execution will take place.
   Butler said that Felde has asked for pizza, fried shrimp and
ginger ale for his final meal.
</TEXT>
