<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Lebanon-US     03-14 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-US,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shiite Moslems Threaten Terrorist Attacks Against U.S.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pro-Iranian militants marking the third
anniversary of a car bombing that killed more than 80 Shiite
Moslems have threatened to launch new terrorist attacks against the
United States.
   ``We should not forget that America is behind all the massacres
and crimes,'' said Sheik Hassan Nasrallah, a senior official of
Hezbollah, or Party of God, at a mass rally in south Beirut's Bir
el-Abed district on Sunday. Excerpts of his speech were published
by Beirut newspapers today.
   ``We have war and we have terrorism to use against America to
defend the interests of the Moslems and the oppressed,'' Nasrallah
said. ``We are always ready to teach the wild beasts in the world a
lesson.''
   The Iranian-backed Hezbollah has accused the CIA of
masterminding the March 8, 1985, car bombing in Bir el-Abed with
the help of the army's intelligence branch. It charged that the
bombing was aimed at assassinating Hezbollah's spiritual guide,
Sheik Mohammed Hussein Fadlallah.
   Hezbollah is believed to be the umbrella for underground
extremists holding many of the 22 foreign hostages in Lebanon,
including nine Americans. The longest held hostage is Terry A.
Anderson, 38, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated
Press, who was kidnapped on March 16, 1985.
   Fadlallah also spoke at Sunday's rally, charging the device that
went off near his residence was ``made in America.''
   He declared: ``America, which accuses us of terrorism, is the
master of terrorism throughout the universe.''
   He vowed that guerrilla warfare against Israel will be escalated.
   ``We consider our movement a supplement to the Palestinian
uprising in the occupied territories,'' Fadlallah said, referring
to three months of rioting by Palestinians in the Israeli-occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Hezbollah leads the Islamic Resistence Front, which has claimed
responsibility for numerous attacks against Israeli troops and
their militia allies in Israel's self-designated security zone in
south Lebanon.
</TEXT>
