<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AIDS-Towing     03-14 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS-Towing,0229</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robbery Suspect Towed After Saying He Had AIDS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A robbery suspect who claimed he had AIDS and
threatened to bite the first police officer that came near him was
put into a patrol car alone and towed to a police station, a
department spokesman said today.
   Richard Simmons was taken out of the patrol car by Emergency
Medical Service personel wearing protective gear, said Sgt. Maurice
Howard.
   Simmons, 27, was taken to Roosevelt Hospital for psychiatric
evaluation and was classified as emotionally disturbed, he said.
   The incident started Sunday morning when Simmons, dressed in a
wig, makeup, a shirt and jeans, tried to rob a passer-by, the
spokesman said.
   Simmons took a small amount of money from the pocket of
19-year-old David Murphy, Howard said. Murphy fought back and two
police officers intervened, handcuffing Simmons and putting him in
the back of a patrol car.
   After he was in the car, Simmons began ``cursing and kicking,''
Howard said.
   ``He said he had AIDS, that he was going to die and that he
would take them all with him,'' Howard said. ``Then he threatened
to bite the first officer who came near him.''
   Police locked Simmons inside the car and summoned a tow truck,
Howard said.
   Simmons was charged with one count of attempted robbery.
</TEXT>
