<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-RobinHood     03-14 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Robin Hood,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tourist Brochure That Punctured Robin Hood Legend Is Withdrawn</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NOTTINGHAM, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robin Hood fans have put an end to a
tourism brochure that says their hero and Maid Marian never met,
good-natured Little John was a grouch, and Robin may have stolen
from the rich just to line to his own pockets.
   ``I would like to see the authors of this brochure locked in the
dungeons of Nottingham Castle,'' said the sheriff of Nottingham,
Royce Young, on Sunday. Legend says Robin Hood, the medieval bandit
who supposedly stole from the rich to give to the poor, repeatedly
outwitted Young's ancient predecessor.
   Howls of protest from Robin Hood fans and deflated tourism
boosters led city officials to withdraw the glossy 45-cent
brochure. It had been compliled by historians and published by the
city council for distribution at a tourist information center.
   Malcolm Barker of the Robin Hood Society, who took up the
cudgels on the outlaw's behalf, charged: ``The city fathers have
done a disservice to their own city.''
   Barker said he didn't claim that the story, as perpetuated by
Hollywood, was true. He said he simply objected to being robbed of
a legend that also brings tourist riches to Nottingham.
   The brochure took a skeptical academic line on the outlaw who,
according to legend, lived in Sherwood Forest with his merry band
of men in the 12th century. City council spokesman Tim Jones said
the brochure put Robin Hood ``in historical context.''
   The brochure said Robin Hood, in the earliest tales, was a
highwayman who robbed travelers in neighboring Yorkshire. He was in
business strictly for himself.
   The brochure also says Robin's true love, Maid Marian, was
introduced into the legend through a 13th-century French poem, and
Robin's rotund lieutenant, Friar Tuck, was probably an amalgam of
two characters from different parts of England.
   Nottingham, a city of 290,000 in northern England, can hardly be
accused of neglecting the legend. Its main beltway is called Maid
Marian Way, and two rival consortiums are planning Robin Hood
exhibition centers for the city.
   In addition, hordes of tourists annually visit the Sherwood
Forest Center, where they see displays of medieval lifestyles and
gaze at the oak tree where the merry men may or may not have
relaxed after a hard day's archery.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
