<1ST_LINE>r a PM-JewishRally     03-14 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jewish Rally,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Demonstrators Clash Over Controversial Peace Plan in Middle East</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Israel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Speakers were heckled with shouts
of ``Nazi'' and ``traitor'' and shoving matches broke out as rival
factions of American Jews clashed during a rally to support a peace
plan for Israel's occupied territories.
   Actor Richard Dreyfuss was escorted from Sunday's Roxbury Park
rally by police after hecklers shouted him down as he tried to
speak in favor of a peaceful solution to clashes between Israelis
and Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Other speakers included feminist Betty Friedan, Yael Dayan,
daughter of the late Israeli Gen. Moshe Dayan, and several rabbis.
   Despite a number of scuffles, police said there were no injuries
or arrests.
   ``I was raised in the temple and the Jewish community to see the
difference between right and wrong,'' Dreyfuss said as he tried to
address the crowd of about 400, which included many immigrants from
Israel.
   ``If he would spill some of his blood like me and my brothers,
then he would have a right to speak out like this,'' countered
Bobby Frankel, a veteran of the 1956 Sinai campaign. ``We're
against people who don't know what they're talking about.''
   The rally was organized on the eve of today's visit to the
United States by conservative Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir.
   Shamir has expressed opposition to an American plan for an
international conference to arrange self-rule for Palestianian
Arabs on the West Bank and Gaza, then an overall settlement. Israel
conquered the territories during the 1967 six-day war against
Jordan and Egypt.
   Sunday's confrontation began as 200 or so counter-demonstrators,
whose ranks included orthodox Jews and militant Jewish Defense
League leader Irv Rubin, circled the rally's original group, then
crowded around the stage.
   ``A good Jew is a Jew, in my opinion, who sticks to the state of
Israel through thick and thin,'' Rubin said. ``They (the peace
plan's supporters) are tearing the Jewish community apart. They're
using their celebrity status to beg and plead and cajole the prime
minister of Israel to accept this suicide plan.''
</TEXT>
