<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Migrant     03-14 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Migrant,0454</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Millions of Peasants Leave Farm to Make Money, Clog Rail System</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Millions of Chinese peasants have hit the road
in recent weeks to seek their fortunes, creating a transportation
crisis along the country's railways, an official report said.
   Armed police have been called out to maintain order at railway
stations heaving under the mass of travelers while some passenger
trains are carrying more than twice their capacity, China's
domestic China News Service said in an article appearing in Hong
Kong on Monday.
   ``Some are going to the northwest for construction, some are
going to the northeast's Daxinganling forest for lumbering, others
are going Gaungdong province (in the south) to farm and still
others are going to large cities as housekeepers,'' the news
service said.
   At the Beijing station, the report said, ``people can be found
everywhere sleeping in the open.'' In Zhengzhou, the capital of
central Henan province and a railroad hub, more than 10,000 people
were said to be waiting at the station for tickets.
   The news service recounted the woeful tale of one passenger who
stood for more than 30 hours on a train trip from Anhui province to
the far-north city of Harbin. At one point he lifted his swollen
foot only to find the tiny space immediately seized by a traveler
squeezed next to him.
   Nearly 4 million people ride the rails daily, the report said,
without saying how much of an increase that represents.
   Most of the travelers are peasants looking for work, the report
said. The exodus from rural homes began with the arrival of warmer
weather following last month's Lunar New Year holiday.
   Poor peasants always have sought their fortune in big cities,
but the situation has become a problem in recent years because of
recent economic reforms that ease travel restrictions and permit
labor markets.
   The railroad situation hits its most critical on the third,
sixth and ninth days of each month, which are considered propitious
days for travel, the news agency said.
   Although authorities are taking several steps to ease the
situation, such as increasing passenger trains, the transportation
crisis is expected to continue, the report said.
   In an earlier report, Sichuan Radio said March 2 that 100,000
travelers were trying to leave Chengdu, the capital of central
Sichuan province, every day for their hometowns, by rail.
   ``A few passengers, heedless of admonitions, have stormed their
way onto the trains by breaking the windows,'' the report said.
``At the same time, trains leaving Chengdu station for destinations
outside Sichuan are seriously overloaded to the extend that it is
impossible to open the doors or supply drinking water.''
</TEXT>
