<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BearKilled     03-14 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bear Killed,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polar Bear Killed After Man Enters Cage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A zoo polar bear injured a man with a
history of mental problems who entered its cage, and police shot
the bear to death, authorities say.
   The 28-year-old man, whose identity was not released, was
treated at a hospital for a gash on his head and was put under
emergency detention by police after the Sunday morning incident.
   Police said it was unclear why the man climbed into the bear's
cage, but that the man told doctors he did it to ``give his brother
strength,'' and that people ``need a show of courage.'' The
``brother'' reference was unexplained.
   Vilas Zoo director David Hall said the intruder had to scale a
wall or climb through a moat to reach the the 7-foot-4, 900-pound
bear, named Chief.
   ``I'd say it's a one in a million chance that you get out of a
polar bear's den alive when a polar bear is in it,'' Hall said.
   A jogger who heard shouts flagged down a motorist, who alerted
police.
   The jogger, Robert Nelson, 47, said the ``bear was standing
above the person, licking him, playing around with him. The man
wasn't screaming. He wasn't doing anything. I thought he was dead.''
   Police Officer Michael Puls fatally wounded the bear with a
12-gauge shotgun after yelling at it and firing shots in the air in
an attempt to scare it. Puls said he shot the animal after it began
to drag the man to its cave.
   Hall said Chief, the only polar bear at the municipal zoo, was
considered one of the largest in captivity. It had been with the
zoo for about 13{ years.
   ``He was a good show and everyone liked him,'' Hall said. ``But
you can't compare his to a human life. All of us in the zoo
profession know that a human life takes precedent.''
   Police said the Sunday incident was the third time this year
that emergency detention procedures had to be used to detain the
man. Those procedures are used when a person is considered a danger
to themselves or others.
</TEXT>
