<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Tomiko'sLetters     03-14 0197</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tomiko's Letters,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Columbus Girl's Anti-Drug Poster Wins Praise From First Lady And
Congressman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 12-year-old girl's anti-drug poster has
brought her praise from first lady Nancy Reagan and Rep. Richard
Ray, D-Ga.
   Tomiko Womack, a sixth-grader at Rigdon Road Elementary School,
got a letter from Mrs. Reagan on Feb. 29, praising her for
encouraging fellow students to ``just say no'' to drugs. She
received a similar letter from Ray on March 4.
   ``I was very surprised when I got the letters,'' Tomiko, a
straight `A' student, said. ``I feel greatly honored and will
treasure them forever.''
   The letters referred to a poster titled, ``How Drugs Affect Our
Nation,'' which Tomiko entered in the Muscogee County Social
Science Fair on March 4-5. Knowing that both Mrs. Reagan and Ray
were active in the fight against drugs, Tomiko wrote letters
inviting them to attend the fair.
   After she received Mrs. Reagan's letter, she added it to her
poster, which won first place in the sociology category.
   ``I came up with the subject because drug abuse is a nationwide
problem, especially for young people, and I want to do something
about it,'' Tomiko said.
</TEXT>
