<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Libya     03-14 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Libya,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Engineer Accused Of Espionage Leaves Libya</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British engineer sentenced to life imprisonment
for alleged espionage left Libya today for a reunion with his
family after his prison term was commuted, the Foreign Office said.
   James Abra, 59, was freed Sunday in Tripoli, the Libyan capital,
after serving almost two years. He was headed for Malta to meet
family members. It was not known when Abra would return to Britain.
   Abra was arrested at Tripoli airport on June 20, 1985, and
accused of passing classified information to his employer, a
British electronics company, Plessey Co. He was convicted of spying
in April 1986 and sentenced to life in prison.
   Abra's Czech-born wife Radislava, 58, died of a heart attack
last July after a fire at their home in Hitchin, 32 miles north of
London.
   JANA, the Libyan news agency, has said Col. Moammar Gadhafi has
declared an amnesty for jailed foreigners. The Foreign Office said
the Italian Embassy, which looks after Britain's interests in
Libya, had submitted Abra's name for consideration.
   Britain broke diplomatic relations with Libya in April 1984
after a London police woman was fatally shot during a Libyan
dissident demonstration. Britain said she was killed by a Libyan
shooting at demonstrators from inside the embassy.
</TEXT>
