<DOCNO> AP880314-0083 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-88 0942EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Sisneros     03-14 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Sisneros,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nation's Oldest National Park Ranger Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOUNTAINAIR, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federico Sisneros, the National Park
Service's oldest ranger who spent his life caring for the San
Gregorio de Abo Mission, has died at age 93.
   Sisneros died Saturday of heart failure.
   Sisneros' family owned the land on which the 17th-century
Spanish mission stands and donated the property to the state in the
late 1930s. It was a state monument for many years and became part
of Salinas National Monument in 1981.
   Sisneros was the mission's caretaker while Abo was a state
monument and was named a ranger when it became part of the national
park system.
   ``It'll always be Abo on paper, but to the ones who worked with
him, it'll always be `Fred's Place,''' said Salinas chief ranger
Glenn Fulfer. ``His father had told him to take care of the
mission. It was more or less a legacy given down to Fred to take
care of Abo.''
   Fulfer said Sisneros worked for many years ``for hardly any
wages at all.''
   ``Fred was the type of fellow that the love of the site
outweighed the importance of money,'' he said.
   Sisneros was born in 1894 in a house near the Indian ruins at
the Abo mission. He and his wife, Guadalupe, lived in a house a few
yards from the ruins.
   Sisneros was honored by the National Park Service in 1981 with
the Superior Service Award for making a significant contribution
during most of the 20th century.
   He received an Honor Award in 1986 from the National Trust for
Historic Preservation at the group's 40th annual meeting.
   His story drew national attention over the years. He was
interviewed by Charles Kuralt of CBS News and was featured in major
newspapers.
   Fulfer said Sisneros had asked to be buried at the mission. The
National Park Servce has authorized his grave to be located there.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
