<HEAD>Girl Born Same Day as Reagan Gets Presidential History Lesson</HEAD>
<HEAD>Retransmitting a0548 to fix category code</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALGARY, Alberta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 7-year-old Canadian girl who shares a
birthday with Ronald Reagan has learned from the U.S. president
that several other important people in history also were born in
February.
   ``It was wonderful to learn that you and I share a mutual
birthday,'' reads a typewritten letter signed by Reagan to Kaliopi
Triantafyllakis.
   ``February is also the month in which George Washington and
Abraham Lincoln were born. I hope you make it a part of your
birthday to learn more about these two great presidents who played
such important roles in shaping our nation,'' the letter said.
   The letter was in response to a birthday card the elementary
school student sent Reagan, who was 77 on Feb. 6.
   The White House response received Friday also included a glossy
photo of Reagan and wife Nancy, and a 32-page booklet about the
Reagan years in the White House.
   Kaliopi said she first heard a couple of years ago that she and
Reagan, who was born in 1911 in Tampico, Ill., shared the same
birthday.
   ``Actually, I think it was very nice of him to take the time to
write her a letter,'' said Kaliopi's mother, Kathy.
   ``Oh Mom,'' injected the youngster, ``he didn't write it, his
secretary did.''
</TEXT>
