<1ST_LINE>r p PM-BayhResidency     03-14 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bayh Residency,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Rules Bayh Eligible To Be Indiana Governor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG RICHARDSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SHELBYVILLE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Shelby County judge today ruled that
Secretary of State Evan Bayh meets the constitutional five-year
residency requirement to be governor.
   In a 10-page ruling, Shelby Circuit Judge Charles D. O'Connor
concluded the Democratic gubernatorial candidate didn't lose his
Indiana residency when he worked as an attorney in Washington,
D.C., in 1983 and 1984.
   Republicans had argued that Bayh, who leads public opinion polls
in the governor's race, lost his Indiana residency when he moved to
the District of Columbia to work for the law firm of Hogan and
Hartson.
   But O'Connor concluded that Bayh always intended to return to
his home state and never established formal residence elsewhere.
   ``Personal presence (away) from one's place of domicile is
insufficient to change one's domicile,'' O'Connor wrote. ``One must
move to another place with the intent to make it his home and
without the intention of returning to his home as such.''
   The judge's decision came after a one-day trial Friday on Bayh's
lawsuit seeking a declaratory judgment that he meets the
constitutional requirement to be governor.
   Bayh filed the suit in February after Republican Gov. Robert D.
Orr instructed the GOP-controlled State Election Board to
investigate Bayh's eligibility.
   The election board last week delayed its probe to allow the
court to rule. The election board and Orr already have called for
any lower court decision to be appealed to the state Supreme Court.
   O'Connor concluded that Bayh repeatedly expressed his intent to
return to his home state and considered his stint in Washington as
only a brief episode of professional development.
   O'Connor noted that Bayh, the son of former Sen. Birch E. Bayh,
voted regularly in Indiana and kept his ties to the state
Democratic organization.
   Bayh, 32, faces opposition from former Kokomo Mayor Stephen J.
Daily in the May 3 Democratic primary.
   Lt. Gov. John M. Mutz is unopposed for the Republican nomination
to succeed Orr, who is barred by the Constitution from seeking a
third straight term.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
