<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DrugDispute     03-14 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drug Dispute,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lab Halts Shipment of Polio Vaccine for AIDS Treatment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALLENTOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The only U.S. manufacturer of injectable
polio vaccine has stopped shipping the drug to California
physicians after learning it was being used as an experimental AIDS
treatment.
   Connaught Laboratories' Vice President David J. Williams said
the company would like to cooperate in such a treatment but is
prohibited by the U.S. Food and Drug Administration from supplying
physicians with the vaccine for anything other than its intended
use _ to prevent polio.
   ``Some doctors in California have been working with AIDS
patients, using our injectable polio product,'' Williams said. ``As
soon as it came to our attention, we were required to contact the
FDA to determine if they had all the approvals.''
   He said the physicians did not have the required approvals, so
Connaught halted the shipments.
   A spokeswoman for the FDA said an ``investigational new drug
application'' should be submitted to the FDA and studied to be sure
experiments are conducted properly and that dosages would not
adversely affect patients.
   ``The risks have to be weighed versus the benefits,'' she said.
   The old injectable Salk vaccine is no longer the preferred polio
vaccine in the United States, having been replaced by an oral
vaccine. It has shown promise for AIDS patients, relieving some
cancer lesions, herpes infections, swollen lymph nodes and fatigue,
a California researcher reported.
   The old, killed-virus vaccine can only be supplied by Connaught.
   Dr. Allen Allen, a California researcher and co-developer of the
experimental treatment, said physicians wonder what will happen now
to patients who have shown improvement after receiving the
injections for as long as two years.
   ``Patients with cancers are getting better and doctors can no
longer give them treatment. Most are close to running out,'' he
said Friday, adding that the physicians planned to meet to form a
plan of action.
   Allen said studies on more than 50 patients have shown the
vaccine ``produces clinical benefits after six weeks.''
   Allen said that it's up to Connaught, not the doctors, to submit
the necessary applications to the FDA, and alleged that the
Pennsylvania lab has financial reasons for not releasing its
vaccine.
   ``What they want to provide is a new vaccine which they have a
patent for, opposed to the old Salk vaccine which is in the publc
domain,'' he said.
   Williams said the company did receive a patent in November for
an improved injectable polio vaccine for global use, but he
insisted Connaught is not pushing one over the other for
experiments on AIDS patients.
   ``We started working on the new vaccine in 1979-80, probably
before AIDS was a household word,`` he said.
</TEXT>
