<2ND_LINE>PM-Gore, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0473,710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gore Says He's Alternative Illinois Wants</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 5 grafs with Gore comment today, picking up in
5th graf pvs, Gore's campaign</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr. portrayed himself today as a
needed alternative to the three Democratic candidates leading him
in polls one day before the Illinois Democratic primary.
   Gore greeted workers during a shift change at a factory in
Rockford, Ill., and said, ``I'm very encouraged'' about Tuesday's
primary, although he and his aides acknowledged on Sunday that he
was far behind.
   ``I think there are an awful lot of voters here in Illinois who
want an alternative to the kind of approach offered by Michael
Dukakis and Paul Simon and Jesse Jackson. I offer a different kind
of approach,'' Gore said today.
   Gore on Sunday had turned his focus to Republican George Bush
and said the vice president's response to the Iran-Contra affair
amounted to: ``Gee whiz, that's great, let's go ahead.''
   The Tennesseean resumed his Illinois campaign after a weekend
break, returning to a state where polls show him stuck in single
digits far behind favorite sons Simon and Jackson, and also
trailing rival Michael Dukakis.
   Gore's campaign bought what deputy campaign manager Larry
Harrington called ``a decent or modest amount'' of television
airtime in Illinois. It was thought to be in the range of $200,000
to $300,000 over the past week. But Harrington downplayed
expectations, saying Gore's only aim was to be ``in the fray'' in
Illinois.
   ``We never put any serious organizational effort into
Illinois,'' Harrington said. He cited Jackson's and Simon's
strength and the timing a week after last week's Super Tuesday
round of primaries that catapulted Gore to the top tier of
Democratic presidential contenders.
   Gore delivered a forceful attack on the vice president and the
Reagan administration for the Iran-Contra affair in a long
question-and-answer session with students at Northwestern
University law school.
   He pointed to the guilty plea by former White House National
Security Adviser Robert C. McFarlane to misdemeanor charges
relating to Iran-Contra as confirming ``the Reagan-Bush
administration violated the law in a brazen way.''
   ``We still don't know what George Bush's role was,'' Gore said.
   Gore said the administration's sale of arms to Iran in a bid to
free hostages would have been ``hooted'' down as ``nuts'' if
Congress was consulted. ``We didn't have that opportunity, but
George Bush had that opportunity,'' he said.
   ``He evidently said, `yeah, gee whiz, that's great, let's go
ahead,''' Gore said.
   Gore voiced sympathy for Simon, the Illinois senator whose White
House bid is on the ropes in Illinois, for a television ad being
aired by Dukakis. It says a vote for Simon is in effect a vote for
a confused race and perhaps a brokered convention.
   ``Gov. Dukakis's commercial tries to lump him in with back-room
politics of a kind Paul Simon has not been associated with,'' Gore
said at a news conference.
   Gore continued to depict himself as a more electable alternative
to Dukakis and his other rivals but did not dwell on them in a
series of speeches in the Chicago area. But asked about Dukakis by
the law students, Gore said he would respond ``with relish.''
   He repeated his contention that Dukakis lacks necessary foreign
policy experience and said Dukakis has wrongly stated that there is
no ``underclass'' in America _ the Tennessee senator asserting that
children trapped in a cycle of poverty do make up such an
underclass. And he faulted Dukakis for shortcomings as a campaigner.
   ``I think he's not yet found his voice to articulate his message
beyond the `Massachusetts Miracle,''' Gore said, referring to
Dukakis' claim that he helped turn around his state's economy.
   ``I don't think he has succeeded in offering a clear vision of
what he would do as president,'' Gore said.
   Gore said his decision to spend Friday night through Sunday
morning in Washington did not reflect an abandonment of his hopes
for Illinois. He said he spent much of the time raising money by
telephone, and said his fund-raisers have collected as much as
$150,000 a day since last Tuesday.
   But acknowledging the polls in Illinois, Gore said: ``There are
two favorite sons here; I understand that.''
</TEXT>
