<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Nurses     03-14 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Nurses,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nurses Across Britain Protest To Demand More NHS Money</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of nurses at hospitals across Britain
held strikes, rallies and marches today in a last-minute attempt to
get the Conservative government to allocate more money to the
National Health Service.
   Bus services were halted or slowed on dozens of routes as crews
at some some London transport centers walked out in sympathy, said
London Regional Transport spokesman Graham White.
   In London, where about 500 nurses mounted picket lines at 15
hospitals, nurses delivered a cake with a message to Chancellor of
the Exchequer Nigel Lawson, who will unveil the budget in
Parliament on Tuesday.
   ``We hope we will get a bigger slice of the budget,'' said
19-year-old student nurse Sue Hogg.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's government, expected to make
substantial tax cuts, has ruled out a big increase in the service's
$41 billion budget.
   Mrs. Thatcher has ordered a review of the service and plans to
encourage more Britons to take out private health insurance.
   Outside the capital, strikes were ``fairly limited,'' according
to the Confederation of Health Service Employees, one of two health
unions sponsoring the protest.
   The third major union, the Royal College of Nurses, has a
no-strike code of principle.
   Overall, 515,000 nurses work in Britain.
   In Northern Ireland, a British province, 10,000 nurses took part
in protest marches. In Wales, nurses presented a 60,000-signature
petition to the Health Department.
   Outside London, strikes were reported at two hospitals in
Manchester and one in Cheshire, in Yorkshire and Wakefield, and at
St. James General Hospital and other hospitals in Leeds.
   Pickets or marches were held in Brighton, Bristol, Nottingham,
Leicester, Coventry, Birmingham, and Coventry.
</TEXT>
