<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Inventories     03-14 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Inventories,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rise Less Than Half of Preceding Month</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Business inventories rose 0.4 percent in
January, less than half the pace turned in during the previous
month, the government reported today.
   The Commerce Department said the gain in inventories pushed them
up by $3 billion in January to a seasonally adjusted $705.85
billion.
   The inventory increase came as total business sales were falling
0.7 percent to a seasonally adjusted $462.78 billion in January,
reversing much of the big 1.2 percent December increase in sales.
   The January gain in inventories held on shelves and backlots
followed an even larger 0.9 percent increase in December. The
Janaury rise was held back by a 1 percent decline in inventories
held by retailers.
   This decrease reflected primarily a 3.3 percent drop in the
backlog of unsold cars as dealers offered new incentive programs to
spur lagging sales.
   Analysts had worried that a huge rise in unsold inventories
during the final three months of the year would force production
cutbacks and weak economic growth in the early part of 1988.
   But economists have recently modified their views somewhat,
contending that the slowdown in growth in the early part of this
year will not be as severe as they had feared.
   The 1 percent decline in inventories held at the retail level
was accompanied by an increase of 1.6 percent in inventories at the
wholesale level and a 0.8 percent rise in manufacturing inventories.
   The 0.7 percent overall sales decline was led by a 1.7 percent
drop in sales by manufacturers and a 0.2 percent decline in sales
at the retail level. Sales at the wholesale level rose 0.4 percent
in January.
   In an advance report on Friday, the government said that retail
sales in February had risen by 0.6 percent.
   The combination of falling sales and rising inventories pushed
the inventory-to-sales ratio up from 1.51 in December to 1.53 in
January. That means it would take 1.53 months to exhaust
inventories at the January sales pace, still a ratio that is not
considered abnormally high.
</TEXT>
