<DOCNO> AP880314-0099 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-88 1124EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Copper-7     03-14 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Copper-7,0491</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Documents Released In Copper-7 Lawsuit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Company documents reveal that G.D. Searle
& Co. misled doctors and federal officials about safety
characteristics of its Copper-7 contraceptive device, according to
lawyers for the plaintiff in a lawsuit.
   According to documents released last week by a federal court,
Searle apparently hid complaints about the Copper-7 from the Food
and Drug Administration, lawyers said.
   Eventually, an FDA task force recommended that a federal grand
jury investigate whether any laws were broken by Searle's allegedly
misleading reports on animal studies for a number of products,
including the Copper-7. No charges were filed.
   Paul Strain, an attorney for Searle, said testimony and
documents not yet made public will show the company did not mislead
anyone.
   The Copper-7 was a popular intrauterine device from 1974 to
1988, when Searle withdrew it from the market citing the costs of
lawsuits claiming it caused health problems. Many American women
continue to use Copper-7 IUDs and Searle recently resumed
manufacturing the device in order to fill foreign orders.
   The Searle documents, produced for a May 16 trial in St. Paul,
became public last Thursday on order of U.S. District Judge Robert
Renner. The judge rejected Searle's arguments that the internal
company memorandums be kept confidential because of trade secrets
and other reasons.
   ``These documents can be characterized as the tip of the
iceberg,'' said Michael Ciresi, a Minneapolis attorney who
represents Esther Kociemba, a Melrose woman who claims to have been
made infertile by the Copper-7.
   ``Once all the documents are disclosed (to the public), they
will collectively establish without a doubt that the Copper-7
causes (infection) and Searle knew about it, but did not disclose
it to doctors or to women,'' Coresi said.
   Nationally, there have been 17 trials over Searle's Copper-7, 14
of them decided in the company's favor.
   Kociemba's case ``will be the first case tried against Searle
where the jury will be presented with evidence from Searle's files
showing what Searle knew about the hazards of the IUD, when they
knew about them and what they did about them _ which was to conceal
the information,'' Ciresi said.
   Strain said, ``We are confident when a jury hears all the
evidence, reviews all the documents and, most importantly, hears
from the doctors that they will conclude the Copper-7 is a good IUD
that does not cause infection.''
   A major issue will be whether Copper-7's withdrawal ``tail''
string was a single strand of polypropylene incapable of
transporting infection-causing bacteria into the uterus, as Searle
contends, or if it was made up of many tiny strands that could act
as a tunnel for bacteria, as Ciresi contends.
   One of the Searle documents quotes a company official saying for
the first time that, although the Copper-7 string is considered a
single line, it actually is a ``bundle of fused micro-filaments.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
