<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FrommeTrial     03-14 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fromme Trial,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fromme Goes On Trial On Escape Charge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTHA BRYSON HODEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BECKLEY, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge today denied for a second
time Lynette ``Squeaky'' Fromme's request for a no-contest plea to
an escape charge and began calling a jury to hear the case against
the Manson disciple and would-be presidential assassin.
   Fromme, who said she intends to act as her own lawyer, said she
wanted to ``disperse with this case as simply as possible.''
   Fromme, 39, is serving a life sentence for a 1975 assassination
attempt on then-President Gerald Ford. She escaped Dec. 23 from the
Federal Correctional Institution at Alderson and was recaptured
about two miles away on Christmas Day after a massive manhunt.
   ``I admit committing the escape,'' she said. ``I was away for
two days.''
   Fromme told U.S. District Judge Elizabeth Hallanan that the case
``doesn't warrant a jury trial'' and professed herself ``willing to
accept whatever sentence you hand down to me.''
   But Fromme failed today to ask for ``bench trial,'' which would
have left the decision in the judge's hands without calling a jury.
   Court officials said 50 potential jurors had been called to be
questioned by Fromme and assistant U.S. Attorney J. Kirk Brandfess.
   Fromme is a follower of Charles Manson, a mass murderer serving
a life sentence in California.
   Ford was unharmed when a Secret Service agent grabbed a
semi-automatic .45-caliber pistol aimed at him by Fromme on Sept.
5, 1975.
   In San Francisco 17 days later, Ford escaped injury when Sara
Jane Moore fired a revolver at him. She eventually pleaded guilty
and received a life sentence.
   In 1979, Moore also escaped from the Alderson prison, but was
recaptured hours later about 25 miles away. She is now in a federal
prison in Pleasanton, Calif.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
