<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration would not say today
whether it would try to extradite Panamanian strongman Manuel
Antonio Noriega on drug trafficking charges if he seeks asylum in
Spain.
   ``Whatever arrangements he makes with another country are his
business,'' said White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater. ``We
intend to follow the legal process.''
   Reagan has the legal authority to move to dismiss drug
indictments against Noriega. Or, the United States could press for
Noriega's extradition and seek to prosecute him. Fitzwater refused
to clear up which legal course would be pursued.
   ``We don't have any comment,'' the spokesman said at a White
House news briefing.
   Officials in Spain have said that government would be willing to
grant asylum to Noriega under certain conditions _ including the
proviso that the United States would promise not to try to
extradite him after he arrived in Spain.
   Reagan on Friday called for Noriega to step down and end his
``illegitimate'' regime. To force Noriega's ouster, the
administration has applied a series of sanctions against Panama,
including the withholding of about $6.6 million in payments
relating to the operation of the Panama Canal.
