<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Poland-Coin     03-14 0202</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Poland-Coin,0209</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Papal Image Struck on Polish Gold Piece</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Poland, in an attempt to cash in on the
popularity of Polish-born Pope John Paul II, has struck new gold
coins with the papal image and will sell them in the United States
for $8,800 apiece.
   It is the most precious coin issued by the Polish national mint
since World War II.
   The state-run PAP news agency said Monday the coin is 12.6
ounces of pure gold and has a face value 200,000 zlotys, but will
be worth 12 million zlotys.
   At the black-market exchange rate of 1,360 zlotys to the dollar,
12 million zlotys is about $8,800. PAP said the coins would be sold
for $8,800 in the United States.
   Poland produced silver coins with the pope's image in 1982,
prior to the second visit to his homeland of the former archbishop
of Krakow, Karol Wojtyla.
   The new coins were contracted by a U.S. company, and will be
sold through coin dealers in the United States, said Zbigniew
Marski of the National Bank of Poland. He declined to identify the
U.S. company.
   It will be illegal to buy the coins in Poland, even for dollars,
PAP said.
</TEXT>
