<2ND_LINE>PM-Border Arrests, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0553,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Mexicans Arrested After Interrogating Americans North of
Border</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lead to show Mexicans apparently interrogated, and
INSERTS three grafs after 6th pvs, ``Initial statements xxx,
picnickers scattered, comment from Mexico</NOTE>
<DATELINE>IMPERIAL BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four armed Mexican naval personnel
who said they were pursuing drug smugglers apparently interrogated
a group of American picnickers on a beach more than a half mile
north of the U.S.-Mexican border, authorities said.
   The four Mexicans were arrested Sunday night, said San Diego
County sheriff's Sgt. Bob Ramirez.
   The four men, whose names were being withheld, interrogated a
group of 10 to 15 U.S. citizens who were picnicking on the beach,
said Dale Cozart, chief agent for the U.S. Border Patrol in San
Diego.
   ``It's a very serious situation,'' Cozart said today. ``Our
investigation is not complete at this time, but it's possible the
Americans were being interrogated against their will.''
   Border Patrol agents scanning the area in a helicopter spotted
the four men dressed in Mexican naval infantry uniforms and armed
with fully loaded automatic rifles, Cozart said. The weapons were
standard military issue, he added.
   ``Initial statements taken were that they were pursuing
narcotics smugglers. But that has not been confirmed and there is
no indication that narcotics were being smuggled in the area at the
time,'' Cozart said.
   Local residents frequently picnic on the beach into the night,
but Cozart said authorities had not been able to speak to any of
the picnickers because they scattered when the helicopter hovered
overhead.
   The Mexican men said they had been chasing two suspected drug or
arms smugglers up the beach when they were discovered. The Mexicans
headed south and were intercepted before they could get across the
border.
   In Mexico City, spokesmen for the foreign ministry and the
Mexican navy said they had no information on the incident.
   The men were being held at the Border Patrol's San Ysidro sector
station, solely for investigation of immigration violations, he
said.
   ``There is no doubt that the individuals knew they were in the
United States,'' the agent said.
   He added that any other allegations, including possible weapons
violations, would be considered at a later time.
   Five sheriff's deputies were called to assist in the arrests,
which occurred without incident, Cozart said.
   State Department officials as well as the Mexican consulate in
San Diego and Mexican military officials were notified of the
arrests.
</TEXT>
