<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-88 1231EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-UN-PLOMission     03-14 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-PLO Mission,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PLO Envoy Says He Will Defy Order To Close Mission</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The PLO ambassador to the United Nations
declared today he will defy a U.S. order to close his mission and
said that if his office is closed, Israel should be excluded from
debates on the Middle East.
   ``We have the right to stay here, we will stay here and we will
stay where we are,'' Zehdi Labib Terzi, the permanent observer of
the Palestine Liberation Organization, told a news conference here.
   The General Assembly may reconvene this week in an emergency
session to consider the confrontation between the United States and
the 159-member world body, U.N. officials said.
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar today was drafting a
letter to protest the U.S. decision to close the PLO's U.N.
Observer Mission under a controversial anti-terrorism law.
   ``If somebody tries to kick us out, we will not respond,'' Terzi
said, adding he had no plans to leave the United States where his
mission has operated for the last 13 years.
   ``The only way they will make me leave is to put me behind bars
and take me away.''
   The PLO envoy also said that if the PLO Mission is closed, as
ordered by the Justice Department, then the General Assembly should
deny Israel the right to participate in U.N. debates on the Middle
East.
   ``If the Palestinian people are not allowed to be here,'' he
said, ``then out of a sense of fairness and justice, the other
party to the conflict should not be here _ namely Israel.''
   Terzi was responding to a U.S. Justice Department statement on
Friday that it would enforce the law to close the PLO's U.N.
Observer Mission by March 21.
   The United Nations has strongly protested the U.S. move to
enforce the law. It says the act violates the U.N. Charter and the
1947 treaty by which the United States agreed to allow U.N.
missions to operate.
   The PLO is an invitee of the United Nations.
   The General Assembly convened in an emergency session two weeks
ago and urged the United States to comply with international law
and allow the mission to operate. It said it would convene again if
the United States decided to enforce the act.
</TEXT>
