<DOCNO> AP880314-0115 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-88 1237EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Zimbabwe-Rain     03-14 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Zimbabwe-Rain,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop-Killing Rains Follow Devastating Drought</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN EDLIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers who prayed for rain during a
devastating three-year drought have faced nearly four months of
almost daily downpours, which threaten to wash away any chance of
an agricultural rebound.
   The rains that began in November have caused widespread flooding
in rural areas, swelling rivers, turning streets into streams, and
virtually isolating some villages by knocking out phone lines and
bridges.
   It also has severely hampered the recovery of farmers who five
months ago were in the throes of drought, the Agriculture Minstry
said Monday.
   Last week, eight soldiers drowned while fording a flood-swollen
river in the eastern highlands. By the weekend, police said 66
people had been killed by lightning since the first storms broke.
   ``We're working all hours and weekends too,'' said Temba
Munyarara, a handyman who works mainly in poor black suburbs.
``It's sad to see the damage that's being done but it's been good
for me.''
   It is in the countryside, where most of Zimbabwe's 8.2 million
people live, that floods threaten agricultural recovery after the
long drought. About 70 percent of the population depends on
agriculture for income.
   Likewise, the bulk of the land-locked nation's export income
comes from cash crops such as cotton, coffee, corn, sugar, tea and
tobacco.
   Last year, agricultural output fell 18 percent, or $180 million,
as a result of drought.
   Business Trends, the Standard Chartered Bank's monthly economic
analysis, reported that the losses would be recouped with the onset
of the regular rains.
   But the agriculture ministry's most recent crop and livestock
report says that in most areas, further widespread rain will ``do
more harm than good.''
   Cotton, peanuts and tobacco are being severely damaged, the
report said, but it predicted that if the rains ease off, Zimbabwe
still can expect bumper harvests.
   The report also said ample water has been stored underground and
in lakes and dams to carry Zimbabwe through the coming dry season,
which usually lasts from May to October.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880314-0116 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-88 1248EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a DomingoandBaltsaSingConcertatMetOpera     03-14 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>Domingo and Baltsa Sing Concert at Met Opera</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Placido Domingo and Agnes Baltsa are two opera
stars who know how to put passion and drama into their singing even
when they're not performing in a staged production.
   The tenor and the mezzo-soprano demonstrated their talents in a
gala concert Sunday night at the Metropolitan Opera. The benefit
for the Met pension fund was sponsored by the Metropolitan Opera
Guild and followed by a champagne supper, underwritten by Merrill
Lynch and Co.
   Since most operatic love duets are written for tenors and
sopranos, Domingo and Miss Baltsa sang three duets of a more
confrontational nature. Their voices blended beautifully but made
the sparks fly.
   They sang a dramatic scene from Verdi's ``Aida,'' in which
Amneris makes one last offer to Radames _ take me and save your
life. Even on that basis, he turns her down.
   They sang Santuzza angrily accusing Turiddu of being unfaithful
in Mascagni's ``Cavalleria Rusticana'' and Turiddu being angry
back, lying and denying it.
   And, building to the most familiar but still the most
spine-tingling, they sang Don Jose pleading with Carmen to take him
back in Act 4 of Bizet's ``Carmen.'' When she turns him down, he
stabs her to death. In that number, the chorus, facing the
audience, was too loud. In staged performances, the chorus is
behind the ``bullring'' at the back of the stage.
   Domingo has a glorious voice for everything he sang. In a
``Luisa Miller'' aria, for instance, he was vocally always
masculine and strong but could at the same time sound soft and
tender in the quiet lines. He was completely equal to the Verdi
music but never overpowered it.
   Miss Baltsa's voice sounds dark in its low tones and light,
almost white, in its top. There isn't a break in her register; her
voice seems to shade gradually. In her first aria, from Rossini's
``The Lady of the Lake,'' it was a bit disconcerting. Then one
became used to it. She used that shading and other vocal colors to
strong dramatic effect, especially as Carmen.
   She sang the title role in ``Carmen'' at the Met last season.
This season the concert is her only appearance.
   Domingo, who made his Met debut in ``Cavalleria Rusticana,'' is
singing in ``The Tales of Hoffmann'' and ``Otello'' at the Met this
season.
   Nello Santi conducted. The orchestra played overtures by Rossini
and Verdi and a Mascagni intermezzo and sounded clear and fresh.
The chorus, with the women in gowns of their choice, also sounded
splendid in Verdi's ``Anvil Chorus'' from ``Il Trovatore'' and
``Va, pensiero'' from ``Nabucco.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880314-0117 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-88 1249EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--OldWreck     03-14 0179</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Old Wreck,0182</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Archaeologists Find Site of Ancient Mediterranean Wreck</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An archaeological team has found pottery from a
vessel that sank about 2,400 years ago in the Mediterranean Sea, a
spokesman for the group said Monday.
   Divers found the wreck site buried in mud and silt in the crater
of a submerged volcano near the island of Isola Panarea off
northern Sicily, said the spokesman for Marine Archaeological
Research for Europe.
   One diver wrote in the team's log that the wreck looks ``as if
the gods had been sitting down to a banquet, and then, for some
reason, they had to dash off, overturning the tables in their haste
and knocking down all the crockery,'' the spokesman said.
   The cups, plates, jugs, bowls and lamps are made of red clay and
painted with a high-quality, black glaze, said the spokeman, who
asked not to be identified.
   ``All that is visible on the seabed is a spread of pottery,'' he
said. ``It is too early to judge with any confidence how much of
the wreck survives.
</TEXT>
