<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Uganda-Rebels     03-14 0163</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Uganda-Rebels,0170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels Attack Ugandan Passenger Train, Killing at Least Five</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rebels derailed and ransacked a passenger
train, killing at least five people, a government newspaper
reported Monday.
   The Islamic Information Center newspaper Focus, however,
reported that 30 people died in the Uganda People's Army attack
Saturday near Nagongera, about 140 miles east of the capital city
of Kampala.
   Focus said the dead included civilians and eight government
soldiers who were disarmed and shot to death by the rebels.
   The government-owned New Vision newspaper said the attack took
place on a newly reopened route.
   An unidentified passenger said the rebels initially asked
passengers for money and clothes and left people in their underwear.
   The rebels are among more than half a dozen groups fighting
President Yoweri Museveni's government. They say they are loyal to
Peter Otai, defense minister under former President Milton Obote,
who ruled from 1980-85.
   Museveni seized power in 1986 after waging a five-year bush war.
</TEXT>
