<HEAD>Australian Party Leader Quits in Flap Over Conflict of Interest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANBERRA, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The embattled president of the
governing Labor Party stepped down Monday after Prime Minister Bob
Hawke criticized him for a possible conflict of interest.
   Hawke called on veteran politician Mick Young to resign after
Young was widely criticized for accepting a post as consultant with
Qantas, the Australian national airline.
   Young earlier this year resigned his seat in parliament and his
position as minister for immigration following a controversy over
undeclared campaign donations made to the Labor Party by
Japanese-owned woodchip company Harris-Daishowa.
   A new party president will be picked April 7.
