<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Bangladesh     03-14 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bangladesh,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bangladesh President Wants To Make Islam Official Religion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HASAN SAEED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Hussain Muhammad Ershad has
declared that Islam will be the official religion of Bangladesh,
but critics say the move is merely a ploy to prevent his ouster and
woo the Moslem majority.
   Government officials on Monday were caught off guard by Ershad's
announcement, made the day before to a Moslem congregation in
Sarsina, 100 miles southwest of Dhaka.
   Ershad said the laws of Bangladesh should conform to the Moslem
code of conduct.
   ``The day-to-day life of the nation must be guided by the tenets
of Islam and the ideals of Prophet Mohammed,'' he said.
   An official at the Law Ministry said he had no information on
the change.
   ``We do not know what exactly the president wants to do,'' said
the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Eighty-five percent of Bangladesh's 105 million people are
Moslem, but the country has had a secular constitution since it
gained independence from Pakistan in 1971. Minority religions are
Christian, Hindu and Buddhist.
   Opposition parties, which have been calling since November for
the president's ouster, opposed the change. Parliament, which is
controlled by Ershad's Jatiya Party, is expected to debate the
change in April.
   ``This is an illegal government and illegal Parliament. It has
no right to enact any legislation,'' said Khaleda Zia, leader of
the Bangladesh Nationalist Party. Zia was referring to
parliamentary elections earlier this month that were boycotted by
opposition groups.
   The Moslem fundamentalist party, the Jamaat-e-Islami, also
opposed the move.
   ``A government which came to power illegally and is staying much
against the wishes of the people can never do any good to Islam,
the people or the country,'' said Ali Ahsan Mohammad Mujahid, a
Jamaat leader.
   Surenjit Sengupta of the opposition Awami League, said: ``This
is yet another gimmick by President Ershad to hang onto power.''
   But Wali Ashraf, an independent member of Parliament, said:
``Such a legislation will only reflect the faith of the vast
majority of the people.''
   Others believe the Islamic law, with its stringent punishments,
could curb crime and increase productivity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
