<1ST_LINE>r p AM-PoliticalAds     03-14 0665</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Ads,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Advertising Buys Fall Off in Illinois</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Only three presidential candidates ran
substantial television campaigns for Tuesday's Illinois primary, a
sharp contrast to the frenzied multi-million dollar advertising
buys that led up to Super Tuesday.
   The big spender in Illinois was Republican front-runner George
Bush, who bought about $400,000 worth of time.
   Two Democrats, Michael Du Gore Jr., were hoping
for respectable showings short of victory in a state that is
fielding two popular favorite sons.
   The Dukakis campaign said it was spending about $250,000 while
Gore media expenditures were estikakis and Albertmated at $200,000 to $300,000.
   The sparse media buys and tame ads were in contrast to the
charges and counter-charges that marred the airwaves ahead of last
week's far-flung Super Tuesday contests in 20 states.
   Bush was running two advertisements in Illinois _ one a
biographical spot and the other showing him with world leaders and
President Reagan.
   The latter ad, used since the New Hampshire primary last month,
says there is a difference between presidential and congressional
leadership. The point is to compare Bush favorably to rival Bob
Dole, the Senate Republican leader.
   However, Dole's chances of winning the GOP nomination plummeted
after he lost all 17 GOP contests last week, and he sharply cut
addition to mounting the strong TV campaign, she said.
   On the Democratic side, Illinois Sen. Paul Simon and Jesse
Jackson of Chicago were neck and neck as each sought a home-state
victory. Neither favorite son was running TV ads and Simon conceded
a lack of money for ads was hurting his prospects to beat Jackson.
   Polls showed Massachusetts Gov. Dukakis in third place with
Tennessee Sen. Gore and Rep. Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., lagging
behind.
   ``With the favorite sons in the race, obviously nobody expected
us to win Illinois,'' said Dukakis spokesman Steve Akey. ``The
objective is to be very competitive and to demonstrate that we can
do well all over the country.''
   To that end, Dukakis was running three ads, including two he
used for Super Tuesday _ a spot stressing his experience as a chief
executive and another in which a union official says Dukakis is not
a ``shot-and-beer kinda guy'' but his economic policies put people
to work.
   Dukakis introduced an new ad saying the days of backroom dealing
are over _ a response to Simon's contention that there will be no
first-ballot victor at the Democratic convention and he still could
secure or at least influence the nomination.
   ``Some people would like to turn back the clock, to go back to
the days when the voters didn't really pick their nominee,'' says
the announcer in the Dukakis commercial. ``They say you must turn
over that power to them at a brokered convention. But you don't
have to do this. On Tuesday, you can pick the next president...''
   Gore was running a mix of three advertisements in Illinois, all
of them positive messages. One especially made for Illinois says
Gore won six states on Super Tuesday by taking his case to the
people, and asks Illinois voters for their support.
   The other two ads, used throughout the South for Super Tuesday,
have a populist thrust. One chides American companies for investing
in jobs overseas rather than at home and the other says big
chemical polluters, price fixers, corporate law breakers, greedy
drug manufacturers ``don't want Al Gore to be president'' because
he's fought them in the past.
   Gephardt made a poor Super Tuesday showing and was skipping
Illinois to concentrate on Michigan, which holds caucuses March 26.
Gephardt had used ads critical of Dukakis and Gore in the Super
Tuesday states and both candidates came back with on-air ``attack
ads'' to which Gephardt couldn't afford to respond.
</TEXT>
