<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-RatPack     03-14 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Rat Pack,0472</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Frank, Dean And Sammy `Start Spreadin' The News'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dean Martin, Sammy Davis Jr. and Frank
Sinatra start spreadin' the news in Canada on Tuesday after
dazzling ``rat pack'' fans here at the start of their 29-city
reunion tour.
   The three veteran showmen joked and sang with the same
easy-going, cocktail lounge manner that has kept them in superstar
ranks for decades as they performed the first of 40 shows in the
Oakland Coliseum on Sunday night.
   Sinatra, 72, Davis, 62, and Dean Martin, 70, were as much adored
as applauded by the 14,500 fans from teen-agers to people in their
80s. The show sold out an hour after tickets became available weeks
ago, and scalpers were getting as much as $300 for a $40 seat.
   Martin opened the show, staggering and swaggering onto the stage
with his trademark cigarette and cocktail in hand. After slurring
his way through, ``That's Amore,'' ``Everybody Loves Somebody
(Sometime),'' and a string of one liners, he yielded to Davis.
   The ``Candy Man'' proved he still can, rousing the crowd with
``What Kind of Fool Am I?,'' ``Bojangles,'' and ``I've Got To Be
Me.'' He also was cheered when he announced he gave up drinking
three years ago.
   ``I've got to tell you the truth. Everybody backstage is being
very cool, but I wasn't this scared when I lived at 147th Street
and Eighth Avenue in New York,'' he confessed.
   But it was Sinatra _ Old Blue Eyes, The Man, The Voice, The
Chairman of The Board _ that most fans had come to see, and they
weren't disappointed as he powered his way through hit after hit:
``What Now My Love,'' ``For Once In My Life,'' ``Mack The Knife,''
and the song he called the national anthem, ``New York, New York.''
   The trio then performed a medley of songs together, as women and
at least one man dropped flowers on the stage.
   ``We bought tickets for ourselves because we knew we'll never
see it again,'' said Dan Chaix of Alameda, a 30-year-old fan who
was considering flying his parents to another city so they could
catch the show. ``I saw Frank 15 years ago in Vegas and he's better
than he's ever been,'' said Chaix' wife, Karen.
   ``I thought they looked great. For me, it was a once in a
lifetime thing,'' said Maureen Pobuta, 33, of San Mateo. Said
Bernice Hourcade: ``I'd have died if I hadn't come tonight.''
   After Tuesday night's show in Vancouver, British Columbia, the
``Together Again'' tour moves to Seattle on Wednesday, then to
Chicago for two weekend shows. The tour is scheduled through
October, with performances across the country. Other dates are to
be announced in Southern California.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
