<DOCNO> AP880314-0134 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NY-03-14-88 1438EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-TaxPenalties     03-14 0716</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tax Penalties,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IRS Endorses Review of Tax Penalties Which Critics Say Hurt Poor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Internal Revenue Service pledged support
Monday to a review of tax penalties that were assessed last year in
some 27 million cases _ penalties that have been criticized as a
special burden on the poor.
   At the opening of a public inquiry into the maze of 154
penalties the IRS can impose, IRS Commissioner Lawrence B. Gibbs
expressed the agency's own concern about the penalties, many of
which were enacted by Congress over the past seven years in an
effort to increase compliance with the tax laws.
   ``A penalty system that operates based on the wrong principles
may provide appropriate sanctions for some types of behavior and
yet have an overall negative impact on taxpayer behavior because it
is not perceived as fair,'' Gibbs said.
   Several witnesses at Monday's hearing accused the government of
using penalties to raise revenues, rather than to assure compliance
with the laws.
   Sen. David Pryor, D-Ark., chairman of a Senate Finance
subcommittee that oversees the IRS, cited the case of one business
that underpaid employment taxes by 2 cents and was hit with a
penalty of $400.29.
   ``We've created some sort of a monster here,'' Pryor said.
``We're going to change that some way.''
   Gibbs and O. Donaldson Chapoton, assistant secretary of the
treasury for tax policy, endorsed a thorough review of tax
penalties. A review also was endorsed by the Chamber of Commerce,
the National Association of Manufacturers and associations
representing lawyers, accountants and other tax professionals.
   ``We certainly hope there's not any reaction ... by IRS agents
in the field ... that penalties should be used as means of raising
revenue,'' Chapoton said.
   The University of Akron Center for Taxation Studies said that
when one penalty is stacked atop another, it indicates a goal of
raising revenue.
   A major problem with penalties, said James W. Childs, director
of the university's tax clinic program, is that Congress has not
given the IRS sufficient guidance on how penalties should be
applied. As a result, he said, penalties often are applied to
taxpayers who have neither the funds to hire a lawyer or accountant
nor knowledge of how the system works.
   ``The low-income taxpayer has about as much knowledge of how to
obtain abatement of a penalty through problems resolution (the IRS'
``consumer advocate'') as he-she does of getting to the moon,''
said Childs. ``Abuses by high-income taxpayers have brought about a
plethora of new penalties. Unfortunately, the low-income taxpayer
has been caught in this net.''
   An even more basic problem, Childs said, is the difficulty in
reading IRS tax forms in general. He cited a finding that
instructions for Form 1040EZ _ the simplest tax form _ require an
8.45 grade reading level, compared to a 7.1 level to read the Wall
Street Journal.
   Penalties in the tax law range from $1 for failing to file a
statement on payment of dividends totaling less than $10 to a
maximum of 25 percent of the tax owed for failing to pay on time to
$10,000 for abetting a corporation in the understatement of its tax
liability. In 1987, the IRS assessed 27 million penalties totaling
$14 billion and excused another 4 million for $4 billion.
   Pryor criticized IRS for the way it applies penalties against
taxpayers who file what the IRS considers frivolous returns.
Congress created the penalty, which can be as much as $500, to
discourage taxpayers from using arguments such as
self-incrimination to avoid a proper tax return.
   Pryor said he has evidence the IRS is imposing the penalty
against those who write critical notes to the agency on their
returns, even though the returns are completed and signed. He cited
the much-publicized case of a Montana woman who was hit with a
penalty for such behavior and whose husband's life insurance policy
was seized before a federal judge intervened.
   ``If that little old lady lived in Arkansas or New Jersey, would
she get the same penalty?'' Pryor asked Gibbs. ``Who makes those
decisions?''
   Gibbs promised to check into the Montana case but Pryor quickly
cautioned against it. ``I don't think she wants you to review her
case and flag her return,'' the senator said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
