<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines     03-14 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines,0443</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rights Group Rips Philippines Military For Civilian Atrocities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES W. HATTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military is killing and
terrorizing civilians under the pretense of fighting communism, and
the campaign has gone unchecked by the government, a human rights
group charged Monday.
   Task Force-Detainees, a group formed by the Roman Catholic
Church to monitor rights violations under ousted President
Ferdinand Marcos, charged that the military began its spree two
months ago in northeastern Aurora province.
   It called for an investigation and claimed that atrocities
included the Feb. 11 slaying of Roberto Rivares, a leftist
provincial leader who helped organize the group's probe.
   At a news conference, the group introduced a 6-year-old boy who
said he was the only member of his family to survive a Jan. 23
massacre. Five others died.
   ``I saw soldiers shoot my father and mother, after which they
turned to me and shot me in both legs,'' said Ronaldo Guzman, his
legs in casts.
   The rights group also claimed more than 1,000 people had fled
their homes in the town of Dinalungan, about 120 miles northeast of
Manila, to escape military operations.
   It said the violence was being waged under the guise of battling
the 19-year-old communist insurgency in the Philippines.
   ``In the past, during Marcos' time, we had military in the towns
in the north but there was not this kind of strafing, massacre and
burning of houses,'' said Bishop Julio Xavier Labayen. ``We're
sitting on a powder keg.''
   In a statement, the group said: ``Task Force-Detainees hopes
that President (Corazon) Aquino will not simply dismiss this
violation as yet another `total lie' but instead will treat the
matter with grave concern.''
   Mrs. Aquino became president in 1986 after Marcos was toppled
from power.
   Bienvenido Amora, chief investigator for the government's Human
Rights Commission, said he would contact the group about the
charges.
   ``We would have appreciated it very much if the Task
Force-Detainees had brought this matter to the attention of the
Commission on Human Rights so that the (commission) could proceed
to investigate this case accordingly,'' he said.
   Last week, the Task Force said its investigation showed 7,444
Filipino civilians were arrested illegally last year, eclipsing the
5,967 arrests in 1985 under Marcos. Spokesman Noel Salazar said 672
of those detained in 1987 were tortured.
   The same day, Amnesty International claimed similar atrocities
in a report released in London.
   Mrs. Aquino branded the Amnesty report ``one-sided'' and charged
it had relied on Task Force-Detainees for its information. She
challenged both groups to provide evidence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
