<1ST_LINE>r i AM-HungerStriker     03-14 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hunger Striker,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Greek Hunger Striker Demands Right Not to Join Army</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HELENA SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AVLON, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 31-year-old pacifist on Monday entered
the fourth week of a hunger strike to try to win an alternative to
compulsory military service.
   In October, a military court sentenced Michael Marangakis to
four years in prison on insubordination charges. On Feb. 22, an
appeals court reduced his sentence to 26 months.
   The 6-foot 5-inch woodcarver, who weighed 222 pounds, started
his hunger strike the next day. He said he has lost 22 pounds since
then and will take only fruit juice and milk every other day until
the Greek government establishes conscientious objection to
military service.
   ``I won't eat until the government recognizes the right of the
individual to act on the basis of conscience,'' Marangakis said in
an interview at Avlon military prison 29 miles north of Athens.
   Military service is compulsory in Greece, where it averages
about 21 months. Unlike some other European countries, Greece
offers no option to compulsory service, and objectors are routinely
given long prison terms.
   Legal experts say there are about 300 Greeks imprisoned for
refusing to serve in the military. Almost all are Jehovah's
Witnesses.
   Marangakis belongs to one of the ancient Eastern Orthodox
churches but says his pacifism is derived mainly from personal
ideals rather than his religion.
   Stelios Nestos, one of Marangakis' three attorneys, said that 11
other conscientious objectors had recently gone into hiding after
they were called up. But Marangakis presented himself to a military
camp in Drama, in northern Greece, where he was called up in March
1987.
   Marangakis said he was planning to appeal his sentence to
Greece's Supreme Court.
   A new law under debate in the Greek parliament seeks to abolish
prison terms for conscientious objectors but doesn't provide for
alternative service. Instead, conscientious objectors will be
required to serve double time in the armed forces as non-combatants.
   But Marangakis said he would refuse to serve as a non-combatant
because it represents a form of military service.
</TEXT>
