<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Angola     03-14 0495</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Angola,0509</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Botha Says Main Issue in Angola is Timetable for Cuban Withdrawal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA WATSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Africa's foreign minister said Monday that
Angola has not presentated a plan for withdrawal of the estimated
40,000 Cuban troops in that country and a timetable remains a
central issue for regional peace.
   Roelof F. Botha was asked at a news conference about an
announcement Sunday by Angola that it and Cuba had given U.S.
officials proposals for a southern Africa peace accord including a
timetable for Cuban troop withdrawal. He replied: ``That is not
correct.''
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Charles Redman said
Monday the Angolan proposal ``appears to break no new ground'' on
the issue of Cuba's military presence in Angola.
   Botha said the withdrawal timetable, along with who would
supervise the pullout, ``is the issue that must be taken up.''
   He spoke to reporters after a day of talks with Chester A.
Crocker, the U.S. assistant secretary of state who specializes in
southern Africa, aimed at advancing plans for peace in the region.
   Botha said they had ``extensive'' discussions of the situation
in southern Africa and ``the question of Cuban withdrawal as a
prerequisite for implementing a settlement in South-West
Africa-Namibia. We discussed extensively the possibilities that
exist in this respect.''
   ``I've received interesting information,'' he added, and
described the talks as ``useful'' but would not give details. Botha
said he and Crocker might meet again Tuesday, but that nothing was
set.
   Since 1981, Crocker has tried to negotiate a withdrawal of Cuban
troops from Angola in return for an end to South African control
over neighboring South-West Africa, also known as Namibia. His last
meeting with Botha was two years ago.
   Cuban troops help Angola's Marxist government fight the National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola, or UNITA, a guerrilla
force backed by South Africa and the United States.
   In January, Cuba declared a willingness in principle to leave
Angola but no deal has been negotiated.
   On Sunday, UNITA leader Jonas Savimbi said South Africa had told
him it would begin direct talks with Angola on the Angolan civil
war, which began with independence from Portugal in 1975.
   Asked about this at the news conference, Botha responded: ``I
have said that I have no problem in talking directly with Luanda
(the Angolan capital) and to a large number of other African
states.''
   He denied reports that preliminary talks for such negotiations
had been held. ``It's not necessary,'' he said. ``I could pick up a
telephone and talk now.''
   Kundi Payama, No. 2 man in Luanda, repeated that Angola was
prepared to negotiate directly with South Africa but also said
previous direct talks on other matters had not produced results.
   ``I think we can negotiate with the South Africans at any time
as long as they deal honestly with us,'' he said, ``but not if (the
talks) turn out to be just a tactic for gaining time.''
</TEXT>
