<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Punjab     03-14 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Punjab,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sikh Militants Kill 15 In Punjab</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh extremists killed 21 people in
Punjab state, including a family of four, it was reported Monday.
   Police shot and killed Balraj Singh, a Sikh radical wanted for
several murders in Patiala on Monday, according to the state police
control center in Chandigarh.
   The deaths late Sunday and early Monday raised to at least 451
the number of killings blamed on Sikh radicals this year.
   Sikh militants have been fighting since 1982 for more autonomy
or an independent homeland for the sect in Punjab. The northern
state, the country's richest agricultural area, is the only one of
Hindu-dominated India where Sikhs have a majority.
   The United News of India reported that Sardul Singh, his wife
and two daughters were shot to death early Monday in Jhander, a
village in Amritsar District. The gunmen burned the family's house
to the ground before fleeing, it said.
   Responsibility was claimed by the Bhindranwale Tiger Force, one
of more than a dozen radical groups in Punjab. Police said a note
left at the scene said Singh, a Sikh, was being ``punished'' for
extortion and looting, but they gave no details.
   Eight other people were slain in Amritsar District, including
four Hindus in Dallin village, UNI said.
   A retired Sikh police constable identified as Gajjan Singh was
shot to death in Ludhiana District and two Hindu men were pulled
from a truck and shot down in Jalandhar District, the news agency
reported. Both districts are in central Punjab.
   A group of Sikh militants riding a jeep sprayed bullets at a bus
terminus in Hoshiarpur killing six people on the spot, police in
Chandigarh said. The identitities of the victims were not
immediately known.
   Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi's government has been trying to stem
the violence since last May, when it removed the state
administration and put Punjab under federal rule.
   On March 4, Gandhi ordered five Sikh high priests released from
jail in an apparent effort to get them involved against terrorism.
He dissolved the Punjab Assembly two days later, paving the way for
militants to compete in anticipated elections.
   There have been no signs, however, that priests and other Sikh
leaders will move against the radicals.
</TEXT>
