<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Strike,0238</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>25,500 Held On Eve of Strike In India</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 25,000 people were taken into
police custody Monday as authorities moved to block a nationwide
strike to protest corruption and official incompetence, officials
said.
   Nine opposition parties, including the communists, have
scheduled the strike for Tuesday to protest government corruption,
failure to halt secterian violence and to demand better facilities
for farmers and farm laborers.
   Police in the southern state of Madras took 25,000 people into
custody to halt violence during the strike, a police officer in
state capital of Madras said.
   UNI reported that 500 people were arrested in the eastern Orissa
state.
   It said state governments across India deployed additional
security forces Monday to guard important installations and to
maintain law and order.
   Besides the two communist parties, the major sponsor of the
strike is the ``Jan Morcha'' or People's Front, an umbrella group
of disgruntled members of Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi's govering
Congress party.
   The parties have accused the government of failure to contain
Sikh separatist violence in Punjab where 450 people were killed by
suspected Sikh radicals this year.
   Radical Sikhs want to seceede from the Indian union and turn the
state of Punjab into an independent Sikh nation.
   Opposition leaders have also accused Gandhi of shielding members
of his party from corruption inquiries involving foreign arms deals.
