<HEAD>Patrick Binder Back In Intensive Care Unit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the West German Siamese twins separated
in an unprecendented operation in September is in stable condition
at Johns Hopkins Hospital after having swallowing and breathing
problems, officials said.
   Patrick Binder's problems began Sunday, said Lisa Hillman,
spokeswoman at Johns Hopkins.
   The twins, now 13 months old, were joined at birth at the back
of the skull. Doctors worked 23 consecutive hours over Labor Day
weekend to separate them.
   Last month, titanium mesh was implanted in their skulls to fill
in the open areas created by the separation.
   The twins had been scheduled to go home sometime in March. Ms.
Hillman said she did not know how Patrick's problems might affect
that.
