<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0641,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Seeks to Catch Simon on Eve of Illinois Primary</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of Bakalis in 4th graf, But his</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential contender
Michael Dukakis made a final bid Monday to drain Illinois primary
support from favorite son Paul Simon, saying that a brokered
convention might bring disaster for their party in the fall.
   Sen. Simon, short on funds and far behind in the delegate chase,
has said he is on the ballot in Illinois because he wants to play a
role at a brokered Democratic National Convention next summer in
Atlanta.
   Citing published polls, Massachusetts Gov. Dukakis claimed
``significant gains'' in recent days in his bid to catch Simon and
a second favorite son in the race, Chicago civil rights activist
Jesse Jackson.
   But his aides sent conflicting signals about his likely finish
in Tuesday's election. Spokesman Mark Gearan said anything better
than third place was unlikely. But Mike Bakalis, Illinois campaign
chairman for Dukakis, said it was ``very possible'' the governor
might slip into second place behind Jackson, with Simon falling
into third.
   From the moment he began his campaign day with an early morning
commuter train ride in Chicago, Dukakis spoke out against a
brokered convention.
   At an airport news conference in Springfield, he suggested it
could damage Democratic prospects of winning the White House.
   He said that to finish the primary season in June and then have
Democrats ``spend seven or eight weeks negotiating, dealing, people
behind closed doors trying to decide who the nominee ought to be,
while Mr. Bush, if he is the Republican nominee, is kind of sitting
there, smiling at all of this, I think would be a disaster.''
   ``The last thing in the world we need is a brokered
convention,'' he said as he hopscotched across the state in his
chartered campaign jet.
   ``The last thing we need is six people in the back room at
Atlanta deciding who the nominee will be.''
   Dukakis never mentioned Simon by name, even avoiding a direct
answer when a reporter asked if a vote for the senator was a vote
for a brokered convention.
   Still, there was no doubt that the governor's criticism was
aimed at Simon.
   Dukakis is in third place in the Illinois polls, but some
surveys show front-runner Simon dropping with Jackson challenging
him for the lead and Dukakis moving up to a closer third-place
position.
   The same surveys indicate that Dukakis is drawing his
last-minute support from Simon's supporters. Dukakis' aides say
privately they would be delighted to see Jackson beat Simon,
believing it would drive the senator from the race.
</TEXT>
