<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Simon     03-14 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Simon,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Simon Says Illinois is a Must-Win Primary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Illinois Sen. Paul Simon said Monday he has no
plans for his Democratic presidential bid beyond his home state
primary, which he said ``I have to win and I will win.''
   ``A strong second isn't very strong,'' Simon said as he greeted
suburban commuters in the bitter cold at a downtown train station.
   Simon said if he finishes second in the popular vote or in the
selection of delegates, ``I'd have to re-evaluate.''
   ``I have no plans beyond tomorrow,'' said Simon, who was joined
by his wife, Jeanne. ``I have to win and I will win.''
   ``Jesse (Jackson) and I will be the No. 1 and No. 2 finishers
tomorrow, but the biggest competition is Mike Dukakis because of
the huge amount of money he is spending,'' Simon said.
   Simon acknowledged that his ``finances are not great,'' but
added, ``We have matching fund money that's coming in ... that will
take care of our bank loans.''
   He would not put a dollar figure on how much is left in campaign
coffers.
   In a speech later in the day before a labor group in Peoria,
Simon declined to explain his plans to re-evaluate in the event of
a home-state defeat.
   ``I'm not going to go down that path,'' he told a crowd of about
100 local labor leaders. ``We're gonna win this thing.''
   Simon insisted he is still a major force, despite having less
than a tenth of the delegates of each of the Democratic
front-runners.
   ``There are a lot of delegates yet to be chosen. At the
convention there should be five of us with blocks of delegates,''
said Simon, who is counting on a brokered convention.
   He said his blueprint for victory at a brokered convention is
winning Illinois, then collecting delegates in Michigan, Wisconsin,
New York and Ohio, and appealing to labor, educators and senior
citizens to put togther a coalition to win the nomination.
   ``It's going to be a wide-open convention,'' Simon told the
labor hall crowd, who interrupted his 15-minute speech several
times with applause.
</TEXT>
