<HEAD>Students Placed On Probation In Alleged Attack On Black Students</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMHERST, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two white students linked to an attack on
two black students have been banned from living on the University
of Massachusetts campus, a spokeswoman said Monday.
   Punishment was handed down late last week for three of the five
white students accused in the Feb. 7 attack of two black men who
accompanied a white woman to a party.
   The beatings kicked off a six-day takeover of a university
building last month by minority students.
   Two of the five students, whose names were withheld by the
university, had withdrawn from the university before disciplinary
hearings. Those two were evicted from their dormitory rooms by
officials Feb. 13 during a preliminary hearing.
   Of the remaining three students, two were found guilty of
violating the university's rules on assault and all three were
found to have violated the university's rules on drinking.
   All three were ordered to undergo an alcohol education program
and two were placed on disciplinary probation for the rest of this
school year and the 1988-89 school year, said school spokeswoman
Jeanne Hopkins.
   Lawyers for the students were out of their offices Monday and
could not be reached for comment. The students have until March 30
to appeal.
   Testimony in a show-cause hearing on whether criminal charges
should be filed against the five and a sixth man, who was not a
student, was to resume Tuesday.
