<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDS-Towing     03-14 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS-Towing,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robbery Suspect Towed after Saying he had AIDS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A robbery suspect who claimed he had AIDS was
locked in a patrol car and towed to a police station after he
threatened to bite any officer who approached him, authorities said
Monday.
   Raymond Simmons, 27, was removed from the squad car by police
wearing protective gear and taken to Roosevelt Hospital, where he
was seen by doctors in the emergency room and released 20 minutes
later, officials said.
   A hospital spokeswoman said she could not comment on Simmons'
condition because of confidentiality restrictions. Police said he
was classified as emotionally disturbed.
   AIDS is known to be transmitted through sexual contact, dirty
needles, tainted blood, and from mother to fetus. There are no
documented cases of the fatal disease being transmitted by biting,
said Gayle Lloyd, spokeswoman for the federal Centers for Disease
Control in Atlanta.
   The incident involving Simmons started Sunday morning, said
police spokesman Joseph McConville. Simmons allegedly grabbed money
from a teen-ager's pocket and a fistfight ensued, McConville said.
Police arrived, handcuffed Simmons and put him in the squad car.
   As the officers interviewed the teen-ager, Simmons, wearing a
wig and makeup, ``started cursing and kicking in the rear of the
radio car and told the cops he had AIDS and was going to die and
would take them with him,'' McConville said. ``He said he would
bite first cop that came near him.''
   Police called emergency services officers, who are trained to
deal with distraught people, and summoned a tow truck, McConville
said. The truck towed the squad car to the police station, where
emergency services officers removed Simmons, he said.
   Simmons faced a charge of attempted robbery, police said.
</TEXT>
