<1ST_LINE>r w AM-AgriculturalTrade     03-14 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Agricultural Trade,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trade Mission Set To Travel To Indonesia, Philippines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first foreign mission under a new law to
promote U.S. agricultural trade will go to Indonesia and the
Philippines this spring, Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng
announced Monday.
   Exact dates will be negotiated with the countries, although Lyng
said the trip will be in mid-spring.
   The mission will include representatives from the departments of
Agriculture and State, and the U.S. Agency for International
Development. Three to six representatives of the private sector
also will be selected for the trip to Indonesia and the Philippines.
   ``During my recent trip to Asia, I discussed possible missions
with the leaders and key agricultural officials of both
countries,'' Lyng said. ``We agreed that these missions would not
only address the food needs of these countries, but would help
develop customers for U.S. agricultural exports as well.''
   The trips are required by the Agricultural Aid and Trade
Missions Act, passed by Congress late last year. It specified that
16 missions be conducted in 1988, with eight to be completed by
June.
   By offering specially designed packages of U.S. trade and food
assistance, the goal of the program is to help the designated
countries develop and to become larger markets for American farmers.
