<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Vietnam     03-14 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Vietnam,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chinese, Vietnamese Ships Exchange Fire Near Disputed Islands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese and Vietnamese ships exchanged fire Monday
near disputed islands in the South China Sea, and each side accused
the other of firing first, news reports said.
   Radio Press, quoting radio broadcasts from the two communist
capitals, said the exchange took place near the Spratly Islands, a
collection of islets and reefs claimed by Vietnam, China and the
Philippines.
   The exchange prompted harsh denunciations from Hanoi and Beijing
and threatened to escalate tensions between the two neighbors.
   China expressed ``great anger and strong protest'' over the
incident in a letter delivered to the Vietnamese Embassy in
Beijing, according to Radio Press, which monitors broadcasts from
communist nations in Tokyo.
   The report, quoting a broadcast by Radio Beijing, said
Vietnamese vessels fired on Chinese warships conducting routine
patrols and research in the area. It said the Chinese ships
returned fire in self-defense.
   Vietnam's Foreign Ministry accused China of distorting the
facts. It condemned Beijing for what it called an armed attack on
two Vietnamese cargo ships conducting ``routine operations.''
   The statement said the ships incurred moderate damage and fired
back in self-defense, according to Radio Press.
   Japan's Kyodo News Service said it was the first armed
confrontation between the two countries since bilateral territorial
disputes have increased in recent months.
</TEXT>
