<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HondaShip     03-14 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Honda Ship,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ship Carrying Hondas Returns To Port</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ship that left with much fanfare a
week ago carrying the first shipment of U.S.-built Hondas bound for
Japan has slipped quietly back to port for repairs.
   The return of the auto carrier Green Bay, which was built last
year in Japan, has complicated efforts by Honda to become the first
Japanese automaker to ship its U.S.-manufactured cars to Japan.
   A spokeswoman for the shipping agent said she had no idea when
the vessel would depart again. June Ainge, district manager for
Williams Dimond & Co. of Portland, said repair crews planned to
examine the vessel Monday.
   The Japanese-built ship left Portland last week with 540 Accords
and 100 Honda motorcyles on board. Sen. Bob Packwood, R-Ore., and
Tetsuo Chino, president of Honda North America Inc., participated
in a news conference to mark the occasion. Chino drove the first
car on board.
   On Sunday, the ship slipped in to the Swan Island drydock.
   Ms. Ainge refused to reveal details of the ship's problems or
its return.
   Francois L. Elmealeh of the Port of Portland's marine marketing
department said he didn't know the details of the ship's problems
but that it was of a ``non-life-threatening, non-cargo-threatening
nature.''
   ``I think it's an embarrassment more than anything,'' Elmealeh
said.
   Honda Motor Co. Ltd. had planned a gala reception to welcome the
vessel March 22 at Narashino Port, east of Tokyo.
   ``The party's postponed, and we're not sure now when it will be
held,'' said Bret Anderson, a Honda public relations official in
Tokyo.
   On Friday, the ship's captain decided to return to Portland, and
the vessel's owner, Central Gulf Lines of New Orleans, was notified.
</TEXT>
