<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LehderTrial     03-14 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lehder Trial,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Smuggler's Wife Testifies She Paid Crews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wife of a convicted smuggler
testified Monday that she disliked her husband's job with alleged
smuggler Carlos Lehder Rivas, but wound up as paymaster for his
crew.
   Lehder, 38, is on trial on charges that he and others conspired
to smuggling 3.3 tons of cocaine into Florida and Georgia from
Colombia via Norman's Cay in the Bahamas from 1978 to 1980.
   The witness' husband, Ed Ward, has testified he was the pilot on
most of those flights.
   Emilie Lassie Ward said she met her husband in 1976 and became
aware that he was involved in smuggling marijuana before their
marriage that summer and confronted him with it.
   ``He told me he was smuggling marijuana. I didn't like it. I was
very much in love with him and he rationalized it,'' she said.
   Ward took her into his confidence as his ``what if'er.''
   As he planned his smuggling operations, ``I would say `what if
this happened'?'' she said.
   All the time, she said she was concerned.
   ``I was worried about him getting arrested and worried about him
being killed,'' she testified.,
   In 1978, she and her husband discussed Lehder's offer to
transport cocaine.
   ``I didn't like it. It was the fear of cocaine. I didn't know
anything about it. It didn't seem like what he was doing was
safe,'' she said.
   She said Ward agreed to make 10 cocaine flights for Lehder, but
she said he quickly became disenchanted.
   Ward, who was very organized, had to deal with uncertain time
schedules and that Lehder wasn't following the safety measures that
Ward insisted upon, she said.
   Mrs. Ward described her duties in the smuggling organization as
counting and handing out the money to Ward's crew.
   Lehder, reputed to be one of the leaders in the violent
Colombian Medellin cartel, is charged with conspiracy, possession
of cocaine with intent to distribute, importation of cocaine and
operating a continuing criminal enterprise.
   Co-defendant Jack Carlton Reed, 57, of San Pedro, Calif., is
charged only with being a part of the smuggling conspiracy.
</TEXT>
