<DOCNO> AP880314-0162 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-88 1642EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CitrusBan     03-14 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Citrus Ban,0529</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Denies Texas Stay In Suit Against USDA</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas lost another round Monday in its
battle to keep Florida citrus out of the state when a federal judge
refused to block those shipments.
   U.S. District Judge Filemon Vela said he needed more time to
study the state's request for a stay of a U.S. Department of
Agriculture decision lifting a ban on Florida citrus to other
producing states.
   Texas sought the stay until its suit against U.S. Secretary of
Agriculture Ricdard E. Lyng could be heard. The state sued Lyng on
Wednesday, accusing the USDA of violating the Adminstrative
Procedures Act when it lifted the 3{-year quarantine on Florida
citrus.
   Texas contends the USDA did not provide an opportunity to
comment on the decision as required by law.
   Monday's hearing was the second time since Texas sued Lyng that
Vela denied the state's request for a stay of the Feb. 11 USDA
ruling.
   Vela gave Texas five days to provide its evidence, from which he
will make a ruling.
   Texas officials say they want to keep Florida citrus out of the
state because they are not convinced an outbreak of bacterial
citrus canker has been controlled in Florida. The USDA quarantined
fruit from Florida after the disease was discovered there in August
1984.
   Canker, which comes in different strains, can cause defoliation
of trees, lesions that make the fruit unmarketable and premature
dropping of fruit from trees.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Jeanette Mercado, representing the USDA,
argued taht Texas has no standing to sue because a quarantine
affecting one industry lacks general importance for the state's
population as a whole.
   Texas Citrus Mutual, a growers' organization, has joined the
state in its lawsuit.
   ``We feel like that if we can get a federal court to address
whether the USDA violated their own administrative procedures, we
think we'll prevail,'' said Ray Prewett, executive vice president
of McAllen-based TCM.
   Bobby McKown of Florida Citrus Mutual said Florida suspended
shipments of fresh citrus to Texas, California, Arizona and
Louisiana on Friday, pending the outcome of Monday's hearing.
   ``We feel much encouraged and we're going to commence shipping
today fruit from Florida to the citrus producing states,'' McKown
said.
   Florida's primary interest in the Texas market is in specialty
fruits, such as tangeloes and honey tangerines, he said.
   Texas officials are seeking to at least keep the fruit out of
the Rio Grande Valley, where the state's $65 million industry is
concentrated in the three southernmost counties.
   Last fall, the USDA published a proposal to lift the Florida
quarantine, but on Jan. 5 withdrew the proposal after new canker
outbreaks were discovered.
   On Feb. 15, four days after USDA lifted the quarantine, Texas
imposed an emergency 30-day quarantine on fresh Florida citrus, and
set up highway roadblocks.
   A federal judge in Austin overturned the Texas quarantine March
1, ruling the federal regulation took precedence.
   A Gulf Coast area of Florida infested with the aggressive
Asiatic strain of canker will remain under quarantine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
