<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-88 1652EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CharlestonDesegregation     03-14 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Charleston Desegregation,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Plaintiffs Near End of Case in Lengthy Desegregation Suit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charleston County schools are segregated
and local school boundaries hamper integration, an expert witness
said Monday as the plaintiff's case in the seven-year-old federal
desegregation suit neared a close.
   ``The schools are racially segregated,'' said William Gordon, a
professor of education at Wright State University in Dayton, Ohio.
   Gordon, armed with a thick black notebook containing results of
a lengthy study of the schools, said the boundaries of eight local
districts within the countywide district hamper both integration
and good education.
   Gordon took the stand as testimony resumed following a two-month
break.
   The suit centers on a 1967 state law which consolidated the
county schools under a countywide.
   The complaint by the U.S. Justice Department alleges that
control of student and faculty assignments were retained by the
local districts for racial reasons.
   Gordon testified on behalf of the Legal Defense Fund which has
intervened on behalf of the families of several Charleston County
school children in the case.
   The Justice Department has completed its case and the Legal
Defense Fund is expected to wrap up its case by midweek. U.S.
District Judge Sol Blatt Jr. is hearing the non-jury trial.
   The complaint asks that Blatt find the local district boundaries
unconstitutional and order steps to promote integration. Blatt has
ruled out busing as a possible remedy.
   Gordon testified that about a third of the schools in the county
can be identified as black, a third white and a third racially
mixed. His guideline for determining a racially identifiable school
is whether the black-white student ratio is more than 15 percent
different from the black-white mix countywide.
   Gordon said that of 35 schools that opened as identifiably white
schools, 17 are still white. Of the 20 that opened as identifiably
black schools, 17 are still black.
   The system of local district lines means ``you take away good
solid educational choices from those who should be making the
decisions,'' Gordon said. ``The boundary becomes the decision.''
   ``Educators should be making the decisions where children go to
school, not boundaries,'' he added.
   He said adherence to the local boundaries has meant overcrowding
in some county schools while others aren't being used to capacity.
</TEXT>
