<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dole     03-14 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dole,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dole Says He Won't Quit, Even if Bush Wins Illinois</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kansas Sen. Bob Dole, saying he would lose
people's trust ``if I cut and run the first bad news we get,'' said
Monday he has no plans to drop his presidential bid after Tuesday's
Illinois primary even if George Bush scores another big victory.
   ``I've made a judgment that Illinois, whatever happens, we're
going to keep going,'' Dole said at a news conference.
   He acknowledged the possibility that a candidate might not
understand when to get out.
   ``Now if you're out there and you've been twisting in the wind
for six or eight months and you're starting to smell a little,
somebody has to cut the rope,'' he said.
   Still, despite polls showing Bush with a lead among Illinois
Republicans of up to 34 points over Dole, the senator said, ``We
believe the bounce is starting to wear of a bit from Super
Tuesday.''
   He referred to the effects of last Tuesday when Bush won 16
primaries to surge far ahead of the rest of the GOP presidential
field.
   ``I think we've made some inroads,'' said Dole when asked about
his prospects in Illinois. ``I don't think we've had quite enough
time. It's a big state.''
   He said a ``realistic estimate'' of his prospects would be 40
percent of the 82 delegates to be elected in the primary.
   Dole said that when a decision is made about the future of his
candidacy ``it will be made by Bob Dole.''
   To emphasize his determination to fight on, Dole planned to
campaign Tuesday in Wisconsin and Connecticut, two of the next
battlegrounds in the race.
   Hammering away at Bush for refusing to participate in a
one-on-one debate, Dole said, ``Why should somebody who's as far
ahead as he is be afraid to stand up and debate issues with
somebody he indicated doesn't have any leadership ability.
   ``I think it's a mark of weakness that he's unwilling with this
big, big lead he has, to say, sure I'll take on Bob Dole any day of
the week. Why shouldn't he?
   ``I may be a pushover. But I dare him to try it.''
   In a speech to the Chicago Council on Foreign Relations, Dole
referred to ``the point where presidential advisers are peddling
arms to the ayatollah while others hear no evil, see no evil,'' an
obvious reference to Bush.
   When Dole was asked why he didn't attack Bush more on
Iran-Contra, he said, ``If I hit him, I get Ronald Reagan first and
then they say, oh, oh, he's out there attacking Ronald Reagan.
   ``It's pretty hard to reach Bush _ except by telephone.''
</TEXT>
