<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson     03-14 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson: `We The People' Will Win</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL DE LA GARZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARBONDALE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Presidential candidate Jesse Jackson
told hundreds of supporters Monday that he would win the Illinois
primary, and not once did he mention rival Sen. Paul Simon, whose
hometown is only six miles away.
   ``On the eve of a significant breakthrough in politics in
Illinois ... with your help, we the people can win Illinois,''
Jackson told about 1,800 cheering backers, an equal mixture of
blacks and whites of all ages.
   ``I tell you, we the people will win.''
   According to a Chicago Tribune poll published Monday, Jackson is
in a virtual dead heat with fellow Democrat Simon.
   But Jackson didn't mention Simon in his hour-long speech at
Southern Illinois University at Carbondale.
   Instead, he reiterated that his candidacy represents a ``Rainbow
Coalition,'' people of all races and age groups. ``Our hope is
sweeping the country,'' he said.
   ``We're running a poor campaign with a rich message,'' Jackson
said. ``Stop drugs. Save jobs. Invest in our children. Peace in the
world.''
   Jackson told the crowd, on its feet through most of the speech,
that the flow of drugs and drug use is the No. 1 problem in the
United States.
   And he said that if elected president, he'd use the Armed Forces
to fight drug trafficking.
   ``I don't want communist insurgencies from the left, and drug
war lords from the right,'' said Jackson, eliciting cries of, ``Yes
sir,'' and, ``Amen.'' ``Let's make America better and keep America
strong.''
   Also, the Chicago civil rights leader promoted fair prices for
farmers, fair wages for workers, justice and peace.
   And Jackson hammered away at U.S. companies that do business
overseas, taking advantage of cheap labor while driving up
unemployment in this country.
   Jackson touted his managerial skills, noting that on the Super
Tuesday campaign he spent only $100,000 in advertising, compared
with his challengers who spent millions.
   ``Once again, little David versus the financial giants,'' he
said.
   ``I'm running the most cost-efficient campaign. I'm getting the
most return on my investment,'' said Jackson.
   The poll in Monday's Chicago Tribune found 32 percent of the
state's Democratic voters supported Jackson while 29 percent backed
Simon, and 20 percent favored Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis.
   The poll, taken of 500 Democrats likely to vote in Tuesday's
primary, has an error margin of plus or minus five percentage
points _ making the Jackson-Simon race a dead heat. A Sunday
Tribune poll had Simon ahead.
   Jackson reminded the crowd in Carbondale of the civil rights
struggle in the 1960s, and said a black man could be elected
president if he cared about all people, as he said he did.
   ``I know just because you're born in the slum doesn't mean the
slum is born in you, and you can rise above it,'' he said. ``Pull
your weight. Let your presence be felt tomorrow.''
</TEXT>
