<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Agriculture Minister John MacGregor on
Monday questioned whether President Reagan's administration means
to end farm subsidies entirely.
   The administration has said it wants them phased out
internationally by the year 2000. It also favors ``decoupling'' of
subsidies from the prices farmers get for crops.
   MacGregor told reporters that while he favored a substantial
reduction in subsidies worldwide, removing them altogether ``is I
think a debatable question because after all decoupling itself does
involve subsidies and decoupling is in the American negotiating
position.''
   Britain is one of the 12 countries in the European Economic
Community, the main U.S. negotiating partner on issues of world
farm trade. The other members are West Germany, France, Italy,
Ireland, Denmark, the Netherlands, Belgium, Luxembourg, Spain,
Portugal and Greece.
   Frans Andriessen of the Netherlands, who is in charge of
agriculture for the European Community's governing body, the
European Commission, told reporters recently the EEC disagrees with
the complete elimnination of subsidies, saying they are needed to
preserve small farms. He suggested that Congress and U.S. farmers
would not stand for complete elimination either.
   Others in the EEC have called the U.S. goal unrealistic.
MacGregor said Andriessen both have pointed to recent efforts by
the EEC to hold down spending on farm supports.
   According to a study published last Friday by Fred H. Sanderson,
formerly in charge of food policy at the State Department, in 1986
supporting farm prices cost consumers and taxpayers about $30
billion in this country and $63 billion in 10 of the Community
countries. Spain and Portugal are not included in those figures.
   MacGregor said he could not estimate the pace at which these
costs could be reduced.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
