<1ST_LINE>r p AM-BayhResidency     03-14 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bayh Residency,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Rules Bayh Meets Residency Requirement for Governor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG RICHARDSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State Evan Bayh meets a
constitutional residency requirement to be governor because he
always intended to return to Indiana during his temporary absences,
a judge ruled Monday.
   Circuit Judge Charles D. O'Connor said that Bayh has been a
lifelong resident of Indiana and didn't lose that residency when he
worked for a District of Columbia law firm in 1983 and 1984.
   Bayh, a 32-year-old Democrat who leads public opinion polls in
the governor's race, said he was ``gratified but not surprised'' by
the decision.
   But David F. McNamar, the special counsel for the GOP-controlled
State Election Board, said he plans to appeal the ruling to the
Indiana Supreme Court.
   ``I'm going to go ahead until someone tells me to stop,'' said
McNamar.
   O'Connor accepted the arguments presented during Friday's
one-day trial by Bayh's attorneys, who said Bayh's intention to
return to his home state meant that he met a five-year residency
requirement.
   McNamar said he wants to give the Supreme Court a chance to
consider his argument that the framers of the state constitution
wanted a potential governor to have been physically present for
five uninterrupted years before election.
   Bayh faces active opposition from former Kokomo Mayor Stephen J.
Daily in the May 3 Democratic primary. Senate Minority Leader Frank
L. O'Bannon also has filed for the primary.
   Lt. Gov. John M. Mutz is unopposed for the Republican nomination
to succeed Gov. Robert Orr, who is barred by the Constitution from
seeking a third straight term.
</TEXT>
