<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SovietShuttle     03-14 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Shuttle,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Launch Of Soviet Shuttle Possible This Week, Scientist Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet launch of an unmanned
spacecraft similar to the U.S. space shuttle could take place this
week, with a crew of two possibly heading into orbit six months
later, a knowledgeable expert says.
   Nick Johnson, an advisory scientist for Teledyne Brown
Engineering in Colorado Springs, Colo., quoted unidentified
European sources close to the Soviet space effort as saying the
launch could be Thursday or Saturday, The Huntsville Times reported
Sunday.
   ``The Soviets have said it is `imminent,''' said Johnson, who
keeps close tabs on the Soviet space program. ``The frequency of
reports is climbing very rapidly. It could be late next week. Like
any new vehicle, problems can crop up.''
   Johnson has written four books on the Soviet program and
publishes the annual Soviet Year in Space.
   Analysts say the first Soviet reusable shuttle flight will be
unmanned, with a totally computerized orbital flight, re-entry and
touchdown at a landing strip next to the launch site at the
Baikonur Cosmodrome in Central Asia, the newspaper said.
   Charles Vick, an employee of the Space and Rocket Center in
Huntsville and a part-time Soviet space analyst, said the Soviet
shuttle will be attached to the new heavy-lift rocket named
Energia, which underwent its first test flight last October.
   The Soviet shuttle strongly resembles NASA's shuttle, but while
the NASA craft has the main liquid fuel engines in the orbiter, the
Soviet shuttle main engines are attached to the external fuel tank,
Vick said.
   He said it has small maneuvering thrusters in the tail as well
as four jet engines that give it ``go-around'' capability on
landing. The U.S. shuttle glides down without power and must land
on the first try.
</TEXT>
