<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Calls Illinois Primary `National Referendum'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS CONRAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush, playing
down suggestions that he is closing in on the Republican
presidential nomination, said Monday ``the speculation has gotten
ahead of the story.''
   Bush's imposing lead in delegates, gained in Super Tuesday
primaries a week ago, left his opponents wondering where to turn to
revive their campaigns. Illinois may not be the place; polls
indicate voters in Tuesday's primary are strongly pro-Bush.
   ``I feel the speculation has gotten ahead of the story,'' he
told reporters aboard Air Force II as he headed for the state
capital.
   Bush said he wouldn't get caught up in ``a lot of premature
speculation about the future'' and whether his rivals would stay in
the race. But asked if he was surprised Dole said he would continue
his candidacy, Bush said, ``I'm not sure I understand what he's
doing.''
   Bush said the aftershock of his Super Tuesday sweep ``seems to
be more persuasive, have a heavier impact than we would have
predicted.''
   At a rally here, Bush said the Illinois primary will be a
``national referendum'' on his candidacy.
   ``I believe if I win it tomorrow, as I think I can, I really
think I will be the next president of the United States of
America,'' Bush told about 400 supporters in a firehouse at the
Capital Airport in Springfield.
   ``If I win convincingly, if I win to exceed expectations, you
can say that in the firehouse, right here, you met with, hopefully
voted for, the next president of the United States.''
   Recent polls show Bush with an overwhelming lead over his two
remaining Republican rivals, Dole and former television evangelist
Pat Robertson. Bush told supporters not to take comfort from his
standing in the polls because such surveys had been proven wrong
before.
   Bush also emphasized his ties to President Reagan.
   ``This is the presidency,'' he said. ``It is different than
anything else. I've stood side by side, through thick and through
thin, with a president for whom I have great respect, Ronald
Reagan.''
   Bush told reporters that he was not concerned about the
re-emergence of the Iran-Contra affair as criminal actions begin.
He said it had ``no relevance to what I'm doing.''
</TEXT>
