<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-88 1708EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RecyclingScavengers     03-14 0622</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Recycling Scavengers,0640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trash Scavengers Competing With Recycling Program For Trash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scavengers are competing with a pilot recycling
program by picking up newspapers and cans put out by residents for
special collection, officials say.
   ``It's easy pickings for these scavengers to come along and
supplement their income,'' says Patrick Barry, a recycling
consultant who designed the new program in Chicago's Beverly
neighborhood.
   ``We've got so many people putting (recyclable) material out
that it's easy to pick up a ton of newspaper in an hour,'' he said.
   He estimated the program was losing about $200 every seven days
because the scavengers were helping themselves to about four tons
of newspaper weekly.
   Barry said the neighborhood program's revenues vary from
week-to-week depending on the number of tons collected, hitting a
peak of about $1,400 per week. So, he estimated that the loss would
represent from 15 percent to 20 percent of weekly revenues.
   ``We've got two different recycling systems converging and it's
not bad from a recycling point of view,'' Barry said. ``But it cuts
into the money for the program.''
   Barry, who also is a spokesman for the Greater Chicago Recycling
Industry Council, an organization of 400 recycling businesses, said
scavengers operate all ovr the country.
   ``They're called alley entrepreneurs,'' he said. ``Some of these
people have developed shrewd operations. They're not always street
people. Some of them are sophisticated business people who are
making enough money for a bare living,'' Barry said.
   Chicago has an estimated 1,500 scavengers, he said. They make
anywhere from $30 to $150 a week sifting aluminimu cans, bottles
and newspaperes from the 9,000 tons of garbage produced daily in
the city, he said.
   The city's 20 privately run recycling centers pay an average of
40 cents a pound for aluminum and about 2 cents a pound for
newspaper or glass, he said.
   ``Some of (the scavengers) drive station wagons or pickup trucks
on routes to bars and restaurants to collect aluminum cans and
bottles,'' Barry said.
   Though scavengers work throughout Chicago, a group of six to
eight alley entrepreneurs is taking advantage of the five-week-old
recycling program in Beverly on the city's Southwest Side, he said.
   The Beverly program, a city pilot project and one of seven
neighborhood recycling programs, has attracted the most
participation from residents _ and the most attention from
scavengers, Barry said.
   The Resource Center, a private, non-profit recycling business
that runs the Beverly program, says about 60 percent of the
neighborhood's residents separate newspapers, aluminum cans and
other recyclable material from their garbage and leave it at the
curb in special blue boxes.
   Resource Center drivers pick up the trash daily, if they get
there before the alley entrepreneurs.
   The scavengers usually raid between 6 a.m. and 8 a.m., said Ken
Dunn, director of the Resource Center.
   ``One gentleman is a minister at a small church that doesn't
support him well,'' Dunn said. ``So he's devised a system to
recycle materials from his congregation and he also, in his free
time, collects out on the streets this way to supplement his
income.''
   Dunn said the Resource Center has hired some of the alley
entrepreneurs to drive recycling trucks, but others say the don't
want such a formal job.
   Barry said he hopes the City Council will adopt a proposed
ordinance that would make it illegal for unauthorized persons to
take waste set out for special recycling collections. The proposal
calls for fining violators from $100 to $500.
   ``Trash scavenging is going to be a problem in areas with large
low-income populations,'' Barry said. ``They're trying to make 10
bucks to make it through to tomorrow. You can't fault them for
that.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
