<HEAD>Defense Minister Meets U.S. Officials</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan on Monday wished West German
Defense Minister Manfred Woerner success in his future post as NATO
secretary general and thanked him for Bonn's contributions to the
alliance, a German official said.
   Woerner in July will become NATO's first German
secretary-general, succeeding Britain's Lord Carrington. He arrived
Sunday night for two days of meetings with U.S. officials,
lawmakers and the media.
   In addition to White House meetings with Reagan and his national
security adviser, Lt. Gen. Colin L. Powell, Woerner lunched with
Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci and also met with Secretary of
State George P. Shultz.
   Reagan and Woerner agreed that the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization summit at Brussels earlier this month was a success
and had strengthened the alliance, said a German official who
talked to a reporter on condition he not be named.
   The source also quoted Reagan as thanking Woerner for the share
of the common defense borne by West Germany and praising Bonn's
reliability as a defense partner.
   Before departing for Europe late Tuesday, Woerner planned talks
with several members of the Senate and meetings with reporters.
