<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HeadInjuryCenter     03-14 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Head Injury Center,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>University Establishes Nation's First Head Injury Research Center</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's first research center for head
injury patients adjusting to their disability will be established
at the State University of New York at Buffalo, school officials
said Monday.
   While four other U.S. centers treat ``traumatic brain injury''
patients in the hospital, university officials said their center is
unique because it will deal with the psychological, practical and
social problems of returning to normal life.
   ``Patients go back with their families, even if they didn't live
there before. And now what do you do?'' said Barry Willer,
co-director of the center and associate professor of psychiatry.
   The center will be funded primarily by a five-year, $3 million
grant from the U.S. Department of Education, with $2 million more
from funding of ongoing research.
   Recent advances in emergency medical care, stemming from
techniques developed largely during the Vietnam War, have increased
the number of those suffering from severe brain injuries, Willer
said. Years ago people with severe brain injuries would have died.
   The $5 million grant is part of a national push from the federal
government to help traumatic brain-injured patients, school
officials said.
   The injury to White House press secretary James Brady, who was
shot in the 1981 assassination attempt of Preside wouldn't have gone after
them,'' Hill
said of Pickens.
   Homestake Vice President Richard W. Stumbo took the bid
seriously.
   ``You always take him seriously,'' Stumbo said, adding he did
not know if Mesa's withdrawal was the end of its takeover efforts.
   Homestake holds interests in oil and natural gas and mines
uranium, silver and gold, as does Newmont Mining Corp., another
major gold producer targeted in an earlier, unsuccessful hostile
takeover bid by Pickens.
   New York-based Newmont was approached last year by Ivanhoe
Partners, a group led by Pickens, which made a $2 billion hostile
bid for control of the company.
   A Delaware court blocked the move in October when it upheld a
``market sweep'' in which Newmont's biggest shareholder, Britain's
Consolidated Gold Fields PLC, grabbed enough shares in a two-day
buying spree to raise its holdings to nearly 50 percent of Newmont
and thwart the hostile bid.
   Pickens' reputation as a corporate raider was made with
high-profile bids for several major oil companies in the early
1980s, including Gulf Corp., Phillips Petroleum Co. and Unocal Corp.
   Mesa launched hostile takeover attempts, then pocketed millions
of dollars in profits when some of the target companies either were
bought out by a higher bidder or repurchased their own stock.
