<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     03-14 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Temperatures Plunge Across Eastern Two-Thirds Of Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Temperatures typical of the middle of winter covered much of the
eastern two-thirds of the nation Monday, with record lows across
the South, and snow flakes fell as far south as Georgia.
   Afternoon temperatures were below freezing as far south as the
southern Appalachians, Kentucky, southern Missouri and northern
Kansas.
   Record lows included 18 at Abilene, Texas; 19 at Albuquerque,
N.M.; 26 at Dallas-Fort Worth; 17 at Midland, Texas; and 20 at San
Angelo, Texas. Shreveport, La., tied its record of 29. Abilene's
former record of 20 had been on the books since 1895.
   More record low temperatures were expected across the Gulf
states Tuesday and Wednesday mornings.
   A freeze warning was posted overnight across all of Georgia,
Alabama and Mississippi, and inland sections of northwestern
Florida.
   Snow flurries fell as far south as Atlanta while sections of the
Tennessee and Ohio valleys received a dusting of snow during the
morning.
   Snow flurries also were reported over the Appalachians, in parts
of Virginia and across southern New England.
   Moisture from the Great Lakes continued to produce lake effect
snow squalls across the southern shores of lakes Erie, Michigan and
Superior. Snow continued to fall over in extreme northern
Wisconsin, where total accumulation since Saturday could reach just
over 2 feet along the southern edge of Lake Superior.
   During the morning, northeastern Ohio reported 4 to 5 inches at
the town of Conneaut, the National Weather Service said. Five
inches of snow fell in sections of western New York.
   Another storm system began gathering strength in Canada, just
north of western Montana. Heavy snow began falling during the
morning in northwestern Montana and a section of northern Idaho and
snow was expected to spread across much of Montana and Wyoming by
Wednesday.
   Elsewhere, showers produced rain over extreme southern sections
of Florida.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 15
degrees at Alpena, Mich., to 77 at Palm Springs, Calif. The low for
the day was 20 degrees below zero at Chadron, Neb.
   For Tuesday, snow showers were forecast from the Great Lakes
across the upper Ohio Valley and the northern and central
Appalachians to New England. Snow also was forecast from northern
and central Rockies to the western borders of South Dakota and
Nebraska.
   Highs in the 20s or 30s were predicted from the northern and
central Atlantic Coast states across the Appalachians, the Ohio and
Tennessee valleys, the Great Lakes, and the northern halves of the
Mississippi Valley, Plains and Rockies; in the 60s in southern
Florida and across most of Texas and New Mexico; in the 60s or 70s
in much of Arizona, southern Nevada and California; a few 80s in
the desert Southwest; and in the 40s or 50s elsewhere.
</TEXT>
