<DOCNO> AP880314-0177 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-88 1750EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CDC-AIDSSurvey     03-14 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CDC-AIDS Survey,0535</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anonymous Tests To Seek AIDS Antibodies in Newborns in 30 Cities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newborn babies in 30 cities will be checked for
AIDS antibodies in anonymous tests the federal Centers for Disease
Control hopes will provide an early and broader look at who is
getting the disease.
   The tests, to be at selected hospitals, are part of a series of
surveys designed to eventually test 1.6 million Americans a year
for acquired immune deficiency syndrome.
   Blood samples from the newborns will be sent without names for
testing, CDC spokeswoman Gayle Lloyd said Monday. The study hopes
to determine the extent to which AIDS has penetrated heterosexual
women of child-bearing age, thought to be a low-risk group.
   Other programs, some of which are already under way, will test
blood samples from sexually transmitted disease clinics, drug
clinics, tuberculosis clinics, military recruits, job corps blood
donors and others, she said.
   Some tests will be routine and anonymous while others will be
voluntary with confidential results, she said.
   Early results are expected next fall, and the findings probably
will determine which programs are continued, she said. The CDC is
helping finance the programs at a cost of an estimated $47 million
for fiscal 1988.
   Some doctors say it violates ethics to test samples from known
people without permission and that getting permission would narrow
the population being tested.
   ``This is the least offensive way of getting a reliable general
population sample,'' Dr. Tim Dondero, chief of surveillance and
evaluation for the CDC's AIDS program.
   Others question whether it is ethical not to tell a patient
something he or she should know.
   ``To simply have the results and not have the ability to do
something with the results isn't a completely reasonable position,
is it?'' asked Dr. Wade Parks, a pediatrics professor at the Miami
School of Medicine.
   Only about half the babies who test positively carry the virus.
The others get a dose of antibody proteins from their infected
mothers. A positive antibodies test on a baby proves only that the
mother carries the virus.
   Similar tests on 30,000 newborns in Massachusetts revealed that
one of every 476 women giving birth there was infected. Not all who
carry the virus eventually develop AIDS.
   The newborns will be tested in 20 cities with a high AIDS
incidence. They are Atlanta, Baltimore, Boston, Chicago, Cleveland,
Dallas, Denver, Detroit, Houston, Jacksonville, Fla., Los Angeles,
Miami, New Orleans, New York, Newark, N.J., Richmond, Va., San
Francisco, San Juan, Puerto Rico, St. Louis, and Washington.
   Tests also will be done in the low-incidence cities of
Albuquerque, N.M., Honolulu, Kansas City, Mo., Memphis, Tennessee,
Minneapolis, New Haven, Conn., Phoenix, Ariz., Rochester, N.Y.,
Salt Lake City and Seattle.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome attacks the body's ability
to ward off disease. It is transmitted through sexual contact with
an infected person, shared hypodermic needles and blood
transfusions, and can be passed from mothers to their offspring.
There is no known cure.
   Since June, 1981 there have been 55,167 cases counted in the
United States and 30,932 patients have died.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880314-0178 </DOCNO>
