<1ST_LINE>u a AM-KellerResigns     03-14 0632</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Keller Resigns,0656</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>University Officials Hope To Name Interim President This Week</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MP3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY R. SANDOK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   University of Minnesota officials said Monday
they hope to quickly name an interim president to replace Kenneth
Keller, who resigned amid controversy about the cost of renovating
his official residence and campus office.
   Meanwhile, Gov. Rudy Perpich withdrew his request for an
appropriation of $23.1 million to fund Keller's program, called
``Commitment to Focus,'' to raise standards at the university while
cutting undergraduate enrollment.
   Perpich said support for the funding had dwindled because of the
controversy over the renovations.
   Keller, president of the university for three years, met
privately with Perpich before calling a news conference late Sunday
night to announce his departure.
   ``At no time did I discuss that he resign, absolutely not,''
Perpich told a news conference.
   However, Perpich said he told Keller he had two options:
``Either leave, or you have a very dramatic plan...to continue with
Focus and get the university back on track.'''
   Perpich said the Board of Regents should consider using a
portion of a $53 million reserve fund to meet the immediate needs
of the quality-improvement program, which the governor said he
continues to support.
   The existence of the reserve fund was revealed last week as a
result of audits ordered after news reports raised questions about
the renovations.
   News reports said that $1.5 million had been spent to renovate
Eastcliff, the university president's mansion, and $200,000 was
spent remodeling Keller's campus office suite.
   The regents never gave formal approval for the mansion
renovation, which was orginally supposed to cost $400,000, the
legislative auditor's office said.
   Among the most embarrassing expenditures were those for a
mahogany desk and credenza for Keller's office that the legislative
auditor said cost $17,445. Keller has offered to pay for the office
furniture.
   The university reportedly met the cost overruns by dipping into
the reserve fund, which included profits from book stores, parking
lots and temporary investments. The audits released last week did
not question the legality of the fund, but criticized accounting
and reporting procedures.
   Earlier Monday, David Lebedoff, chairman of the 12-member Board
of Regents, said he hoped an interim president could be named at a
special meeting Wednesday. Selection of a permanent replacement
could take months.
   Lebedoff, who headed a search committee that recommended Keller
to be president of the 55,000-student school, pledged continued
support for Commitment to Focus.
   ``All of my life I will be proud that we selected a president
who came up with a plan to make this university even better,''
Lebedoff said.
   Some lawmakers had criticizeed the Focus program as smacking of
elitism, and the $23.1 million proposed by Perpich for the program
was $12 million less than the university had requested.
   Legedoff said the regents should have demanded an accounting of
the remodeling projects, but added that under existing guidelines
the spending should have been reported.
   Keller, 53, apologized in his resignation statement Sunday.
   ``Over the past few weeks, you and I have lived with stories
about Eastcliff renovations and repairs,'' Keller said.
   ``The stories have not been good ones,'' he said. ``I bear a key
responsibility for it. ... I am profoundly embarrassed and
profoundly sorry for it.''
   The legislative auditor's report said the involvement of Keller
and his wife, university attorney Bonita Sindelir, in the
renovation led to some of the Spending on the mansion was revealed
in news media reports in early February. Keller annoyed some
legislators by going to Hawaii on a vacation instead of being
available to answer questions about the remodeling.
   Keller, a native of New York City, came to the university in
1964 as an assistant professor in chemical engineering and
materials science, and became a department head in 1979.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
