<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDSTest     03-14 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Test,0435</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Minnesota May Test Students For Understanding Of AIDS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Board of Education is studying
a proposal to test students about their understanding of AIDS
prevention, but the Legislature is considering action to kill the
program.
   ``There are states doing innovative things in the area of AIDS
education, but Minnesota is the first I've heard about that is
trying to mandate assessment this way,'' said Katherine Fraser,
co-director of the AIDS Education Project of the National
Association of State Boards of Education.
   ``It's a good idea because it involves an educational program
aimed at changing behavior and that's what is really needed to
fight AIDS,'' she said.
   Fraser commented last week after the state Board of Education
took the first steps toward requiring students in the sixth and
10th grades to be tested on their knowledge of AIDS prevention.
   The proposal also would require school districts to teach
courses on prevention of AIDS and other communicable diseases in
kindergarten through the senior year of high school.
   The proposal still faces public hearings and the scrutiny of an
administrative law judge before taking effect. Department of
Education officials say the process will take about 10 months to a
year and cost $10,000 to $20,000.
   A bill pending in the Legislature which would block board's plan
was passed unanimously by the School Finance Division of the House
Education Committee Friday and will be discussed Wednesday before
the full House Education Committee.
   ``We disagree on mandating. We think school districts in
Minnesota have good progams in place, and we'd like to continue to
help them do that. Taking the time and money to develop a rule
might upset this progress,'' said state Rep. Bob McEachern, sponsor
of the move to block the board's proposal.
   Fraser says the school boards association backs mandatory AIDS
education because it means local school boards do not have to face
as much controversy from people offended by discussion of AIDS.
``They can just say, `It's the requirement. Let's work on how we
can meet it,''' she said.
   According to the Minnesota Department of Education, about 386
Minnesota school districts say they have some kind of AIDS
education, but provide no information on what kind. That means
about 50 districts still don't have any type of AIDS education.
   Board member John Plocker, who prefers a voluntary approach,
said the board still wants local school boards to shape their
programs. ``We're just telling them they have to do it. There's
still a lot of latitude,'' he said.
</TEXT>
