<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Murph'sMinistry     03-14 0532</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Murph's Ministry,0549</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Infamous Criminal Now Preaches Word of God</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jack Roland Murphy was always successful: a
violin player with the Pittsburgh Symphony, a tennis star in
college, onetime national surfing champion.
   Later, he became famous as Murph the Surf: playboy, jewel thief,
murderer. Now, Murphy calls himself a ``frontline Christian
soldier,'' an ex-convict who has ``dedicated the rest of my life to
the Lord.''
   ``I've got what they call chain-gang religion, jailhouse
religion, and it's easy for people to scoff at it,'' Murphy said
during a recent interview at The Bridge, a prison work-release
facility in Orlando.
   Murphy, 50, said he has traveled more than 100,000 miles to
counsel prisoners and has given his Christian testimony at hundreds
of schools and churches.
   He was paroled in November 1986 after 19 years in Florida
prisons. One of the conditions of his release was that he spend his
time helping others by preaching and teaching.
   Many are watching and judging, he knows.
   They remember that it was Murphy who stole the Star of India, a
563-carat sapphire, in a spectacular heist from the Museum of
Natural History in New York in 1964, along with a 100-carat ruby
and 20 other gems.
   They remember too that he was convicted of murder in the 1967
slayings of two women whose bludgeoned bodies were found dumped in
Whiskey Creek, a tidal waterway between Miami and Fort Lauderdale.
Prosecutors said the two women were killed over $488,000 worth of
negotiable securities they stole from their employer.
   ``There will always be critics or skeptics who don't believe in
born-again experiences,'' Murphy said. ``But I guarantee it happens
and has happened to me.''
   Those he works with believe in him and his work.
   ``His goal is to help prisoners come to Christ,'' said the Rev.
George Crossley. ``He wants to help fight crime and wage war on
drugs. I believe churchgoers should support Jack Murphy's
ministry.''
   Vernon Rainwater, head of Central Florida's Youth for Christ,
echoes Crossley's statements.
   ``I've heard nothing but real good reports on Jack Murphy since
he has been paroled,'' Rainwater said. ``He has been a good
representative of the Christian community.''
   Murphy said he is just starting.
   ``I have a number of mentors who have been down the road before.
Good Christians. Prison chaplains. People who care about people.
   ``Jesus told us to represent him in Jerusalem. My Jerusalem is
in the jails. . . The jails are the places I least want to be. But
it's there I believe God wants me to be. It is where he allowed me
to grow up.''
   Murphy married Catherine Collins, who visited him in prison for
12 years, last December. She frequently travels with him on
speaking engagements. He is sometimes paid by groups that ask him
to speak. Other income comes from the sale of paintings he did
while in prison.
   ``I don't have wealth. I don't have material things. I go from
month to month, but God provides,'' he said. ``I never could have
imagined the peace, quality and joy of such a life.''
   To those who doubt or scoff, Murphy said, ``If you don't believe
me, just watch me.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
