<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Nicaragua     03-14 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Nicaragua,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Sign Agreement to Cooperate with Sandinistas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials of the Soviet Communist Party met Monday
with representatives of the Nicaraguan government and signed an
agreement of cooperation, the Tass news agency reported.
   It did not describe the agreement.
   The report said the Sandinistas stressed their determination to
defend their government against U.S.-backed rebels, known as
Contras, and to seek political settlement of the Central American
conflicts.
   Tass said the Soviets ``declared invariable support for the
struggle of Nicaragua for freedom and independence, its
constructive moves, as well as efforts of the Contadora group and
other Latin American countries aimed at a peaceful settlement of
the conflicts in the region, with strict observance of the right of
any nation to its own social and political choice.''
   The Contadora group was formed in January 1983 by Mexico,
Venezuela, Colombia and Panama at a meeting on Panama's Contadora
Island with the aim of resolving armed conflicts in Central America.
   Tass said the Sandinista delegation met with Anatoly F.
Dobrynin, a secretary of the Communist Party Central Committee and
a former ambassador to the United States, and Karen Brutents,
deputy head of the Central Committee's international department.
   Tass said the Sandinista delegation was led by Bayardo Arce,
deputy coordinator of the ruling Sandinista National Liberation
Front.
   It gave no other details of the meeting.
</TEXT>
