<2ND_LINE>AM-Gore, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0648,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gore Says He'll Battle Dukakis, Jackson in Industrial Midwest</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds 3 grafs on computer research</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Albert Gore Jr., campaigning against long
odds in Illinois' Democratic primary, looked ahead Monday to the
rest of the Northern industrial states and said he would ``compete
everywhere and look for an opportunity to punch through'' with a
victory.
   The Tennessee senator flew around Illinois in a final day of
campaigning before Tuesday's primary, repeatedly describing himself
as the alternative to rivals Michael Dukakis, Paul Simon and Jesse
Jackson. He said he was encouraged about prospects in the state
despite polls showing him stuck in single digits behind the others
in Illinois.
   ``The polls have been wrong quite frequently in this race
because the voters are thinking for themselves,'' Gore said at an
airport news conference in Peoria.
   Gore began his day at a factory gate in Rockford, Ill., where he
stood coatless in a light snowfall and greeted workers during a
shift change before flying to Peoria, Springfield and Champaign.
   Speaking to reporters aboard his chartered airplane, Gore said
that regardless of the Illinois outcome he saw the race for the
Democratic nomination as a battle between himself, Jackson and
Dukakis that would be fought out in industrial states during the
spring.
   ``We've got a whole series of contests between now and June 7,''
Gore said. ``We're going to compete in all of them.''
   Needing a victory to to demonstrate appeal outside his native
South, Gore said he saw ``a number of opportunities for a win,''
naming Connecticut, Ohio, Pennsylvania, New York and Indiana.
   ``We're looking at the primary schedule,'' Gore said. ``We're
going to compete everywhere and look for an opportunity to punch
through.''
   Gore strategist Larry Harrington said the campaign's aim in
Illinois was to be ``in the fray.'' He said the campaign had bought
``a decent or modest amount'' of television airtime in Illinois,
and did not dispute estimates putting the figure in the $200,000 to
$300,000 range over the past week.
   ``I think we're going to do better than people expect here,''
Gore said.
   ``I think there are an awful lot of voters here in Illinois who
want an alternative to the kind of approach offered by Michael
Dukakis and Paul Simon and Jesse Jackson,'' Gore said. ``I offer a
different kind of approach.''
   In Springfield, he said each of those three rivals represents
``the same old formula'' that has led the Democratic Party to lose
four out of the past five presidential elections.
   In Peoria, home of the Caterpillar tractor manufacturing
company, Gore said the Reagan administration ``has not been willing
to use the tools'' available under current trade laws to ensure
fairness by foreign competitors.
   He also said that ``a majority of the problems identified in the
trade deficit are here at home,'' citing massive federal borrowing
and saying there was a need to improve education and economic
policy.
   In Springfield, Gore toured a small homeless shelter and visited
with a mother and her baby who live there, underscoring his call
for more federal assistance to the homeless. He said much of the
increase in homelessness was due to ``slashes'' in housing programs
under the Reagan administration.
   At an American Legion post in Chicago Sunday night and again in
Peoria on Monday, Gore, a Vietnam veteran, faced questions about
men left behind after that war. He drew praise from other Vietnam
veterans when he promised to ``pursue to the ends of this earth''
any remaining leads on such men.
   At the University of Illinois in Champaign, Gore stood before a
Cray super computer and accused the Reagan administration of ``the
starvation of super computing'' through denial of federal support
for civilian computer research.
   He called for more federal money to support development of
computer technology and the linking of super computers _ systems
capable of performing millions of computations in an instant _ into
a nationwide network.
   Pointing to one of the rare super computers, Gore referred to
the confused Democratic presidential race and said: ``If there's a
brokered convention, this is a possibility.''
</TEXT>
