<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Jackson-Delegates     03-14 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson-Delegates,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Aims To Pick Up Uncounted Delegates; Jackson Closing In</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson is within striking distance of
leading the Democratic race for national convention delegates, but
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, the leader in the field, is
planning to pick up delegates from yet uncounted caucuses.
   Jackson, who is favored in some polls to win his home state of
Illinois in Tuesday's primary, could still wind up losing when the
delegate prize is divided.
   Dukakis led the Democratic presidential field with 462.5
delegates, followed by Jackson with 423.55. But Dukakis' campaign
said he stands to gain at least another 100 delegates when caucus
results from Texas, Washington and Minnesota are finally tabulated.
   Meanwhile, Jackson's campaign said that the rules in Illinois do
not favor him in picking up many delegates from his home state.
   ``If we get as high a percentage of delegates as we do the
popular vote that would be a smashing success,'' said Steve Cobble,
who monitors delegate selection for the Jackson campaign.
   Illinois holds a direct-election primary in which slates of
delegates are elected from the ballot. Presidential candidates are
also listed on a ``beauty contest'' section of the ballot, but the
results have no effect on picking the delegates.
   The Jackson campaign does not expect to pick up the nearly 40
delegates needed to overtake Dukakis in the national count, Cobble
said. At stake in Illinois are 173 delegates.
   Two recent polls show favorite sons, Jackson and Illinois Sen.
Paul Simon, neck-and-neck in the contest. In a Chicago Tribune
poll, Jackson edged Simon 32 percent to 29 percent, while Simon
held a slim lead over Jackson _ 39 percent to 34 percent _ in an
ABC News-Washington Post poll.
   But the percentages separating them were within the polls'
potential margins of sampling error.
   Simon, who needs to win in his home state to keep his political
hopes alive, had 35.5 delegates. Sen. Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee
was third behind Dukakis and Jackson with 352.8 delegates, while
Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt was in fourth place with 145
delegates.
   Uncommitted delegates totaled 275.65 delegates.
</TEXT>
