<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CampaignCoverage     03-14 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Campaign Coverage,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Says Jackson Gets Best TV Coverage, Robertson Gets Most
Negative</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A study of network evening newscasts from Jan.
1 through Super Tuesday March 8 says Democrat Jesse Jackson got the
best television coverage and Republican Pat Robertson got the most
negative.
   The Center for Media and Public Affairs, a non-partisan study
group, said it studied 532 news items involving the election and
found:
   _Evaluations of every major candidate, based on clearly positive
or negative statements from all sources relating to character, job
performance, campaign performance or issue stands, became more
negative after the New Hampshire primary Feb. 16.
   _Jackson suffered the least. Telecast comments involving him
were favorable 74 percent of the time, compared with 90 percent
this year before New Hampshire. He also nearly tripled his share of
the Democrats' coverage, from 9 percent before New Hampshire to 26
percent in the weeks leading up to Super Tuesday, the big round of
primaries and caucuses.
   _Robertson dropped from 70 percent positive evaluations before
New Hampshire to 33 percent after it. Comments about his prospects
also became more negative.
   _Republican George Bush got his best attention in the week
before the New Hampshire primary _ 66 percent of the comments were
favorable. Since then, his favorable coverage percentage has
dropped to 44 percent.
   The analysts also said there have been four stories on the
campaign horse race for every story on policy issues since the Feb.
8 Iowa caucuses and the issues most frequently mentioned are taxes
and trade.
</TEXT>
