<1ST_LINE>r w AM-EnergyNomination     03-14 0450</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Energy Nomination,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>DOE Nominee Once Was Asked To Resign AID Post Over Passing
Documents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man nominated to head the Economic
Regulatory Administration was asked to leave another government
agency after providing documents to a friend who was seeking a
contract, according to Rep. John Dingell.
   Dingell, D-Mich., chairman of the House Energy and Commerce
Committee, has written Energy Secretary John Herrington asking the
secretary to relieve the nominee in question, Chandler Van Orman,
as acting head of the ERA and that Van Orman ``refrain from
participating in any sensitive matters of any kind.''
   Van Orman was traveling Monday and could not be reached, his
office said. Enegery Department spokesman Doug Elmets said: ``We
support Chandler Van Orman. We feel that he is well qualified and
we plan to stand behind him. We do not feel that there are
unanswered allegations that would prevent him from getting this
job.''
   Dingell earlier asked the Senate Energy Committee to hold up Van
Orman's confirmation until the General Accounting Office could
report on the circumstances of Van Orman's replacement of Marshall
Staunton as head of the Economic Regulatory Administration. The ERA
seeks refunds from overcharges when crude oil was under price
controls.
   Dingell wrote Herrington that the GAO investigation was still
under way, but GAO officials had briefed him that in February 1983,
the head of the Agency for International Development ``asked for
and received Van Orman's resignation.''
   Van Orman, according to Dingell's account, had given documents
to a friend seeking a $450,000 contract to prepare for an
international conference on a new way to cure cholera and related
disorders, oral rehydration therapy.
   The contract was awarded but later terminated ``at some cost to
the government,'' Dingell wrote Herrington.
   A memo on the stationery of the AID general counsel said it did
not appear that Van Orman helped his friend get the contract, and
he had not disclosed any classified information. The memo, which
was obtained by The Associated Press, said the evidence assembled
by the AID inspector general ``does not indicate that any statutory
violation occurred,'' and Van Orman had not disclosed classified
information, but had provided documents on at least one other
occasion.
   AID declined to take further action after Van Orman resigned.
   The AID memo was disclosed in a letter Dingell wrote the GAO
with further questions about Van Orman.
   Van Orman had served as an advance man for trips by Vice
President Bush and President Reagan when he was appointed deputy
ERA administrator in August. He was nominated for the
administrator's job in September, but did not assume the post as
acting administrator until Staunton left in December.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
