<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     03-14 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0544</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brite and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALY CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Julie and Guy Garner's boat
disappeared, but it found its way home the next day.
   As Ms. Garner was listening to her emergency radio Sunday
morning, her ears perked up when she overheard someone on the radio
``call for assistance from a boat named `Tradition.'''
   Seems that ``Tradition,'' the Garners' 36-foot cabin cruiser,
had disappeared the previous evening from a dock in San Francisco
Bay while the couple and friends were having dinner in San
Francisco. They were afraid that vandals had untied the lines and
the boat was heading out to sea.
   As she listened to the radio the next morning, she said, ``The
man aboard was saying something about waking up on the boat and not
knowing how he got on board or where he was.''
   There was another surprise in store for Ms. Garner when she
turned on a scanning device that can pinpoint the boat's position.
   It turned out to be in the ocean right near their beachside Daly
City home, about 10 miles from where it was docked when it
disappeared.
   ``We looked out and saw our boat sailing about a mile out,'' she
said.
   The Coast Guard dispatched a crew, which intercepted the boat.
San Francisco police Sgt. Jerry Senkir said Edward Thomas James,
26, was taken into custody for investigation of grand theft.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KILKENNY, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of this village, settled 131
years ago by Irish homesteaders, celebrated St. Patrick's Day a bit
early with their decidedly un-Irish tradition: toilet bowl racing.
   To the cheers of 100 onlookers Sunday, two-time champion Darrell
Knish downed a cup of beer and jumped on a bowl perched on plywood
and bicycle tires.
   Teammates whisked him down the block toward a second beer
sitting on the snow-covered pavement, which he chugged before
racing back up the hill ahead of a competitor.
   His trophy? A toilet seat cover with the names of the winning
team members scrawled on the back.
   Kilkenny, population 180, swelled by several hundred Sunday as
locals and visitors sprayed their hair green, painted shamrocks on
buildings, and gulped homemade mulligan stew and beer.
   ``If you're going to pick a town to go to, this is it,'' said
Kevin Taaffe of Richfield, who has come to the last four St.
Patrick's Day celebrations in Kilkenny.
   ``If you don't know anybody, you'll know them before you leave
town,'' said Gene Mach, son of the mayor.
   Dana Begley, 36, was quick to learn that. She passed through the
town a while ago on a trip and liked it so much that she and her
children moved here from southern California.
   Kilkenny was all-Irish at its founding in 1857, but mobility and
marriage have gradually reduced the ranks.
   ``There are a few around here who are 100 percent Irish, but not
many,'' said Ann Sheridan, 62, one of the 100 percenters. ``But
even if the people aren't Irish, on St. Patrick's Day, they're all
Irish.''
   As put by Donald Kewatt, tapping his foot to the beat in the
Lions Den: ``I'm German, but I help 'em celebrate.''
</TEXT>
