<HEAD>Former Reagan Aide's Sentencing Postponed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sentencing of former presidential aide Lyn
Nofziger was postponed Monday from March 25 until April 8 to give
defense lawyers more time to study a report being prepared by the
federal probation office.
   U.S. District Judge Thomas A. Flannery granted the defense
request to postpone the sentencing. The request was not opposed by
independent counsel James C. McKay.
   Nofziger, who was White House political director from 1981 until
early 1982, was convicted last month of three counts of illegally
lobbying former colleagues in the Reagan administration on behalf
of private clients.
   He faces a potential two-year prison term and a $10,000 fine on
each count.
