<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HeroinArrest     03-14 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Heroin Arrest,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Feds Nab Alleged Heroin Kingpin</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Asian businessman identified as the Drug
Enforcement Agency's No. 1 heroin target has been arrested and
charged with importing 1,000 pounds of heroin from Southeast Asia
over three years, authorities said Monday.
   The drug ring run by Kon Yu-Leung Kon was much larger than those
in such well-known heroin smuggling cases as the French Connection
or the Pizza Connection, said Robert Stutman, head of the DEA's New
York office.
   The French Connection involved 70 pounds of heroin, the Pizza
Connection about 200, he said.
   Heroin trafficking ``is now controlled by Chinese ethnic groups
that are bringing in vast amounts to the United States, in amounts
far more than any of us who have been professionals in the field
ever thought possible,'' Stutman said.
   U.S. Attorney Andrew Maloney said federal authorities lured Kon
to New York, where he was arrested Sunday night in front of the New
York Hilton Hotel. The 44-year-old Kon was charged under an
indictment handed up in December.
   Maloney refused to give details of the arrest.
   Stutman said that although Kon is charged with importing 1,000
pounds of heroin, it is believed he is responsible for bringing in
twice that amount.
   The heroin was smuggled into the country from 1984 to 1987
through various means, including suitcases and shipments of vases,
ice buckets, T-shirts and wall plaques, said Maloney.
   Couriers then carried millions of dollars in proceeds back to
Hong Kong to be laundered, authorities said. Kon allegedly used $20
million to buy commercial real estate in the New York area and San
Francisco.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Catherine Palmer said Kon, who was born
in China and later moved to Hong Kong, had numerous businesses in
Asia and the United States, including several fur companies.
   Kon had eluded arrest by becoming ``an international gypsy'' and
moving between Thailand, Taiwan, Japan and Manila, Maloney said.
Kon had at least six phony passports, Palmer said.
   Authorities confiscated 570 pounds of heroin alleged to have
been imported by Kon's organization in several seizures over the
years, Stutman said.
   Authorities also arrested John Routollo, a former New York City
police officer, at his Mountclair, N.J., home Sunday night.
   Routollo, 50, was allegedly responsible for picking up the
heroin in New York, usually at the Hilton, for distribution in the
United States. He gathered the drug money and arranged its return
to Hong Kong, according to authorities.
   Routollo worked with Kon before leaving the force in 1981,
authorities said. Maloney said Routollo supplied weapons to Kon's
organization through his position in the Police Department's office
of pistols and licenses.
</TEXT>
