<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Trade     03-14 0514</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trade,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senators To House: Drop Gephardt Trade Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate negotiators on Monday called on their
House counterparts to drop Democratic presidential hopeful Richard
A. Gephardt's heavily debated amendment from their sweeping trade
bill.
   ``We decided to stick with our own Super 301 plan and to oppose
the Gephardt amendment,'' Finance Committee Chairman Lloyd Bentsen,
D-Texas, said as he emerged from a meeting of Senate conference
committee members.
   The move, which came on a voice vote in the closed-door meeting,
could set the stage for the gradual erasure of the Gephardt
amendment if the House presents a compromise counteroffer to the
Senate that makes a substantial change in the wording.
   However, Gephardt spokesman Mark Johnson said that the Senate's
action represents ``nothing new.''
   ``We've known the Senate's bargaining position for eight
months,'' he said. ``It in no way reflects a decision by the
conference committee. It's merely an opening bargaining position.
We're confident that whatever emerges from conference will be new,
forceful legislation to open foreign markets. And clearly the
Gephardt amendment paved the way.''
   Gephardt's plan would require negotiations to reduce Japanese
and other nations' ``excess and unwarranted'' trade surpluses with
the United States. If that failed, it would prescribe presidential
action to cut the surpluses by 10 percent a year.
   Such a move could include tariffs or import quotas on Japanese
goods imported into the United States. But the president could
refuse to act, either to uphold ``national economic security'' or
if the other country were wrestling with a serious international
debt problem.
   The Reagan administration has criticized the Gephardt plan as
being likely to hurt consumers, cost more jobs than it would save
and invite retaliation against U.S. exports.
   The administration also has been critical of the ``Super 301''
provision that the Senate is pushing.
   ``Super 301,'' named for the section of the Trade Act calling
for retaliation against overseas barriers to U.S. exports, would
require the president to act to eliminate all of the unfair foreign
trade barriers listed on an inventory to be drawn up by the U.S.
trade representative.
   The Senate's offer was not immediately sent to the House.
   Instead, the senators planned to return to the bargaining table
on Tuesday and fashion additional provisions involving steps to
combat ``dumping,'' or selling foreign-made products in world
markets at prices lower than those in home markets.
   They also planned to work on provisions involving countervailing
duties, or tariffs that are imposed to offset the price advantage
that some foreign-mad products get from export subsidies in their
home countries.
   The senators also eased some of the provisions in the portion of
their 1,000-page bill calling for retaliation against foreign
unfair trade practices.
   They moved to expand from seven months to 12 months the time for
the president to make a determination as to whether a foreign trade
practice should be considered unfair. And they acted to remove some
of the specific reasons for retaliation from the bill itself and
put them instead in a report that will accompany the legislation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880314-0194 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-88 1839EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Gorbachev 2ndLd-Writethru aa0675 03-14 0805</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gorbachev, 2nd Ld - Writethru, aa0675,0831</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Says Soviet Ethnic Minorities Don't Challenge Government</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-14 UPDATE with talks among leaders, added
comments. Picks up 11th graf pvs, During a ... with minor editing
to conform and trim. Adds one graf at end Soviet comment on
Yugoslav economic reform.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEL3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev
said Monday that ethnic minorities stirring unrest in his vast
country are raising old grievances but not challenging the
authority of the Communist government.
   Soon after arriving on Monday in Yugoslavia, which has a long
history of its own nationality problems, Gorbachev was asked about
recent demonstrations and ethnic riots in the southern Soviet
republics.
   ``Show me the country in which there are no such problems,'' the
Communist Party chief replied. ``If you show me, I will travel
there right away, without stopping in Moscow on return from
Yugoslavia.''
   Gorbachev, who is on a five-day visit, is the first Soviet
leader to visit Yugoslavia since the death of President Josip Broz
Tito in May 1980.
   Referring to recent demonstrations in Yerevan, capital of Soviet
Armenia, and rioting in neighboring Azerbaijan between ethnic
Azerbaijanis and Armenians that left more than 30 people dead,
Gorbachev said the problems had been brewing for a long time.
   He acknowledged some tensions between ethnic groups have been
neglected in his nation of more than 100 nationalities, but said
the protesters were not questioning socialist rule or ``challenging
our political line.''
   The remarks were his first personal comments on the situation in
the Soviet south, although a statement in his name was read to
Yerevan demonstrators.
   Gorbachev plans to visit Slovenia, Yugoslavia's northernmost
republic, and the Croatian city of Dubrovnik.
   Missing from his itinerary is Kosovo, which is beset by strife
between the Albanian majority and Slavic minority.
   Late Monday, after touring memorials and monuments, Gorbachev
began talks with President Lazar Mojsov and Bosko Krunic, head of
Yugoslavia's party.
   Yugoslavia's assistant foreign minister, Ilija Djukic, briefed
reporters later. He said national minorities were not raised as a
separate topic, but that in a general discussion on social
developments, Gorbachev stressed the difficulty of resolving ethnic
problems.
   Djukic quoted Gorbachev as saying, ``There are no problems that
could be solved once and for all, that conditions change, that
everything requires improvement.''
   Gorbachev and his wife, Raisa, set an informal pace Monday as
they took their first look at a Communist country that has
implemented some of the economic reforms Gorbachev proposes _ but
with mixed results.
   The Soviet leader made an unscheduled stop in a busy downtown
square and left his armored limousine to shake hands and chat with
pedestrians. A witness said he picked up a child and gave it a kiss.
   Mrs. Gorbachev tried to take a walk through downtown Belgrade
but was nearly overwhelmed by several hundred people pressing for a
closer look.
   The Gorbachevs placed a wreath at the Tomb of the Unknown
Soldier atop Mount Avala, just outside Belgrade.
   On the way down the mountain, their limousine made an
unannounced stop at a monument in the shape of a broken airplane
wing that marks the site of a Soviet air disaster. On Oct. 19,
1964, a plane carrying former Soviet soldiers who helped liberate
Belgrade 20 years earlier crashed there, killing all aboard.
   The Gorbachevs left two small bouquets.
   At one point, a reporter asked Gorbachev if there was progress
at the Geneva talks on the Afghan conflict. With a smile, he said
``There is,'' and ``There will be,'' but did not elaborate.
   He has pledged to withdraw all Soviet troops from Afghanistan _
estimated at 115,000 _ in less than a year if the Geneva talks
produce a settlement.
   Gorbachev said he came to Belgrade to give ``new impulses'' to
the friendly relationship between the countries.
   Yugoslav officials have said a principal topic of discussion
will be Yugoslavia's economic system of ``self-managed, market
socialism.''
   It also allows for private initiative along lines similar to
cooperative enterprises that have sprung up in the Soviet Union
under new laws.
   The Yugoslav system was developed by Tito, who broke with the
Kremlin in 1948 on ideological grounds and pursued his own
communist course. While maintaining relations with the Soviet
Union, he was a founder of the non-aligned movement and developed
ties with the West.
   Yugoslavia enjoyed a long economic boom, but has encountered
hard times in recent years.
   Today, the government and party are struggling with annual
inflation of 170 percent, 15 percent unemployment and a $20 billion
debt to Western creditors.
   Gorbachev is trying to end stagnation in the Soviet economy by
encouraging more accountability by management and more local
control of production.
   Soviet Deputy Foreign Minister Vadim Loginov told reporters the
Soviets are studying Yugoslav economic reforms.
</TEXT>
