<1ST_LINE>u a AM-LouisianaGovernor     03-14 0552</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Louisiana Governor,0571</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Roemer Becomes 51st Louisiana Governor</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY COATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charles E. ``Buddy'' Roemer III, a
self-styled reformer who toppled a political legend, was
inaugurated governor Monday and challenged the people of Louisiana
to help him ``clean up our politics.''
   The 44-year-old Democrat, who won a runoff concession from Gov.
Edwin Edwards on Oct. 24, took the oath of office from former Sen.
Russell Long, the son of legendary Gov. Huey Long, shortly after
noon on the Capitol steps.
   He takes office amid fiscal crisis, with an accumulated budget
deficit and cash shortfall of as much as $1.2 billion, much of it
due to the oil patch depression.
   ``Do we have the character to clean up our politics, to free our
political leadership from the stranglehold of the special
interests?'' asked the former four-term congressman. ``From the
governor's mansion to the Pardon Board, from the Legislature to the
local government, I say we do.''
   ``I will lead, but I need you to pick me up when I fall,'' said
Roemer, Louisiana's 51st governor. ``I need you to stand beside me
when the special interests attack.''
   Edwards, who served as governor from 1972 to 1980 and returned
for a third term in 1984, was occupied for much of his last
administration defending himself successfully against federal
racketeering charges.
   Roemer, during an inaugural address to some 5,000 people, did
not cite the usual litany of Louisiana's problems, including high
unemployment, teen pregnancies, high school dropouts and
nearly-empty state coffers.
   Roemer was interrupted frequently by applause, Edwards included.
   ``I'm going hunting tomorrow,'' Edwards told reporters. ``It's
his now.''
   The state's unemployment rate hit 12 percent in January, one of
the highest in the nation, due primarily to the long downturn in
the oil and gas industry.
   Louisiana's schools are under challenge, business interests are
demanding an overhaul of the tax system to attract industry and
environmental groups are calling for tougher regulations to protect
the air and water.
   Roemer campaigned on calls for major reforms in those areas and
others, including campaign financing. He said recently that the
challenge is unlike that facing any other Louisiana governor.
   ``I've got to do both to get us out of debt and build _
education development, economic development, better environment.
It's going to be a difficult and interesting job,'' Roemer said.
   As solutions for the state's budget problems, Edwards had
proposed a statewide lottery and casino gambling in New Orleans.
Roemer is opposed to both.
   ``We are not going to raise taxes or change taxes until we cut
this budget,'' said Roemer. ``It is out of control.''
   Even before his inauguration, Roemer won two key victories in
the Legislature as his candidates for House speaker and Senate
president were elected during organizational meetings by lawmakers.
   Roemer said earlier that a change in the legislative leadership
was needed to give his ambitious programs a fair hearing by
lawmakers.
   Before Roemer was sworn in, Lt. Gov. Paul Hardy, a Republican,
took the oath from former Gov. Dave Treen. Hardy defeated Lt. Gov.
Bobby Freeman in a runoff last fall. Other top state officials, all
Democrats, also were sworn.
   Roemer, his wife, three children and his parents started
inauguration day with a worship service at the First United
Methodist Church.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880314-0196 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-88 1851EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Scotus-Felde     03-14 0140</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Felde,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Court Denies Felde Stay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court by a vote of 7-2 refused
Monday to postpone the execution of Wayne R. Felde, who was due to
be executed in Louisiana Tuesday.
   Justices Thurgood Marshall and William J. Brennan, who oppose
capital punishment in all circumstances, voted to grant the stay.
   At the same time, the court refused Felde's request for formal
consideration of his appeal.
   Felde's claimed he was denied competent representation at his
1980 trial on charges of killing a police officer because his
attorney joined him in asking for the death sentence.
   Felde had claimed his experiences in the Vietnam War left him
subject to flashbacks and unable to tell right from wrong. He
described himself as a walking time bomb who would have to be
executed to prevent further killings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
