<DOCNO> AP880314-0197 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-88 1858EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Colombia-Elections     03-14 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia-Elections,0532</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Young Anti-Drug Lawyer Wins Bogota Mayoral Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A young lawyer who is the son of a
former president and was kidnapped for campaigning against drugs
has won the Bogota mayor's office in the first mayoral elections in
Colombian history.
   Security for Sunday's voting was tight throughout Colombia,
where violence by extremist political factions and powerful
narcotics traffickers is common.
   An alleged leader of the biggest drug organization even tried to
run for city council in the town of Armenia, but Carlos Lehder
Rivas failed because Colombian law demands that candidates register
in person. Lehder is in jail in Jacksonville, Fla., facing drug
charges there and in Miami.
   Andres Pastrana, 34, son of former President Misael Pastrana,
won the mayoralty election in Bogota and will be one of the
youngest men to hold the office, which often has been a stepping
stone to the presidency.
   Pastrana is a rising star in the Conservative Party and his
election was a setback for President Virgilio Barco's governing
Liberals.
   He was the only Conservative running for mayor in Bogota, but
feuding factions in the Liberal Party ran a total of three
candidates. Pastrana got 324,801 votes and Juan Caicedo, Liberal
former president of the Colombian Association of Businessmen,
finished second with 236,212.
   Voters heeded Barco's call to fight bullets with ballots in the
first election of mayors. For 169 years the president, always from
either the Liberal or Conservative parties, had appointed governors
who in turn chose the mayors.
   Colombians elected 1,008 mayors Sunday. They also chose city
councils, state legislatures and governing bodies for remote
territories with too few people to become states.
   By late Sunday night the elections office said the Liberal Party
had won 405 of the races for mayor, Conservatives 379 and the
leftist Patriotic Union 13. Coalition candidates representing
several parties won 104 of the mayoral contests, the elections
office said. Results were not yet in from remote areas.
   Barco said in a speech televised Saturday night that voting
would be a way to reject the violence. More than 1,700 people were
killed in the past year in fighting between leftist guerrillas and
government security forces and by right-wing death squads and drug
traffickers.
   On Sunday, soldiers and police guarded voting places and
patrolled cities and towns. The election campaign was one of the
bloodiest ever in Colombia, with leftist guerrillas and right-wing
death squads killing five mayoral candidates and 19 city council
candidates. Hundreds of other political activists were slain.
   Leftist guerrillas kidnapped 14 mayors in the two weeks before
the election, then freed them after telling each to do more for the
poor.
   Pastrana, who called for stronger action against the
multibillion-dollar cocaine and marijuana trade, was kidnapped by
drug traffickers in January. A week later, police acting on a tip
raided a farmhouse where he was held and rescued him unharmed.
   One group, the Medellin Cartel, is said to be responsible for 80
percent of the cocaine smuggled into the United States. Lehder is
charged in Miami with being one of its leaders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880314-0198 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-88 1909EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-PLOMission     03-14 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-PLO Mission,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PLO Observer Says He Will Refuse to Close Mission</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Palestine Liberation Organization
observer said Monday he will defy Washington's decision to shut the
PLO mission to the United Nations, and U.S. officials said they
would not try to close it immediately.
   Zehdi Labib Terzi said American authorities would have to ``put
me behind steel bars'' if they wanted to close the mission, which
is in a New York City townhouse.
   ``We have the right to stay here and we will stay where we
are,'' he told a news conference, and added that if the mission is
closed the United Nations should exclude Israel from debates on the
Middle East.
   Last Friday, Attorney General Edwin Meese III said he would have
to close the PLO observer mission as required by a new
anti-terrorist law.
   U.N. officials said Monday another session of the 159-member
General Assembly was possible this week in an effort to retaliate
or thwart U.S. plans. The PLO mission was established 13 years ago.
   U.S. officials said they would not physically close it by March
21, as stipulated in the law, but would let legal proceedings run
their course.
   The legal situation was confused. Terzi said he opposes PLO
action in U.S. courts because the dispute is between the United
States and United Nations.
   ``Unless I am dragged, I see no reason why I should appear in a
U.S. court,'' he told reporters. Terzi added, however, that a U.S.
citizen might sue in an American court to keep the mission open and
protect constitutional rights of free speech and association.
   The United Nations recognizes the PLO as the sole legitimate
representative of the Palestinian people and it has non-voting
observer status. Its representatives have the right to address
every U.N. debate on the Middle East.
   The United States considers the PLO a terrorist organization.
   If the mission is forced to close and the PLO message cannot be
heard, Terzi said, the General Assembly should decide ``in a sense
of fairness and justice'' to exclude Israel from Middle East
debates.
   The United Nations and U.S. State Department have said the
decision to close the mission violates the international U.N.
Headquarters Treaty under which the United States allows U.N.
missions to operate.
   At a three-day emergency session Feb. 29-March 2, the General
Assembly condemned U.S. plans to close the mission, asked the World
Court to rule on arbitration and urged the United States to abide
by the Headquarters Treaty.
   It passed the resolution of condemnation overwhelmingly, with
the United States not participating, and decided to reconvene
before March 21 to decide what to do if Washington decided to press
ahead with closing the mission.
   General Assembly resolutions carry moral weight as expressions
of world opinion but are not binding, as are those of the Security
Council.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
