<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0602,0719</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq, Iran Unleash Air, Ground Assaults</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with Iraqi report of eight
missiles fired into Tehran and claims of plane and helicopter
downed. Picks up 6th graf pvs bgng: It said ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran and Iraq shot missiles at each
other's most heavily populated cities and pounded border towns with
renewed intensity Monday after a weekend truce. Scores of civilians
were killed and wounded.
   In a resumption of the ``war of the cities,'' Iraq reported it
fired eight surface-to-surface missiles into Iran's capital of
Tehran, the last one at 11:27 p.m., and Iran said its forces shot
two missiles at Baghdad, the Iraqi capital.
   The Iraqis, declaring an all-out offensive on Iranian cities,
also launched air raids on ``military and economic targets'' in
Dezful, Kermanshah, Shushtar and three other border towns, scoring
what it said were ``destructive hits.''
   Iraqi communiques said the air raids were carried out in a
40-minute period, with all planes returning safely.
   Iraq also claimed its helicopter gunships downed an Iranian
helicopter.
   Iran, meanwhile, claimed its Revolutionary Guards and
Iranian-backed Kurdish guerrillas have killed or wounded 1,900
Iraqis during ground assaults that began Sunday in the mountains of
northeast Iraq.
   Tehran Television reported Iran fired nine surface-to-surface
missiles into Umm Qasr, an industrial town near Iraq's southern
border with Kuwait, and said anti-aircraft gunners shot down an
Iraqi fighter-bomber in the northeastern battles.
   The official Iraqi News Agency, monitored in Cyprus, said the
Iraqis fired eight long-range Al Hussein missiles into Tehran
Monday.
   It said the barrage was a reprisal for the shelling of Iraqi
border towns Sunday night in which at least 21 civilians were
killed and 80 wounded.
   Iraq resumed firing on Sunday when it shot a lone ``warning''
missile into Tehran, also in retaliation for the shelling of
civilian areas.
   The exchanges shattered the uneasy two-day truce in the war
against cities that began Friday, bringing a brief respite after a
12-day exchange of missiles, artillery fire and air raids by both
sides.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency, also monitored in
Cyprus, reported that Iraq's missiles on Monday exploded in
residential sections of the Iranian capital, a city of 6 million,
killing at least 26 civilians and wounding 50.
   The news agency, quoting military communiques, said the Iranians
retaliated by lobbing two missiles at ``military and economic
centers'' in Baghdad.
   The Iraqis reported that only one missile crashed into a
residential area, killing an undisclosed number of civilians.
   The missile exploded as oil and energy chiefs from 20 Arab
countries gathered in Baghdad for a conference on resources.
Officials in Baghdad said some Arab ministers had canceled plans to
attend the session, apparently because of the flare-up in the war.
   Both sides in the 7{-year-old Persian Gulf war vowed to keep
pounding each other cities until the other quits.
   ``Iran will not rest until the blood of our martyrs of Iraqi
missile and air attacks has been avenged,'' said Kamal Kharrazi, a
member of Iran's Supreme Defense Council and head of the War
Information headquarters in Tehran.
   Iraqi News Agency quoted an unidentified military spokesman in
Baghdad as saying that ``Iraq has decided to resume its missile
attacks and air raids on all Iranian cities, not just Tehran ...
because of Iran's new crimes.''
   The Iraqi agency said that heavy Iranian shellfire of the border
cities that began Sunday was continuing Monday, with a ``large
number'' of civilians killed or wounded.
   It said the northern towns of Halabja and Darbandikhan were
badly hit.
   Iraqi communiques said the southern port of Basra, heavily
bombarded by the Iranians in the last 18 months, was hammered by
artillery and short-range missiles, with casualties reported to be
heavy.
   The nearby refinery town of Zubair and other southern towns also
were being shelled, the communiques reported.
   Iraq said it fired 71 missiles into Tehran, the holy city of Qom
and the central city of Isfahan, capital of ancient Persia, between
Feb. 29 and March 11.
   Iran said it shot 27 missiles into Tehran and two into the
northeastern city of Mosul in that period.
</TEXT>
