<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Revolutionaries'Trial     03-14 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Revolutionaries' Trial,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyers Unsuccessfully Urge Judge To Separate Husbands' Trial From
Wives'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The judge in the case of seven
revolutionaries accused of plotting the overthrow of the government
refused a defense request Monday to let the three women defendants
be tried separately from their husbands.
   Ruling on pretrial motions, U.S. District Judge William Young
also rejected the defendants' request to dismiss the case because
of what they claimed was the vagueness of the sedition statute
under which they were charged.
   However, the judge gave the defense a victory when he indicated
that witnesses who had been hypnotized to help them recall events
related to the case might not be allowed to testify.
   Jury selection was slated to begin Tuesday. The trial is
expected to last up to a year.
   The so-called Ohio 7 face one count each of seditious
conspiracy, racketeering conspiracy and racketeering enterprise.
Each count carries a maximum penalty of 20 years in prison and
$20,000 in fines.
   The indictment accuses defendants Raymond Luc Levasseur and
Thomas W. Manning of nearly 20 bombings and 10 robberies throughout
the Northeast since 1975 to raise money to finance their radical
political aims.
   Two others, Jaan K. Laaman and Richard C. Williams, allegedly
joined them on later crimes.
   The wives of three defendants _ Patricia H. Gros Levasseur,
Carol A. Manning and Barbara J. Curzi Laaman _ are accused of
harboring their husbands as fugitives, using false identification
and taking part in some bombings.
   Ms. Levasseur's attorney, William Newman, argued Monday that
prosecutors were trying to ``bury the women'' by tying them to the
crimes allegedly committed by their husbands.
   Prosecutors, however, accused the women of taking an equal part
in planning the violent crimes, and Young denied the women's
request for a separate trial.
   Young denied without comment the defendents' motion to dismiss
the case because of what they claimed was the vagueness of the
sedition statute, enacted during the Civil War to punish
Confederate rebels.
   He also denied a motion by the government to add to the
indictment some of the defendants' convictions on bombing, robbery
and other charges. Prosecutors had asked that the convictions be
included to help prove a conspiracy.
   The judge agreed Monday with the defense team's objection to
government witnesses who were hypnotized to help them recall events.
   ``Before that witness takes the stand, before you even call that
witness, you must file a motion detailing explicitly that witness's
pre-hypnotic testimony,'' the judge told prosecutors.
   ``I am not disposed to let any of these witnesses testify to
anything.''
   U.S. Attorney Frank McNamara said after the hearing that two or
three witnesses had been hypnotized. He wouldn't comment on who
they were or their potential importance to the prosecution.
</TEXT>
