<2ND_LINE>AM-Cuomo-Jackson,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuomo Says ``Of Course'' Jackson Electable</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York Gov. Mario Cuomo said Monday that
Jesse Jackson was electable as a Democratic presidential candidate
and ``has done extremely well'' at getting out an appealing message.
   ``Of course he's electable,'' said Cuomo during an inpromptu
news conference following a speech to New York's county officials.
``If the Democrats _ and that's a majority in the country, is it
not? _ if the Democrats say they want Jackson, how can you say he's
not electable?''
   Some political observers have suggested that Jackson could not
win the general election even if he were the Democratic nominee,
saying the country is not ready to elect a black man as president.
   ``His message is appealing,'' Cuomo said of Jackson. ``He's
saying to the people ... that we have many people who have been
left out that we need to educate and house through job training
because we can't make it without them. It's not just a matter of
compassion, it's a matter of common sense.''
   ``It's an important message,'' said the New York governor. ``And
I think people relate to it. I think we need to fashion the most
effective message that the Democrats can put together.''
   Cuomo, who announced more than a year ago that he wouldn't seek
the Democratic presidential nomination, has refused to rule out
accepting a draft for the nomination if there were a deadlocked
national convention.
   The New York governor has refused to endorse Jackson or any of
the other active Democratic candidates.
   Cuomo has said he believes Jackson stands a good chance of
winning New York's important April 19 primary.
</TEXT>
