<1ST_LINE>u a AM-FrommeTrial 2ndLd-Writethru a0767 03-14 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fromme Trial, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0767,0596</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fromme Convicted In Escape</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 10th graf pvs, `Assistant U.S. ...' to CORRECT name to
Brandfass sted Brandfess.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTHA BRYSON HODEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BECKLEY, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury Monday found Manson disciple and
would-be presidential assassin Lynette ``Squeaky'' Fromme guilty of
escaping from a federal prison after she told the panel: ``You
don't have any choice.''
   ``I'm guilty as charged, legally, and without remorse morally,
so that's that,'' Fromme, acting as her own lawyer, said in closing
arguments.
   Fromme, 39, a disciple of mass murderer Charles Manson, is
serving a life sentence for a 1975 assassination attempt against
President Ford. She escaped Dec. 23 from the Federal Correctional
Institution at Alderson, W.Va., and was captured about two miles
away on Christmas after a manhunt.
   Fromme called only herself as a witness and carefully followed
Hallanan's instructions that her testimony had to be in the form of
questions and answers, questioning herself on the pronunciation of
her name and cautioning: ``Miss Fromme, you talk too much,'' and
``Wait a minute, you're getting ahead of yourself.''
   The U.S. District Court jury returned its verdict after less
than 10 minutes of deliberation. Judge Elizabeth Hallanan set an
April 28 sentencing date. Fromme faces an additional sentence of up
to five years in prison and a $250,000 fine.
   Fromme has been described as the main member of the ``family''
that congregated around Manson, who is serving a life sentence in
San Quentin prison in California for the 1969 murders of actress
Sharon Tate and eight others.
   She told the jury Monday that she attempted to escape because
``I got word that (Manson) had cancer.
   ``He needs a relative, somebody to check on him,'' she said of
Manson, whom she described as ``my husband, my brother, my father,
my son, the man who's been my friend.''
   She said she decided to escape because ``my access to him is so
limited, I've been feeling helpless for years. If love means
anything at all it means stop feeling helpless ... (and) take
action if necessary.''
   Assistant U.S. Attorney J. Kirk Brandfass called four prison
employees to testify about Fromme's disappearance and her capture.
   Fromme cross-examined each government witness on the population
of the prison, and each of them indicated the institution _ which
has an official capacity of 670 prisoners _ now holds about 1,000,
   In her testimony she told the jury that the overcrowding was one
of the reasons she tried to escape.``The prison has become more and
more crowded, and the institution staff has become more and more
tense,'' she said.
   The judge had twice denied Fromme's request for a no-contest
plea and entered an innocent plea on her behalf.
   Fromme had told Hallanan the case ``doesn't warrant a jury
trial'' and said she was ``willing to accept whatever sentence you
hand down to me.''
   But Fromme failed on Monday to ask for ``bench trial,'' which
would have left the decision in the judge's hands without calling a
jury.
   Ford was unharmed when a Secret Service agent grabbed a
semiautomatic .45-caliber pistol aimed at him by Fromme on Sept. 5,
1975.
   In San Francisco 17 days later, Ford escaped injury when Sara
Jane Moore, 45, fired a revolver at him. She eventually pleaded
guilty and received a life sentence.
   In 1979, Moore also escaped from the Alderson prison but was
recaptured hours later about 25 miles away. She is now in a federal
prison in Pleasanton, Calif.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880314-0205 </DOCNO>
