<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FishyProtest 2ndLd-Writethru a0733 03-14 0622</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fishy Protest, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0733,0632</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>International Paper Co. Protesters Place Dead Fish in Bank Safety
Box</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs, `Members of ...' to CORRECT protest to
last week sted this week.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Activists protesting the Bank of Boston's
investment in a paper mill succeeded in depositing a dead fish in a
safety deposit box despite pleas from bank officials.
   The protesters appeared outside the bank building at noon in
opposition to what they said are toxic hazards at the International
Paper Co. mill in Jay, Maine. Mill workers on strike since last
June have been replaced and in recent weeks, there have beeen three
incidents of gas leaks.
   Members of the National Toxics Campaign and a group from Jay,
Stop Toxics Against Citizens, placed dead fish in safety deposit
boxes in several Bank of Boston branches last week to symbolize
what they said are the fish killed in the Androscoggin River
because of International Paper's alleged toxic dumping.
   Bank of Boston controls 189,000 shares of International Paper
and a bank board member, Donald McHenry, is on the board of
International Paper.
   On Monday, three activists entered the bank as some people
outside chanted ``Bank of Boston, they won't tell, holy mackerel,
what's that smell?''
   As Michael Stein, representing the protesters, Kate O'Connor, a
National Toxics Campaign worker, and Tina McDonald, a Jay resident,
walked to the vault, a coterie of bank security guards scurried
after them, banishing press photographers from the premises.
   One bank official, who declined to give his name, first tried to
dissuade the protesters from placing two fish inside the deposit
box.
   ``I'm just another schlep here,'' he told them. ``I don't know
why you want to do this, but I don't think it's a good idea.''
   Another official, who would only identify himself as ``Ronald
McDonald,'' informed Stein that he would be allowed to place the
two dead fish in his box, but that the bank planned to terminate
his contract immediately thereafter.
   ``We're asking you to surrender the box,'' said the official.
``We don't want you as a customer any more.''
   Stein then desposited the fish and was ushered out of the
building.
   Wayne Taylor, spokesman for the Bank of Boston, said the
protesters' tactics were hypocritical and caused a health issue.
``They're jeopardizing the safety and health of bank employees and
customers,'' he said, arguing that the dead fish could attract
cockroaches.
   Taylor said the bank has been, and will remain, neutral in the
controversy surrounding the paper mill and the strike.
   Members of the United International Paperworkers Union and the
Brotherhood of Firemen and Oilers walked out June 16 in a contract
dispute. International Paper wanted to eliminate 170 jobs and cut
premium pay on Sundays.
   Eight workers were sent to the hospital after being exposed to
hydrogen sulfide on Jan. 28, and a 112,000-gallon chlorine dioxide
leak on Feb. 5 forced nearly 4,000 residents out of their homes and
schools for several hours. A leak on Feb. 14 chlorine gas leak
injured seven people.
   Following protests from residents, Maine Gov. John R. McKernan
Jr. and International Paper chairman John A. Georges agreed on a
full-scale inspection of the plant, at the company's expense, by an
outside consultant selected by the state.
   Bill Greener, spokesman for International Paper in Purchase,
N.Y., said that the Maine Department of Environmental Protection
last week announced they had found no reason to close down the
mill. Greener said the three chemical leaks were ``something to be
avoided'' and said the company is cooperating with efforts to make
the mill as safe as possible. He denied the protesters' claim that
the company engages in toxic dumping.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
