<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Cuba-US     03-14 0227</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cuba-US,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuban Claims U.S. Paid Bribes To Gain Support Against Cuba</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Cuban official on Monday claimed the United
States paid bribes to win support for its effort to have the U.N.
Human Rights Commission investigate Cuba, the news agency Prensa
Latina reported.
   The Cuban news agency said Assistant Foreign Minister Raul Roa
told the Havana newspaper Granma that some people at the commission
hearings held in Geneva received $50,000 in bribes.
   In the report monitored in Mexico City, Prensa Latina mentioned
no names and gave no further details on the bribe allegation.
   Last week, the 43-nation Human Rights Commission accepted
President Fidel Castro's invitation to send a delegation to Cuba to
investigate allegations of human rights abuses.
   After that action, the United States withdrew a resolution
calling for the U.N. secretary-general to study the human rights
situation in Cuba and report to the commission.
   Roa, who returned to Havana last weekend from Geneva, called the
commission decision ``the most crushing defeat'' the United States
``has suffered in recent years in an international forum,'' Prensa
Latina said.
   Armando Valladares, a former Cuban political prisoner who headed
the U.S. delegation to the Geneva meeting, said last week the
two-year U.S. effort to have the commission examine the human
rights situation in Cuba had forced Castro to invite a delegation
to his country.
</TEXT>
