<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DonorBaby     03-14 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Donor Baby,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brain-Absent Infant Still on Life-Support</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOMA LINDA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A baby born with most of his brain
missing clung to life Monday at a hospital where doctors hoped to
make the doomed infant's organs available for transplant, a
hospital spokeswoman said.
   ``He shows progressive signs of brain stem deterioriation but
has not yet met all the criteria for total brain death,'' said
Anita Rockwell, a spokeswoman for Loma Linda University Medical
Center.
   The boy, identified only as Baby D, was born at an unidentified
Southern California hospital March 10 with a fatal birth defect
known as anencephaly, in which much of the brain and skull are
missing.
   The newborn's other vital organs are healthy, and his parents
asked that their child be considered an organ donor. He was
transferred to Loma Linda.
   Loma Linda has developed the nation's first medical guidelines
for preserving anencephalics' heart and other vital organs for
transplanting into critically ill infants.
   The baby is the fourth brain-absent newborn accepted at Loma
Linda for possible use as an organ donor.
   Under criteria established by the hospital, Baby D was placed on
life-support systems for a seven-day period, which ends Thursday
night.
   If doctors determine that Baby D is brain-dead during that
period, the hospital will serve notice that the organs are
available for transplant.
   If the infant is not declared brain-dead within seven days, Baby
D will be taken off the respirator and will be allowed to die
naturally.
   The guidelines were developed to address ethical questions
surrounding use of doomed anencephalics as organ donors.
   Loma Linda received nationwide attention and criticism in 1984
when Dr. Leonard Bailey transplanted a baboon's heart into a girl
known as Baby Fae. She died 20{ days later.
   Bailey later transplanted infant hearts successfully. However, a
shortage organ donors led Loma Linda to develop its policy on
anencephalic infants.
</TEXT>
