<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Panama 1stLd-Writethru a0650 03-14 0897</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0650,0924</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Distributes Food to Workers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with supermarkets attacked in
Colon, U.S. reinforcements sent to Panama. Picks up 8th graf:
Primary and ... INSERTS 2 grafs after 11th graf pvs, ``Alberto Soto
... with Colon strike, other details; minor editing thruout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By REID G. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police fired tear gas Monday at
protesters who blocked traffic in the capital and cried, ``Noriega
must go!'' Work stoppages broke out as employees learned they would
not be paid by a government that has run out of money.
   The government began selling sacks of food, called ``dignity
bags,'' to unpaid workers. Some schoolteachers, telephone company
and Panama Canal dock workers demanded cash and struck to reinforce
their demand.
   In Washington, the Pentagon announced it had sent 104 Marines
and Air Force military police to Panama to reinforce U.S. security
units.
   Violence was reported in the port city of Colon at the Caribbean
entrance of the Panama Canal.
   Nicolas Psichoyos, a manager of the Rey supermarket chain, said
two company stores were attacked by gangs demanding free food for
government employees. Five supermarket employees were injured in
fights with the attackers, one of them seriously, Psichoyos said.
   He said the gangs were supporters of Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega, the nation's strongman.
   Protesters in Panama City erected flaming street barricades of
trash. Others yelled at security forces and were met by volleys of
tear gas.
   For the first time, the disturbances reached into the heart of
the capital's business district.
   Riot police used tear gas to disperse about 600 primary and
secondary school teachers blocking traffic in front of the Ministry
of Education. ``We want our pay!'' shouted the teachers. ``Books
yes, arms no!''
   As the police, armed with rubber truncheons and tear gas
grenades, forcibly removed them, the teachers cried: ``Noriega must
go!'' No arrests were reported.
   Primary and secondary schools were to have reopened Monday
following a three-month vacation, but they stayed closed.
   Alberto Williams, a secretary of the Dock Workers Union, said
about 700 employees walked off their jobs at 9 a.m. at the Port of
Balboa, the Pacific Ocean entrance to the Panama Canal, after being
told they would not be paid their semi-monthly salaries.
   ``This strike is not a political movement,'' said Williams, a
forklift operator who makes $5.85 an hour. ``All we want is that
the workers get their money.''
   Alberto Soto, the port administrator, said the strike would have
``absolutely nothing'' to do with traffic through the 50-mile
waterway linking the Pacific and Atlantic Oceans.
   Dock workers also struck at Colon 50 miles north of Panama City.
Colon residents told The Associated Press that in another protest,
teachers temporarily blocked the highway that runs parallel to the
canal.
   The U.S. Defense Department announced that 60 Marines and a
44-man Air Force police unit were flown to Panama Monday. A
Pentagon spokesman, Cmdr. Robert Prucha, said, ``This is simply a
prudent measure to augment the security personnel who are already
in place.''
   U.S. officials in Washington have said President Reagan's
decision to withhold a $6.5 million payment due Panama on Tuesday
was aimed at impairing the Panamanian government's ability to pay
Panama's 130,000 public workers this week.
   Withholding the payment was one of a number of economic
sanctions the United States has imposed to pressure Noriega to step
down as chief of the Defense Forces.
   Nearly one in every five working Panamanians is employed by the
government. Until now, they have supported Noriega, at least
outwardly.
   According to Panamanian figures, their payroll comes to about
$33 million every two weeks. Diplomatic sources and private
economists, speaking on condition of anonymity, say the nation's
treasury is empty.
   The ``dignity bags'' contained such staples of the Panamanian
diet as rice, beans, flour, onions, cheese and lard. They were
being sold for between $15 and $16 but the government apparently
was not demanding immediate payment.
   Horacio Rodriguez, director of the Ministry of Farm and Dairy
Products Marketing, said his agency prepared 12,000 of the bags.
   The nation's new civilian chief executive, Manuel Solis Palma,
Noriega and other top officials resumed an emergency economic
conference Monday morning after recessing an earlier session at 2
a.m. without comment.
   Solis Palma, installed by the military last month, has been
meeting frequently with his chief advisers but Sunday's meeting was
the first time that Noriega had been known to join them.
   Noriega, the power behind the government since 1983, was
indicted by two U.S. federal grand juries last month on charges of
drug trafficking and money laundering.
   About 40 employees outside the state-run telephone company's
main office told reporters they were striking because they had not
been paid.
   ``Nobody has told us anything,'' said one worker, who refused to
identify himself.
   The 118 local and foreign banks in Panama remained closed by
government order for the 10th straight day. Most had closed their
doors earlier because the government was unable to provide them
with the cash to cover a run on deposits.
   The bank run began Feb. 26, the day Noriega engineered the
dismissal of Eric Arturo Delvalle as president. The day before,
Delvalle had tried to fire Noriega. The deposed president has been
in hiding for more than two weeks, but is still recognized by the
United States as Panama's legitimate chief executive.
</TEXT>
