<2ND_LINE>AM-Mecham, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0702,0788</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>In Stormy Session, Ex-Mecham Aide Accusses Witness Of Lying</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with former aide accusing witness of
lying, deleting some detail to tighten. CORRECTS spelling of
Fields, sted Field, in 9th graf pvs. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former official in Gov. Evan Mecham's
administration, testifying Monday at the governor's Senate
impeachment trial, accused a key prosecution witness of lying about
an alleged death threat.
   Max Hawkins said the witness, Peggy Griffith, ``really had it in
for Lee Watkins,'' the man Griffith accused of making the threat.
   In a heated round of questioning, Hawkins insisted repeatedly he
did not believe a death threat had been made. ``I thought Peggy
really detested Lee Watkins,'' said Hawkins, former director of the
Department of Administration.
   Asked by Sen. Carolyn Walker whether he was accusing Griffith of
lying, Hawkins said: ``I testified I think she did lie on that.''
   Watkins, former state prison construction chief, has been
accused of threatening Donna Carlson, a former Mecham aide who was
testifying at the time before a grand jury investigating Mecham's
finances.
   Mecham, the first U.S. governor to face an impeachment trial in
six decades, is charged with obstructing an attorney general's
investigation of the alleged threat.
   Other impeachment charges against the first-term Republican
allege he concealed a $350,000 campaign fund and misused $80,000 in
a state fund by loaning it to his auto dealership.
   Mecham has not attended the trial since it began Feb. 29.
   Earlier Monday, Mecham's lawyer, Fred Craft, accused the state
police of intimidating defense witnesses as he moved for a mistrial
or dismissal of charges against Mecham.
   Mecham sent a letter to acting Gov. Rose Mofford asking that
three top state Department of Public Safety officials be placed on
leave. Mecham sugested that federal authorities be called in to
investigate the intimidation claims.
   ``A political trial that is difficult at best is made even more
difficult when witnesses are subject to these kinds of intimidation
and harassment,'' the letter said.
   There was no immediate response from Mrs. Mofford's office to
the letter requesting that she place DPS Director Ralph Milstead
and two other officials on leave.
   Arizona Supreme Court Justice Frank X. Gordon, who is presiding
over the impeachment trial, said he would not rule on Craft's
motion until Tuesday.
   Gordon also spent an hour in chambers with attorneys.
Prosecutors asked for sanctions against Craft for trying the case
in the news media with a weekend news conference, according to Rep.
Henry Evans, a Democrat who is a member of the House prosecution
team.
   Craft held the news conference to protest the arrest Friday of
defense witness Terri Fields on an outstanding warrant. She had
testified the day before.
   DPS arrested Ms. Fields on a January warrant charging that she
failed to attend court-ordered Alcoholics Anonymous meetings
following a driving-while-intoxicated conviction. She was released
on $1,000 bond.
   Ms. Fields testified that a state official who had testified
about the alleged threat tended to exaggerate. Ms. Fields also said
she thought there had been no death threat.
   DPS spokesman Sgt. Allan Schmidt has denied that Ms. Fields'
arrest was an attempt to intimidate impeachment trial witnesses.
   Meanwhile, Hawkins testified Monday that he considered the
alleged death threat ``a culmination of comical errors.''
   ``I saw no crime,'' Hawkins testified. He denied any attempt to
shield Watkins.
   House prosecutor William French, confronting Hawkins with his
own words in a news release, a newspaper interview and a tape
recording of a phone call, suggested Hawkins tried to shief Watkins
and help him pass a lie detector test.
   Hawkins said he was misquoted in the newspaper article and
wasn't sure his phone conversation with Watkins' attorney was
transcribed accurately. He complained bitterly that the
conversation with attorney Dale Anderson was illegal because it was
recorded without his knowledge.
   On the tape, he was quoted as saying: ``I love Lee and I want to
save his ass. I believe he's being railroaded.'' A transcript also
shows Hawkins discussing questions that could help Watkins pass the
polygraph test.
   Outside, some 200 pro-Mecham demonstrators protested Ms. Fields'
arrest. They carried placards denouncing the DPS and the news media
and calling for Mecham's reinstatement as governor.
   A two-thirds vote of the Senate is required to convict Mecham
and remove him from office.
   Mecham contends he has broken no law and is the victim of a
political conspiracy. He also faces an April 21 criminal trial on
felony counts alleging he concealed the $350,000 loan, and a May 17
recall election.
</TEXT>
