<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Writer'sStrike     03-14 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Writer's Strike,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Independent Producers Seek Exemptions From Striking Scriptwriters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST HOLLYWOOD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 50 independent TV
production companies, including Johnny Carson's ``Tonight Show,''
appealed to striking scriptwriters for an exemption from the
walkout, a union official said Monday.
   Brian Walton, West Coast executive director of the striking
Writers Guild of America, said the union board would consider the
special requests to allow scriptwriters to return to work at some
companies during the strike.
   The strike by 9,000 Guild members against the 200-member
Alliance of Motion Picture and Television Producers began March 7.
   Walton declined to identify the productions companies seeking
special, interim agreements, but ``The Tonight Show,'' announced it
was among them.
   About 40 percent of the companies that make shows for television
are wholly independent. Of the rest, about half are considered
independent but are affiliated with a major studio.
   Among shows already rejected for an exemption was the Academy
Awards ceremony, which is scheduled for worldwide broadcast April
11.
   Lobell-Bergman Productions said Monday the strike has affected
development of five of eight movies on its slate and stopped work
on a network comedy series.
   Previously postponed was a revival of ``The Smothers Brothers
Comedy Hour'' and a new series, ``The Dictator,'' starring
Christopher Lloyd.
   A spokesman for the producers belittled the union's assertion
about the number of independents seeking waivers.
   ``With the exception of Carson, I don't know of any other
independent producer looking to make a deal who is also member of
the alliance,'' said Herb Steinberg.
   No new talks were scheduled in strike. The guild is seeking
greater creative control, higher residuals from foreign market
distribution, and no adjustment by producers of residuals for
hour-long syndicated TV shows.
</TEXT>
