<1ST_LINE>u a AM-LiuKilling 1stLd-Writethru a0740 03-14 0609</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Liu Killing, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0740,0616</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tung Testifies About Liu Slaying</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf pvs, `Tung, 35 ...' with two grafs to CLARIFY
why Tung went to trial; SUBS 9th graf pvs, `Two years ...' to ADD
Tung is serving 20-year sentence.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY McGRATH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>REDWOOD CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former gang member testified
Monday that he agreed to the assassination of Chinese-American
journalist Henry Liu because he believed it was a patriotic act
requested directly by the Taiwanese government.
   Tung Kuei-sen, the former member of a Taiwanese criminal
``Bamboo Gang,'' has pleaded innocent to the 1984 shooting death of
journalist Henry Liu. He faces a sentence of 27 years to life in
prison if convicted of first-degree murder with the use of a
handgun.
   Liu, 52, was killed in the garage of his Daly City home just
south of San Francisco on Oct. 15, 1984. Liu, a columnist for
Chinese-language newspapers in San Francisco, had just finished a
biography critical of Chiang Ching-kuo, Taiwan's president from
1978 until his death of a heart attack in January.
   Tung, 35, has admitted the killing but went to trial because the
prosecution has not offered a plea bargain and because Tung want to
tell his story, said defense attorney Douglas Gray.
   Tung testified in San Mateo County Superior Court that he had
never heard of Liu or his writings until he was driven to San
Francisco the day before the killing.
   Speaking through an intepreter, he said he agreed to act as a
gunman at the request of Chen Chi-li, a reputed United Bamboo gang
leader who told him he received his orders from Taiwan's then chief
of military intelligence, Vice Adm. Weng Hsi-ling.
   ``He asked first of all, `Am I willing to help my country?'''
said Tung. ``I said, `Yes, of course, because this is everyone's
obligation.' And then he showed me he was a member of the
intelligence bureau with the ID card of the intelligence bureau of
the Republic of China.''
   He said Chen told him Liu was a traitor who had become a double
agent for Taiwan and the People's Republic of China.
   Tung said he was recruited by Chen because they both been United
Bamboo members before Tung moved to the United States to set up an
import-export business in August, 1984.
   Two years ago, Tung testified about his role in the Liu killing
while on trial on heroin smuggling charges in New York. He has said
that he wanted to testify in order to apologize and possibly lessen
his sentence. He received 20 years in prison for conspiracy to
smuggle 600 pounds of heroin into the United States.
   Tung described the shooting scene Monday. He said he and Wu Tun
rode up to Liu's home on bicycles, hiding in the garage until Liu
came in. He said Wu Tun shot first. ``I heard a shot and I went
forward and I saw this man fall down. At that time, I believed that
should be the man I should assassinate. I aimed at his tummy and
shot him twice,'' Tung said.
   Tung fled the country and was apprehended in Rio de Janeiro
after stops in Bangkok, the Philippines and Singapore.
   Chen Chi-Li, reputed head of the Bamboo Gang, and Wu Tun were
convicted in a Taipei court and are serving life terms in Taiwan.
The Taiwanese government has refused U.S. attempts to have them
extradited for trial here.
   Weng and two of his aides were convicted and given life
sentences in the case. Chen testified that the admiral and other
high-ranking military officers recruited him to kill Liu.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
