<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Gephardt     03-14 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gephardt,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gephardt Talks Up Trade Issues As He Heads Into Key Michigan
Contest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM IRWIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOUNT CLEMENS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential hopeful Rep.
Richard Gephardt brought his tough trade talk to a bastion of
organized labor Monday night, telling Democrats here that America's
allies must be prepared to accept U.S.-made products.
   For Gephardt, whose campaign stumbled badly on Super Tuesday,
the March 26 Democratic caucuses here are a crucial test. The
Missouri congressman passed up campaigning in Tuesday's Illinois
primary.
   Gephardt told about 300 supporters that in the past, the threat
of tariffs has helped the United States persuade Canada to stop
dumping wood products and the Japanese in dumping microchips on the
U.S. market.
   ``When we finally lose the timidity and stand up for basic
fairness, other countries open up,'' said Gephardt, who has made
trade issues a campaign centerpiece.
   Gephardt drew scattered groans and catcalls from the audience
when he quoted President Reagan as saying the trade deficit was a
sign of strength.
   ``I thought maybe he got his cuecards messed up,'' Gephardt said.
   Even as Gephardt talked up his stance on trade, lawmakers in
Washington moved toward to discard the trade amendment the Missouri
congressman authored.
   Senators are starting to push their House counterparts in
earnest to abandon the provision as conferees from the two houses
try to hammer out a final version of sweeping trade legislation.
   Gephardt spokesman Mark Johnson said the Senate action
represented ``nothing new'' in the trade debate.
   Gephardt planned to remain in Michigan through Wednesday, then
return Friday to continue campaigning in advance of the caucuses.
   Michigan Attorney General Frank Kelley, Gephardt's state
chairman, said the Missouri congressman had between $400,000 and
$500,000 available for a television advertising blitz over the next
11 days.
   ``It's very important that I win in Michigan, and we're going to
win in Michigan,'' Gephardt said after the speech.
   Kelley likened Gephardt's campaign to that of 1948, when another
Missourian, Harry Truman, won an upset victory for the White House.
   ``I predict he's going to surprise a lot of people,'' Kelley
said.
   Earlier Monday, Gephardt talked to more than 300 members of
United Auto Workers Local 569 in Flint, where he repeated his call
to rebuild America's declining industrial base.
</TEXT>
