<1ST_LINE>u p AM-RodinoProfile     03-14 0579</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rodino Profile,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rodino Became A House Institution As He Helped Write History</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Retransmitting a0804 to add `p' category code.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Rodino Retirement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB McHUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In 1948, Peter Rodino left his native Italian
neighborhood in Newark, N.J., an eager 38-year-old lawyer ready to
represent the bustling city in Congress.
   Rodino became an institution in the intervening 40 years:
fighting for liberal legislation, controlling one of Congress' most
powerful committees and helping write into history the downfall of
a president.
   On Monday, the 78-year-old congressman announced his plans to
retire after 20 terms.
   In those years, Newark decayed from the heart of the Garden
State into the brunt of jokes. Rodino's political base eroded, too.
His decision not to seek re-election came in the face of mounting
pressure from black political leaders, who claim it's now their
time to represent the vastly changed area.
   Born in 1909, the son of an Italian immigrant toolmaker, Rodino
seemed awed by responsibility when he was placed in charge of the
President Nixon's impeachment proceedings in 1974.
   ``If fate had been looking for one of the powerhouses of
Congress, it wouldn't have picked me,'' he told a reporter then.
   But Rodino's steady, judicious handling of the momentous
hearings earned him widespread praise and helped produce an
overwhelming bipartisan majority in favor of impeachment.
   Rodino said last year he retired to a private office and cried
after his committee approved three articles of impeachment, forcing
Nixon to resign two weeks later.
   More recently, Rodino was again in on the making of history, as
a senior member of the House Iran-Contra committee that
investigated the sale of arms to Iran and the funneling of profits
to the Nicaragua Contra rebels. He had harsh words for what he
called the Reagan administration's lack of concern for the
Constitution.
   He has continually used the Judiciary Committee to press for
civil rights and what he calls ``the rule of law.''
   Little in the early years of Rodino's career suggested he might
climb to the center stage of national political life.
   A child of the Depression, he completed law school in 1937,
after 10 years of night classes. He was later decorated for World
War II Army service in Italy.
   Like many members of Congress, Rodino relied upon service to his
constituents for his electoral success. But he was a strong civil
rights advocate, and that served him well as his once-prosperous
city became predominantly black by the 1970s.
   He spoke proudly of his Italian heritage, and sponsored
legislation that made Columbus Day part of a three-day annual
holiday.
   ``Peter Rodino was an unknown quantity,'' former House Speaker
Thomas P. O'Neill, D-Mass., once recalled. ``He was a flame under a
bushel basket.''
   Nixon's political demise raised Rodino's stock considerably. He
made the cover of national news magazines, starred on the dinner
circuit, and was even interviewed to be Jimmy Carter's running mate
in 1976.
   In December 1980, his wife and high-school sweetheart, Marianna
Stango Rodino, died after suffering for two years from a brain
tumor. Rodino had missed many a House session caring for her. He
received further blows in 1982 and 1983 when he lost his brother,
sister and mother-in-law.
   Rodino focused himself on his work, running for his seat and
winning, despite ever-mounting challenges. Two years ago, he hinted
he would step down as soon as Reagan left office.
   He said then he would concentrate on writing his memoirs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
