<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Bolivia     03-14 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bolivia,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Attend Funeral of Slain Student and Protest March</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER McFARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 10,000 people marched through La
Paz Monday in a funeral procession for a student who died from a
bullet wound he received during a violent protest.
   Later Monday, about 5,000 workers demonstrated in the capital
against the government's economic policies. At one point, police
threw tear gas canisters to disperse protesters about to throw
rocks at the U.S. Embassy, authorities said.
   The students and faculty were protesting the death of Marco
Antonio Uria, a student at San Andres University in La Paz who died
Saturday morning after being hit by a bullet during a confrontation
between students and police.
   The march was peaceful and no arrests were reported.
   Students said police were responsible for Uria's death, but the
Ministry of the Interior said the bullet was fired by students.
   Friday's protest was organized to demand an increase in the
federal budget for universities. Students threw rocks at police,
overturned vehicles and threw up roadblocks. Police pursued fleeing
students onto the campus.
   A group of students returning from the funeral Monday afternoon
destroyed a booth in downtown La Paz that was selling souvenirs of
the pope's visit to Bolivia in May, witnesses said.
   Later in the afternoon, at least 5,000 workers marched through
La Paz to protest the economic policies of the administration of
President Victor Paz Estenssoro.
   The march, organized by the Bolivian Workers Central, was called
to pressure the government to increase wages, protect the
government social security system and strengthen the public school
system.
   ``The government is obeying the mandates of the International
Monetary Fund and as a result workers are suffering the
consequences with starvation wages,'' said Simon Reyes, executive
of the Workers Central, during a rally that preceded the march.
</TEXT>
