<1ST_LINE>u a AM-JohnnySpain     03-14 0560</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Johnny Spain,0575</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Spain's Shackling Justified, Lawyer Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STANFORD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The shackling of former Black Panther
Johnny Spain at his murder trial stemming from a 1971 prison
breakout attempt was justified by the threat of violence, a
prosecutor told an appeals court Monday.
   As the 38-year-old Spain, newly released from prison after 21
years, looked on, Deputy Attorney General Ronald Niver argued that
the judge who presided at the trial ``was confronted with six
violent men'' charged with murder.
   ``It was reasonable for (the judge) to fear for the safety of
those in the courtroom,'' Niver told the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals. ``He tried the best way he knew how to protect the safety
of the spectators.''
   But Spain's lawyer, Dennis Riordan, urged the panel to uphold a
lower-court order granting Spain a new trial on the grounds that
the heavy and painful shackles influenced the jury and deterred
Spain from testifying.
   ``We know that this jury only heard one half the story,''
Riordan said. In five years of court proceedings and a 17-month
trial, Spain wore 25 pounds of chains around his body, arms and
legs.
   The three-judge appeals panel heard more than 90 minutes of
arguments and will rule on whether to reinstate Spain's two murder
convictions.
   One option raised during the hearing was to return the case to a
lower court to find out what Spain would say if he had testified
and whether it could have affected the verdict. Riordan opposed the
suggestion.
   Spain, released on $350,000 bail last week, told reporters after
the hearing that being free was ``an incredible feeling'' and he
wasn't worried about the court sending him back to prison.
   ``I probably won't put a down payment on a home, but I can't
stop living because of that possibility,'' Spain said.
   Spain faces a more immediate threat to his freedom: a vote next
week by the state Board of Prison Terms reconsidering a panel's
decision to parole him from a life term for a 1966 murder-robbery
committed when he was 17.
   In the unrelated trial known as the San Quentin Six case, Spain
was the only prisoner convicted of murder in a 1971 bloodbath that
took the lives of militant leader George Jackson, two other inmates
and three guards.
   Authorities said Spain, who was seen running out of a
maximum-security unit with Jackson, conspired with Jackson in the
escape attempt. Three other prisoners were acquitted, and two were
convicted of assault.
   In his 1986 ruling granting Spain a new trial, U.S. District
Judge Thelton Henderson said Superior Court Judge Henry Broderick
had failed to consider alternatives to the shackling, such as the
warnings used for another of the six defendants.
   But Niver said the appeals court, reviewing the trial years
later, should defer to Broderick's evident conclusion that he had
no safe alternative.
   Circuit Judge Alex Kozinski pressed Niver on whether safety
could have been maintained with less severe measures _ for example,
leaving an arm unchained so Spain could write a note to his lawyer
without pain.
   ``We wouldn't do that to an animal, right?'' Kozinski asked.
   Niver replied that Spain, even while fully manacled, threw a
file folder at the jury and caused other courtroom disruptions. But
Riordan said the disruptions were caused by the pain of the
shackles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
