<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Argentina-Teachers     03-14 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Argentina-Teachers,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teachers Strike Across Argentina On First Day Of Classes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDALL HACKLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Primary school teachers across
Argentina went on strike Monday demanding higher wages and forcing
cancellation of most classes on the first day of the public school
year.
   Officials said only in northeastern Corrientes province, where a
salary agreement was reached earlier this month, did teachers begin
regular classes for pre-schoolers and youngsters in grades one
through seven.
   More than 450,000 members of the CTERA teachers' union are
demanding a minimum salary of 770 australs a month _ the equivalent
of $126.
   CTERA has said grade school teachers in some poorer provinces of
this nation of 31 million people receive about 350 australs ($57) a
month, requiring many to seek second jobs.
   It issued a statement saying that except in Corrientes, at least
90 percent of the primary school teachers joined Monday's walkout.
   Their strike could extend to high school teachers if no
agreement is reached by next Monday, the opening day of high school
classes. University teachers have threatened to boycott classes
because of wage conflicts.
   The government has acknowledged that teachers' salaries are low,
but said the wage demands cannot be met because of the country's
severe economic problems.
   Education and Justice Minister Jorge Sabato described the union
decision to disrupt the opening of the school year as abrupt and
lamentable.
   Most private schools, many of which are operated by churches,
opened as scheduled but a few reported walkouts by teachers
sympathetic with their public school collegues.
   CTERA is demanding a uniform minimum salary for teachers in all
of Argentina, noting differences between wages in districts in and
around Beunos Aires and those in lesser developed regions.
   The government and provinces have offered to gradually increase
salaries by an unspecified amount over several months. That was
rejected by CTERA, saying the offer was inadequate considering
Argentina's rampant inflation.
   Inflation registered 189 percent over the past 12 months.
</TEXT>
