<HEAD>Fugitive, Spotted on `Password,' Pleads Guilty</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fugitive arrested after he was recognized
on the TV game show ``Super Password'' pleaded guilty Monday to
collecting $100,000 on a life insurance policy by falsely claiming
his wife had been killed in an auto accident.
   Kerry Dee Ketchem, 36, entered the plea to two counts of
mail-fraud indictment. He admitted submitting the false insurance
claim while stationed with the Air Force in England.
   He faces up to 10 years in prison and a $500,000 fine at
sentencing May 2.
   Ketchem, appearing under a pseudonym on ``Super Password,'' was
identified by a TV viewer in Alaska and was arrested as he
attempted to pick up a record $58,600 in winnings from his
appearance on the show.
   The Alaskan banker who spotted Ketchem and called authorities
claimed Ketchem had run up about $25,000 in bills by using
fraudulently obtained credit cards.
   After Monday's hearing, Ketchem's attorney, Jerry Newton, said
his client also may be indicted in Indiana on charges of obtaining
a $26,000 bank loan by using a car he didn't own as collateral.
