<HEAD>Consul General Leaves Office With Official Seals, Papers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pro-Noriega diplomat who was replaced at the
Panamanian consulate here Monday apparently left with official
diplomatic seals and important papers, authorities said.
   Consul General Joaquin Meza left office after Panamanian
Ambassador Juan Sosa replaced him with Robert Dominguez, a
prominent businessman who fled Panama after President Eric Delvalle
was forced from office.
   Sosa supports the ousted Delvalle and has replaced 25 other
consuls general who had backed Panamanian military strongman Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   Dominguez said that when he arrived at the consulate Monday
morning, he found seals and important immigration papers were
missing. Miami police are investigating, but a spokesman said Meza
already has left the country.
   Among the papers missing were visa applications filed by dozens
of Cuban Americans who had paid thousands of dollars to visit or
pick up relatives living in Panama, Dominguez said.
   The Central American nation has been in turmoil since Noriega
was indicted in Miami and Tampa on drug charges and Delvalle called
for his ouster.
   The U.S. State Department has said it recognizes Delvalle, who
is in hiding, as the official leader of Panama.
