<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Gulf     03-14 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Gulf,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Renewed `War of Cites' Sets Off Flurry Of UN Activity</HEAD>
<HEAD>WWith AM-Gulf Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union acknowledged Monday it
has failed to win support for a Security Council resolution calling
for an end to the deadly missile duel against each other's cities
by Iran and Iraq.
   The United States viewed the proposal as a maneuver to deflect
attention from the U.S. push for a worldwide arms embargo against
Iran for its refusal to honor the council's July 20 cease-fire
resolution and peace plan.
   It is expected the council now will just issue a statement this
week by the council president calling for an end to the missile
attacks.
   Soviet Ambassador Alexander Belonogov acknowledged that the
Soviet bid for a new resolution on the ``war of the cities'' had
failed after the council met behind closed doors.
   ``Our personal preference would be a resolution of the Security
Council,'' he said, but the important thing is ``not the form but
the essence'' of the council's action.
   ``If the presidential statement has better chances than a
resolution to be adopted by the Security Council, we are all for
it,'' he told reporters.
   Belonogov urged the council to do its utmost to end the
long-range duel, which he said was poisoning the ``political and
psychological'' atomosphere for peace talks centering on the
council's July resolution.
   A weekend truce in the war of the cities began collapsing
Sunday. By Monday, both sides had unleashed missiles on each
other's capitals.
   Both Iran and Iraq are believed to be using Soviet-made Scud-B
missiles in the duel that has killed scores of civilian since Feb.
29.
   U.S. Ambassador Herbert S. Okun said the council does not want
to ``proliferate pieces of paper when we have a resolution that we
are in the process of implementing.''
   The superpowers have been at odds over the July 20 resolution
demanding an immediate cease-fire and withdrawal to international
boundaries as the first steps in a complex plan for negotiating an
end to the 7{-year-old war.
   America has been trying to gain support since last fall for an
arms embargo against Iran, which has refused to accept the U.N.
resolution. The Soviet Union is trying to improve its relations
with neighboring Iran and has been reluctant to suppport an embargo.
</TEXT>
