<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Hastings     03-14 0169</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hastings,0174</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Says Judiciary Committee Can Receive Hastings
Information</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court Monday ordered grand jury
material concerning U.S. District Judge Alcee Hastings of Florida
turned over to a House committee considering his impeachment.
   In a 2-1 ruling, a panel of the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals said the House Judiciary Committee had demonstrated a
``particularized need'' for the normally secret material.
   The grand jury had investigated whether Hastings tipped off a
politician about a FBI wiretap the judge had authorized in 1985. No
indictments resulted.
   Hastings, 52, the first black federal judge in Florida, was
acquitted in an unrelated case in 1983 of charges he conspired to
solicit a $150,000 bribe.
   However, two fellow judges filed a complaint that Hastings lied
in his defense and was guilty of judicial misconduct. A 27-judge
Judicial Conference last year recommended that the House consider
Hastings' impeachment.
   Hastings, who was appointed by President Jimmy Carter in 1979,
claims the impeachment proceedings are racially motivated.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
