<DOCNO> AP880314-0226 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-88 2301EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Israel 3rdLd-Writethru a0717 03-14 1243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Israel, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0717,1200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shamir Brings New Ideas, Delays Decision On US Plan For Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 4th graf pvs, bgng: ``I am'' to UPDATE
with response and show speech followed text; INSERTS 1 graf after
10th graf pvs, bgng: ``In an ..'' to UPDATE with Shamir also
meeting with senators; Minor editing to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir arrived
here Monday with what he called new ideas for Mideast peace talks
and said he would not give a yes-or-no reply to the U.S. blueprint
for negotiations with the Arabs during his four-day stay.
   ``For us, these matters are questions of life and death, of our
very existence,'' Shamir said Monday night in a speech to the
United Jewish Appeal.
   While he promised to keep an open mind in the talks, Shamir took
a hard line on Israel's retention of the West Bank and Gaza, at
least part of which the Reagan administration is calling on Israel
to surrender.
   ``I am astonished at some people's short memory,'' Shamir said.
``Did we have peace when we did not have these territories? Don't
they remember that the two most dangerous attempts to destroy us _
in 1948 and in 1967 _ were made when we did not control any of
these territories? Do they want us to go back to a situation which
would inevitably invite another such attempt?''
   Shamir's speech was well-received by an enthusiastic crowd of
about 3,000 people, who gave him several standing ovations.
   Referring to the violence on the West Bank and in Gaza in which
91 Palestinians have perished, Shamir said ``it is not a war for a
Palestinian state in those areas. It is a war against Israelis,
against the existence of the state of Israel.''
   Shamir's reluctance to respond directly to the U.S. plan did not
seem to distress the Reagan administration. ``We are not pressing
Israel,'' a senior U.S. official told reporters at a White House
briefing.
   But the official, who spoke under rules granting anonymity, said
``it is the situation in the area which is pressing Israel and all
the other parties in the area.''
   Shamir did not disclose the revisions he will propose to
Secretary of State George P. Shultz, who devised the plan and set
this week as a deadline for a reply from the Israeli and Jordanian
governments.
   The senior U.S. official said ``we are not hung up'' on a
specific date for Israel's response. But he said the Middle East
was not stable and ``we feel very strongly that everyone, Arabs and
Israelis, must move forward.''
   In an arrival statement, Shamir said the 1978 Camp David
agreements, which called for a five-year trial period of
Palestinian self-rule, ``should serve as our guide.''
   Shamir also met Monday with three of the 30 senators who had
sent him a letter urging him to give up some occupied territory in
exchange for peace. The three Democrats _ Sens. Carl Levin of
Michigan, Frank Lautenberg of New Jersey and Howard Metzenbaum of
Ohio _ again urged that Israel cede land for peace, but Shamir did
not soften his position.
   The State Department did not indicate whether Shultz would be
willing to alter his formula for negotiations. Spokesman Charles E.
Redman simply called it ``a serious proposal'' that was under
``active consideration'' in Israeli and Arab capitals.
   But the senior official said ``we won't let any aspect be eroded
or compromised.''
   He said the Camp David framework was a ``work of`genius,'' but
was partly out of date, especially since Jordan and the
Palestinians did not participate in negotiations that fell apart in
1981.
   Shultz is pushing for a three-year interim arrangement on the
Israeli-held West Bank and Gaza Strip, with negotiations for an
overall settlement to open by December. He also is prodding Israel
to cede territory in exchange for Arab recognition.
   Shamir, stepping from a U.S. Air Force plane at Andrews Air
Force Base in suburban Maryland, said he was ``always open to new
and constructive proposals'' to bring peace to the Middle East.
   He said Israel wished to live in peace with its neighbors, but
that ``violence, terrorism and war are endemic'' to the region.
   Meanwhile, Senate Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va.,
cautioned that for Israel ``to continue down the road developing
now is a road to disaster.''
   Byrd told reporters on Capitol Hill that ``Mr. Shamir would be
well-advised to listen to the viewpoints of the friends of Israel
in this country,'' including Congress and the American Jewish
community.
   Shamir, after an overnight flight from Tel Aviv, met with about
30 Jewish leaders at Kennedy International Airport in New York
before continuing on to Washington. Avi Pazner, his spokesman,
said, Shamir told them, ``I have decided not to take any decision
right now because people in Israel are divided.''
   Shamir told the group, which including Morris B. Abram, head of
the Conference of Presidents of Major American Jewish
Organizations, that most people in Israel want peace.
   But Shamir added that the question was whether it was possible
to make peace with the Arabs now and also maintain ``our normal
lives and our security,'' Pazner said.
   Shultz escorted Shamir to his hotel in downtown Washington on
Monday morning and talked with him for a half-hour over coffee.
   Shultz reportedly underscored the importance of Shamir's visit
as well as the ``strong and unshakable'' ties between the United
States and Israel.
   In reply, Israeli sources said, Shamir said he had brought some
``new ideas'' that he would present to Shultz in their talks over
the next three days.
   In his arrival statement, Shamir appealed for understanding.
``In our search for peace, the United States has always been
helpful, open and indispensable,'' he said.
   He said ``violence, terrorism and war are endemic'' in the
Middle East and the area ``is littered with broken agreements.''
   Shamir said the Camp David agreement, which led to a peace
treaty between Egypt and Israel in 1979 but failed to resolve the
Palestinian issue, ``should serve as our guide'' in the current
search for a negotiating formula.
   He said if past accords were ignored ``future agreements will be
meaningless.'' The Camp David agreement called for self-rule for
the 1.5 million Palestinian Arabs who live on the West Bank and in
Gaza for five years. Jordan and the Palestinians did not
participate in the talks, which ended in failure in 1981.
   Shultz has proposed a three-year interim arrangement, with talks
on an overall settlement of the Arab-Israeli dispute to begin by
December.
   On Sunday, in Israel, Shamir said ``after I come back with a
summation of my talks with representatives of the American
government, the cabinet will meet immediately and I think we'll
have a decision on this subject.''
   Meanwhile Monday, Hanna Siniora, a Palestinian who met here with
Shultz in late January, urged the secretary to make room at the
negotiating table for the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   At a news conference, Siniora, who is a newspaper editor in
Jerusalem, said ``so far there has not been a credible effort to
seek Palestinian representation.''
   Shultz's plan envisions a joint delegation of Jordanians and
Palestinians, who could participate only with the approval of the
PLO.
   But the PLO, which Shultz and Israel have branded a terrorist
group, would not take part directly. All the Arab governments have
endorsed Yasser Arafat's organization as the only legitimate
representative of the Palestinians.
</TEXT>
