<2ND_LINE>AM-Brush Fires, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0780,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Savage Fire Declared Under Control, But Cattle Low on Forage</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf pvs, `Gov. Bill ...' with two grafs to UPDATE
with disaster proclamation, availability of federal aid; SUBS 11th
graf pvs, `The Federal ...' to CLARIFY that aid will be
reimbursement of firefighting costs.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A wildfire that charred hundreds of square
miles of Texas prairie, killing cattle and wildlife, was declared
under control Monday, but surviving animals faced possible
starvation without forage or feed.
   Federal and state officials were organizing a hay donation
program for cattle roaming past burned fenceposts through the
blackened terrain.
   Officials declared the five-county fire under control Monday
about noon, said Murry Fly, the state Forest Service's head of
operations for fire control. But the forecast called for continuing
dry, windy weather.
   Damage was so widespread that crews were still trying to assess
it five days after flames from burning trash went out of control
near Abilene.
   Hundreds of firefighters, National Guardsmen and state and
federal workers contained the blaze after three days. The burned
swath covered parts of an area 56 miles long and 24 miles wide.
   ``There's been a tremendous amount of forage lost right now,''
Fly said.
   Lt. Gov. Bill Hobby issued a disaster proclamation Monday,
freeing up state money to help the area clean up and recover, said
Don Couch of the governor's Emergency Management Division. Gov.
Bill Clements was out of state.
   Bashur said representatives of the state Department of Emergency
Services will instruct local officials Tuesday on how individuals
can apply for relief grants from the federal government.
   In about 87,000 acres surveyed so far, more than 100 cattle were
killed or had to be destroyed, said Lawrence Winkler, agriculture
extension agent in Shackelford County, the hardest-hit county with
more than 250,000 acres burned. An additional 175 head were injured.
   Wildlife in the area also suffered, he said. A herd of about 20
antelope perished in the flames, according to ranchers who answered
questions about damage as they put in requests for hay and feed to
keep their livestock alive.
   There is a two-day supply of donated feed on hand, Winkler said.
Ranchers without winter forage for their herds will have to sell
their livestock, haul in hay or feed, or truck the cattle
elsewhere, he said.
   The Federal Emergency Management Agency will make disaster aid
available to reimburse firefighting costs in the five-county
region, said Bruce Miles, Forest Service director.
   If ranchers had to buy feed for all 15,000 cattle affected by
the fire, it would require 175 tons a day, at a daily cost of
$30,000, said Winkler.
   Over the weekend, ranchers from across Texas began donating hay.
By Sunday, tractor-trailers stacked with hay rolls were parked on
the courthouse square in Albany.
   At least seven firefighters were treated for minor injuries,
said Fly. The wildfire at one point threatened the towns of Albany,
Moran and Baird.
</TEXT>
