<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci was to ask
his Soviet counterpart at talks beginning Tuesday in Switzerland
whether highly publicized changes in Kremlin military doctrine mean
reductions in Soviet forces.
   Carlucci, meeting Tuesday through Thursday with Soviet Defense
Minister Dmitri Yazov, will also discuss arms control, human
rights, the proposed Soviet withdrawl from Afghanistan, and such
dangerous military situations as a collision between U.S. and
Soviet warships in the Black Sea last month, a senior Pentagon
official told reporters Monday.
   Carlucci has said he doesn't want the meeting to pre-empt talks
on reducing nuclear and conventional forces, but he does want to
ask Yazov about the emerging Soviet doctrine of ``reasonable
sufficiency.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BALBOA, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Panama Canal, still one of the
hemisphere's most important pieces of real estate, has allowed
ships to move between the Atlantic and Pacific without interruption
through nine months of political unrest.
   Nearly 13,000 vessels a year avoid the long voyage around Cape
Horn, the southern tip of South America, by traveling 50 miles from
sea to sea through the ``Big Ditch'' that opened in 1914. More than
140 million tons of cargo move through it every year.
   The Panama Canal Treaties signed in 1977 commit the United
States to turn over complete control of the canal and military
installations to Panama by midnight Dec. 31, 1999.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>STARKE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legal options dwindled Monday for convicted
murderer Willie Jasper Darden, who was scheduled to die in
Florida's electric chair Tuesday after surviving an unprecedented
six death warrants.
   The Florida Supreme Court refused to grant a stay Monday for
Darden, who became the focus of an international campaign against
capital punishment. It was the eighth time the high court had
upheld either his conviction or death sentence.
   Darden's immediately attorneys asked a federal judge in Tampa to
block the execution, and a federal appeals court in Atlanta was
standing by to consider an appeal. The attorneys have already filed
with the U.S. Supreme Court.
   Darden, who has maintained his innocence in the 1973 fatal
shooting of a Lakeland furniture store owner during a robbery, was
scheduled to be electrocuted at 7 a.m. Tuesday at Florida State
Prison near this North Florida town.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Experts have agreed on a name and definition for a
lingering attack of exhaustion sometimes called the ``yuppie
disease,'' but they still don't know its cause or cure.
   In a new report, 16 doctors who study the illness agreed to call
it chronic fatigue syndrome, and they settled on a detailed
definition. The purpose is to help researchers and physicians rule
out dozens of other diseases that can produce the same symptoms.
   ``It's a diagnosis of exclusion, and it has to be considered as
such even after you've ruled everything else out,'' said Dr. Gary
P. Holmes. ``You have to continue to be concerned that there is
something else going on. You have to keep an open mind and not
simply close the books.''
   Holmes, who studies the syndrome at the U.S. Centers for Disease
Control, was the chief author of the new definition, published in
the March issue of the Annals of Internal Medicine.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev
said Monday that ethnic minorities who have protested in his vast
country are raising old grievances but not challenging the
government's authority.
   On the first day of his tour of Yugoslavia, which has its own
nationality problems, the Soviet Communist Party chief was asked
about recent demonstrations and ethnic riots in southern Soviet
republics.
   ``Show me the country in which there are no such problems,'' he
replied. ``If you show me, I will travel there right away, without
stopping in Moscow on return from Yugoslavia.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pressure mounted Monday on Pakistan to sign an
Afghan settlement aimed at securing the withdrawal of an estimated
115,000 Soviet troops and end nine years of fighting in Afghanistan.
   Sources close to the talks said the Pakistani chief
representative, acting Foreign Minister Zain Noorani, received a
message from the Kremlin calling upon him to sign the documents
without further delay.
   The chief Afghan negotiator, Foreign Minister Abdul Wakil,
scheduled a news conference for Tuesday, the day Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev named as a target date for the conclusion of
the nearly 6-year-old talks. Gorbachev said Moscow will bring home
its troops starting May 15 if the settlement is signed Tuesday.
</TEXT>
