<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-88 0717EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APArts:Lola Adv16   03-14 0608</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP Arts: Lola, Adv 16,0626</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 16</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed PMs, March 16 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>The Queen of Ranchera Music</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAVIER PICHARDINI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All you have to say in Mexico is Lola la
Grande, or Lola the Great One, and everyone knows who you're
talking about.
   Lola is Lola Beltran, the queen of ranchera music, whose rich,
husky and wide-ranged voice can evoke the pain and happiness of
love, tender feelings for the land or the gaiety of a Mexican
fiesta.
   For 35 years, Beltran has shared those sounds of Mexico
throughout the world, often bringing tears to the eyes of homesick
Mexicans in the United States and elsewhere.
   ``My soul feels like crying. ... I need you so much and yet I
swore I would never tell you this,'' she sang in one of her first
concerts after she made a hit on Mexico City XEW radio station.
   ``Three days without looking at you ... three days crying for
you ... three days looking at the sunrise,'' she sang in another
song, this one written by a friend _ composer Jose Alfredo Jimenez,
the sad-faced, tragic figure of modern Mexican music who died an
early death and who became famous for songs about love, land, bars
and drink.
   ``I will always remember Jose Alfredo,'' Beltran said, recalling
the times they performed together in Mexican films. ``Since he
died, many beautiful things have disappeared. He was unique and
extraordinary. Only those who go to heaven can have his kind of
heart.''
   Jimenez wrote the lyrics that broke down barriers and appealed
to pure, raw, feelings. ``What can you know about life? When did
you ever open with me the doors to Tenampa?'' which is a popular
Mexico mariachi bar.
   On March 12, Beltran was honored in New York by the Hispanic
Association of Entertainment Writers.
   The honor came as the sounds of ``ranchera'' music gets new,
widespread attention in the United States from pop singer Linda
Ronstadt and her Spanish-language album ``Canciones de Mi Padre,''
or ``Songs of My Father.''
   Ronstadt, who was recently in Mexico rehearsing for her current
concert tour of the United States, said she always has been an
admirer of the regal Beltran.
   ``When I was growing up, my father used to play the records of
Lola Beltran, who has always been a great influence on my
singing,'' Ronstadt recalled.
   ``I love that young girl,'' Beltran said. ``Whenever I am in the
United States, she comes to see me and when she comes here, I am
happy to receive her.''
   Beltran and Ronstadt performed a duet last fall at the Acapulco
Film Festival.
   ``I am very grateful to everyone,'' Beltran said in an
interview. ``I have been lucky enough to sing for people like
(Presidents) Eisenhower, Nixon and (former French President
Charles) De Gaulle.''
   Like most music of the people, ``ranchera'' music is similar to
American country music, with a few Mexican variations.
   ``May the devil take you, you murderous bull,'' Beltran curses
in a soulful song that recounts the death of a young boy who sneaks
into the corrals and is killed by the brave bulls under a moonlit
night.
   Since Beltran's first three songs on XEW, she has maded more
than 100 albums and acted in more than 50 movies.
   However, she is not as active as she used to be years ago when
she would sing before a weekly TV audience or in between cockfights.
   But she does three benefits every year and has an invitation to
sing at the University of Southern California next May.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Wed March 16</NOTE>
</DOC>
