<1ST_LINE>a i PM-France-DeuxChevaux Adv22   03-14 0824</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Deux Chevaux, Adv 22,0848</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv22</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tues PMs March 22 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Demise of the Deux Chevaux, a French Automotive Institution</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For nearly half a century, mountains, deserts and
Paris' traffic couldn't stop it _ that chugging, ungainly
four-wheeled beast known as the Deux Chevaux. But modern times
have, and an era in the French auto industry has come to an end.
   The Deux Chevaux (French for two horses, or two horsepower) is a
car, although some say it is an exaggeration to call it that _ tin
can on wheels is more like it. The last one rolled off a French
assembly line Feb. 29 when France's oldest automobile factory, the
Citroen plant in Levallois, shut down.
   There was hardly a whimper or a word in the press.
   Yet the closing of the plant on the western edge of Paris
signals the demise of the tortoise-shaped automotive with bulging
headlights that look like a frog's eyes.
   So ends an institution as French as the beret or baguette.
   Whether rattling down a country road or careening across a city
boulevard, with its side windows flapping on their hinges, the Deux
Chevaux has long been part of the French landscape. Its snail's
pace and its noisy chugs have endeared millions, spawning Deux
Chevaux fan clubs worldwide.
   ``When the last car left the factory in Levallois, you can say
it was the end of an era,'' said Gro Hoeg, a Citroen spokeswoman.
``But you can't say it is the end of the Deux Chevaux.''
   The car will continue to be manufactured in Portugal, but at
less than half the 1987 rate, when 43,255 Deux Chevaux were turned
out.
   ``I don't have great patriotic sentiment, but it's the only car
with a French identity,'' said three-time Deux Chevaux owner Gilles
Collignon.
   The Deux Chevaux was conceived as an affordable car for those of
modest means.
   When it first came out the Deux Chevaux cost the franc
equivalent of about $650. The two latest models cost $6,500 and
$7,460.
   Like sensible shoes, the buggy with bed-spring suspension, a
simple engine, no ``extras,'' is functional in the extreme. And
allegedly indestructible.
   Funny looking to some people, downright ugly to others, the Deux
Chevaux is simply ``beyond beauty,'' says Citroen. In the 1960s,
Deux Chevaux's heyday, it became a reverse status symbol among the
rebellious young.
   ``It's more than a car,'' said Collignon. ``Everyone who has one
has a more or less sentimental relationship with it.
   ``The big advantage is that it can be completely falling apart,
broken all over, and it keeps running. It has an incredible life.''
   The Deux Chevaux has set altitude and depth records for a car _
climbing to 17,180 feet on Bolivia's Mount Chacaltaya in 1953 and
down deep into a salt mine in France's Lorraine region.
   Two Frenchmen, Jacques Seguela and Jean-Claude Baudot, made an
87,000-mile round-the-world trip in a Deux Chevaux, once resorting
to crushed bananas to replace oil lost from a broken gearbox during
a 200-mile desert stretch.
   ``Four wheels under an umbrella'' was the order to engineers
working on the design in the 1930s, according to Citroen, which
later touted it as ``the most minimum car.''
   A wooden model was produced in 1936. World War II intervened,
and the car was not formally unveiled until October 1948 at the
Paris Auto show.
   Originally available only in gray, with a top speed of 37 miles
an hour, today's Deux Chevaux streak by in all colors, or even
two-tone, and can reach a top speed of 72 mph.
   The upgraded engine remains mechanically elementary and the
horsepower has increased from two to three.
   Citroen brochures call the Deux Chevaux ``a mechanical
phenomenon, a commercial phenomenon, a sociological phenomenon.''
But the truth, Ms. Hoeg concedes, is that the car is outmoded.
   ``Orders have fallen a lot,'' she said in a telephone interview.
``The European market is increasingly closed to the Deux Chevaux
because of pollution norms.''
   Strict pollution controls, for example, have effectively banned
the car from Switzerland and Austria since October 1987. It has not
been sold in Sweden since 1968 and in Finland since 1982 because it
doesn't come up to their safety standards. Deux Chevaux fans in
other countries are expected to be deprived of the car in the
coming years, Ms. Hoeg said. No effort was ever made to sell it in
the United States, but she said she understands there are some Deux
Chevaux collectors there.
   The closing of the Levallois plant, built in 1893, is part of an
overall retrenchment of the French auto industry. At its peak in
the mid-1960s, the plant turned out 550 Deux Chevaux a day,
compared to 80 a day last year.
   The Citroen plant in Manguade, Portugal, manufacturing Deux
Chevaux since 1982, is expected to produce about 20,000 in 1988.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Tues PMs March 22</NOTE>
