<1ST_LINE>a a BC-History Adv20   03-14 0449</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-History, Adv 20,0468</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv20</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 20th</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Today is Sunday, March 20, the 80th day of 1988. There are 286
days left in the year. This is the first day of spring.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On March 20, 1852, Harriet Beecher Stowe's influential novel
about slavery, ``Uncle Tom's Cabin,'' was first published.
   On this date:
   In 1727, physicist, mathematician and astronomer Sir Isaac
Newton died in London.
   In 1815, Napoleon Bonaparte entered Paris, beginning his
``Hundred Days'' rule.
   In 1833, the United States and Siam concluded a commercial
treaty.
   In 1896, U.S. Marines landed in Nicaragua to protect U.S.
citizens in the wake of a revolution.
   In 1899, Martha M. Place of Brooklyn, N.Y., became the first
woman to be put to death by electrocution. She was executed at Sing
Sing for the murder of her stepdaughter.
   In 1942, during World War II, Gen. Douglas MacArthur vowed, ``I
shall return,'' having left the Philippines for Australia.
   In 1969, Beatle John Lennon married Yoko Ono in Gibraltar.
   In 1976, newspaper heiress Patricia Hearst was convicted of
armed robbery for her part in a San Francisco bank holdup.
   In 1977, voters in Paris chose former French Prime Minister
Jacques Chirac to become the French capital's first mayor in more
than a century.
   In 1980, the United States went before the International Court
of Justice in The Hague to appeal for the release of the American
hostages in Iran.
   In 1981, former girls' school headmistress Jean Harris was
sentenced in White Plains, N.Y., to 15 years to life in prison for
the slaying of ``Scarsdale Diet'' author Dr. Herman Tarnower.
   Ten years ago: Israeli troops tightened their grip on southern
Lebanon, creating a ``security belt'' paralleling the border
between the two countries.
   Five years ago: NBC broadcast ``Special Bulletin,'' a movie
which depicted a nuclear extortion threat against Charleston, S.C.
The program, in the form of a simulated newscast, alarmed some
viewers who thought the events being portrayed were real.
   One year ago: The Food and Drug Administration approved the sale
of AZT, a drug shown to prolong the lives of some AIDS patients.
   Today's Birthdays: Producer-director-comedian Carl Reiner is 66.
Comedian Ray Goulding is 66. Actor Jack Kruschen is 66. Former
Nixon White House aide John Ehrlichman is 63. Children's TV host
Fred Rogers is 60. Actor Hal Linden is 57. Actor Ted Bessell is 52.
Singer Jerry Reed is 51. The prime minister of Canada, Brian
Mulroney, is 49. Hockey hall-of-famer Bobby Orr is 40. Actor
William Hurt is 38.
   Thought for Today: ``The heaviest baggage for a traveler is an
empty purse.'' -- German proverb.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
