<1ST_LINE>a i AM-BeriaRemembered Adv21-2Takes   03-14 0753</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Beria Remembered, Adv 21-2 Takes,0769</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv21</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, March 21 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>The Name Lavrenti Beria Still Brings Chills to Soviets</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Spelling ``Sergo'' correct start of 14th graf.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lavrenti Beria.
   The mere mention of the name stills brings chills to some
Soviets.
   In the 1960s, years after his death, people still avoided
walking past his drab mansion at 28 Kachalov St. in Moscow because
of the terrible memories it might evoke.
   Now, 34 years after Beria's own execution, the mansion houses
the Tunisian Embassy.
   Ambassador Abderraouf Ounaies of Tunisia said there were stories
that Beria had a dungeon built in the basement and a secret
passageway. Some areas of the basement could have been used as a
dungeon, Ounaies said, but he found no evidence of that they
actually were used for that, nor was there evidence of a secret
passageway.
   The curse seems to have worn off. People these days walk by,
apparently without giving a thought to Lavrenti Beria, the balding,
small Georgian who wore pince-nez and is held responsible for the
executions of millions during the Stalin era.
   ``Every generation has its horrors,'' said an elderly
neighborhood woman, who recalled seeing Beria strolling outside the
mansion when he lived there.
   The administration of General Secretary Mikhail S. Gorbachev
says it wants the current generation of Soviets to know the truth
about the past, and is reviving nightmares about Beria and the
machine of terror he ran in the late 1930s and 1940s as Stalin's
most ruthless and powerful henchman.
   Press articles and the portrayal of a Beria-Hitler-like
character in the recent Georgian movie ``Repentance'' are part of
Gorbachev's attempts to fill in ``blank spots'' in history _
formerly taboo subjects. He believes that extending his policy of
glasnost, or openness, to the crimes of the Stalin era will help
ensure that such mistakes are not repeated.
   The effort parallels Gorbachev's drive to rid Soviet society of
Stalinist policies under which the central government exercised
tight control over the economy.
   Sergo A. Mikoyan, the son of the late Anastas I. Mikoyan who had
served with Beria in the Stalin leadership, wrote Feb. 21 in the
youth newspaper Komsomolskaya Pravda that it is important to review
Beria ``to finally free the future from the past.''
   Beria's legacy is the image of the state security forces as
all-powerful and ruthless. In their re-examination of Stalin and
Beria, Soviet media have not touched on this image as it pertains
to the present-day KGB, successor to Beria's NKVD. Also
conspicuously absent is any criticism of the system that enabled
such a pair to take charge and to operate their machine of terror
for so long.
   This is not the first time the official media have focused on
Beria's reign of terror. He was first exposed during Nikita S.
Khrushchev's de-Stalinization drive in the 1950s and 60s.
Khrushchev, in his memoirs _ published only in the West _ called
Beria ``a butcher and an assassin,'' a ``beast'' who was ``without
the slightest trace of human decency'' and who was ``very skillful
at anything that was filthy and treacherous.''
   Although Beria was sharply condemned during Khrushchev's years,
the early official accounts inacurrately described his relationship
with Stalin.
   ``We refused to believe that Stalin himself could have been
behind the terror which Beria oversaw,'' Khrushchev wrote. ``For a
while, we gave the party and the people incorrect explanations
about what had happened; we blamed everything on Beria. He was a
convenient figure.''
   The truth, Khrushchev said, was that ``Beria didn't create
Stalin; Stalin created Beria.''
   Only now, under Gorbachev, is the official record being
corrected, with the help of Sergo Mikoyan and the sons of other
members of Stalin's Politburo, Georgy M. Malenkov and Khrushchev.
Andrei G. Malenkov and Sergei N. Khrushchev are quoted in a recent
edition of Nedelya, a weekly supplement to the Literary Gazette
newspaper. That and the other articles put the blame squarely on
Stalin.
   ``I believe that the roots of Beria's evil deeds should be
sought in the personality of Stalin rather than in Beria himself,''
Nikolai Zhusyenin wrote in Nedelya. ``Namely the cult, the
deviation from Leninist norms, resulted in the Beria phenomenon.
Beria was able to guess Stalin's wishes, was able to exploit the
weaknesses of his master for personal profit and
self-glorification.''
   Zhusyenin said that when he interviewed people, ``their arms
began to tremble at the very mention of the name Beria.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880314-0246 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-88 1319EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i AM-BeriaRemembered Adv21-1stAdd   03-14 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Beria Remembered, Adv 21-1st Add,0583</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv21</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, March 21 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>MOSCOW: name Beria.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The writers of the recent articles said they had trouble
researching Beria because he did such a good job of covering his
tracks, making sure that any evidence that could be used against
him was destroyed and witnesses killed.
   Komsomolskaya Pravda stated the new evaluation of Stalin's
relationship with Beria in its headline over Sergo Mikoyan's
article: ``The Servant.''
   Stalin tapped Beria, a fellow Georgian, to be deputy head of the
already-dreaded NKVD, as the state security and police force was
known at the time, in the summer of 1938. By year's end, Beria
replaced NKVD chief Nikolai Yezhov, who had fallen out of favor
with Stalin and was executed in 1940.
   The people breathed a sigh of relief, hoping that the years of
bloody mass purges were behind them. Mass arrests did end, but the
terror continued. Beria simply made it more selective, playing on
Stalin's paranoia by identifying and eliminating those deemed to be
``enemies of the people.''
   In the meantime, he garnered a staggering amount of power. Beria
became the first secret police chief elevated to the Communist
Party's ruling Politburo. During World War II, Stalin named Beria
to the committee supervising defense and later put him in charge of
developing a Soviet atomic bomb. After the war, Beria controlled
the regular and secret police, the country's labor camps,
propaganda and transport, as well as a private empire in his native
Georgia and surrounding regions.
   Among the horrors Western historians link to Beria was the
massacre of more than 4,000 Polish officers in the Katyn Forest
near Smolensk by NKVD troops in April 1940. The official Soviet
version is that the Poles were killed by Germans.
   On a personal level, Soviet accounts of Beria said he
interrogated and executed prisoners himself. Khrushchev claimed
Beria raped teen-age girls after having them kidnapped off the
streets.
   Beria's intrigues also took a heavy toll on the party itself.
Nedyelya noted that Beria collected files on every government
leader, including Stalin, for possible use against them. His
victims included veteran party members, comrades-in-arms of V.I.
Lenin and officials of the party youth group Komsomol, Nedyelya
said.
   Even Stalin began to fear Beria, and by 1946 had taken away all
his henchman's security posts. But Beria retained unofficial
control over the security organs, and planned to use his forces to
seize power after Stalin's death in March 1953.
   Khrushchev, in his memoirs and in remarks cited Feb. 24 in
Literary Gazette, said he was aware of Beria's ambitions and
suggested privately to the other top leaders in the summer of 1953
that they oust Beria. They agreed. The Politburo, in Beria's
presence, met and voted to arrest him. Military troops outside
Beria's control took him to prison. He was put on trial, convicted
of being a British agent _ a dubious charge _ and of trying to
``elevate the Ministry of Internal Affairs above the party and
government in order to seize power.''
   Official accounts say he was executed Dec. 23, 1953, but some
Western historians believe he was put to death months earlier.
   Beria, who had been in the limelight for 14 years, quickly
became a non-person. The editors of the official Soviet
encyclopedia, for example, told readers to paste an article about
the Bering Strait over one about Beria.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, March 21</NOTE>
