<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-88 1338EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s w BC-APN--AirlineTurmoil Adv27-2Takes   03-14 1017</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Airline Turmoil, Adv 27-2 Takes,1046</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv27</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 27</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 2 b&w
photos and 1 graphic.)</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Labor relations in the airline industry used to
be fairly genteel and mutual accommodation was the rule. Then,
after deregulation, came a competitive crunch, mergers and
cost-cutting, and at many carriers snarl has replaced purr. A
reporter surveys today's turbulent scene.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of Pan American World Airways and
several senior executives are fired after a closed-door deal with
the airline's labor unions.
   Flight attendants trek to the suburban home of the chairman of
Trans World Airlines to register a protest about a strike that
ended nearly two years ago. More than 4,000 of them are still
looking to get their jobs back.
   Eastern Airlines, expecting a strike, is planning for a small
cargo carrier with non-union pilots to fly many of its passenger
planes, prompting charges of union busting from Eastern pilots and
mechanics.
   It's management and labor hardball, pure and simple.
   And it has become more frequent since the government eased out
of regulating the airline industry in the early 1980s. Along with
bitter competition among airlines have come increasingly
acrimonious relations with labor.
   In the wars between airline workers and their bosses, the
genteel atmosphere of bargaining _ common when the government had
its reins on the industry _ seems to have gone the way of the
propeller airplane.
   The hotbed of labor-management combat is at Eastern, the
Miami-based airline that has struggled with huge losses and almost
continuous labor turmoil for more than a decade. The company wants
major concessions. The unions say they're being pushed into a
strike.
   When word came recently that 26 Eastern jets were being leased
to a little known cargo operator named Orion Air, the news
unleashed a firestorm among many of Eastern's employees.
   It was no secret that Eastern, in the midst of stormy contract
talks with its mechanics, intends in event of a strike this summer
to have non-union Orion Air pilots fly the leased planes on
Eastern's most critical routes.
   ``It's an attempt to decimate Eastern's cockpit crews,'' says
Jack Bavis, head of the airline's pilots union. There are hints
from the parent 40,000-member Air Line Pilots Association of a
one-day nationwide shutdown of air service if Eastern ever uses the
Orion pilots.
   Thomas Matthews, Eastern's vice president for human relations,
calls the non-union Orion pilots ``our insurance coverage.''
   Corporate hardball.
   ``Prior to deregulation, for maybe 20 years, there was a posture
of accommodation. The unions accepted the companies and the
companies accepted the unions. Government generally was neutral or
slightly on the side of labor,'' says Frank Cassels, a professor of
industrial relations at Northwestern University.
   When labor wanted more money, the airlines often agreed. They
knew that the government would pass the increased costs on in the
form of higher fares. Today, airlines compete vigorously on fares
and have argued that one of their biggest problems has been high
labor costs. On average, 35 percent of airline operational costs
are for labor, according to the Air Transport Association.
   As a result, there has been ``a stage of outright hostility''
between labor and management in recent years, Cassels says.
   The tiff at Eastern may be the latest, but it's hardly the most
bitter standoff between labor and management in recent years.
   It was in September 1983 that Frank Lorenzo, chairman of Texas
Air Corp., the nemesis of airline labor, stopped negotiating with
the unions and shut down Continental Airlines. He declared
bankruptcy and shed the existing labor contracts.
   Three days later, Continental emerged with pilots flying the
same planes, but earning half the salary. Pilots and flight
attendants saw their strike fizzle.
   Today, Continental, which like Eastern is owned by Texas Air
Corp., is larger than ever, but many of its one-time well-paid
pilots are wearing the uniforms of other airlines and have lost
much of their seniority and pay.
   In early 1986 the flight attendants at TWA, faced with demands
for sharp salary cuts, walked off their jobs and onto the picket
lines. Today two-thirds of the 6,500 attendants who went on strike
are still grounded. While the attendants await a recall from TWA,
the airline continues to fly with a third fewer attendants who earn
less money and work longer hours.
   Would the flight attendants again choose a strike?
   Victoria Frankovich, president of the Independent Federation of
Flight Attendants, who led the 1986 walkout, mulls the question
over before answering. ``I don't think we had a choice,'' she says.
   Attendants at other airlines may not have lost their jobs in
recent years, but they have not been able to exert much clout.
Recently, flight attendants were pushed reluctantly into a
settlement at American and thought better of a strike at Northwest,
where negotiations continue.
   But labor _ at least in terms of the more-powerful pilots and
mechanics unions _ has flexed its muscles as well after several
years of back-pedaling and reeling from management demands.
   Consider the fired Pan Am executives.
   William T. Coleman, with the blessing of fellow members of the
Pan Am board of directors, resigned and sealed the deal with a
handshake last January. He then walked into the office of Pan Am
Chairman C. Edward Acker and informed Acker and Vice Chairman
Martin Shugrue they were fired.
   By the time the bloodletting was over, three senior vice
presidents, including Raymond Grebey, who was in charge of labor
relations, also were forced to resign.
   Acker is now in Bermuda ``assessing what he's going to do
next.'' Shugrue recently was hired by Texas Air Corp. to head its
Continental Airlines subsidiary.
   Richard Ferris can understand how they feel.
   A former hotel executive, Ferris had a dream of turning United
Airlines into a broad-based travel company. While at the helm of
UAL Inc., he bought two hotel chains and a rental car company and
envisioned one-stop shopping for transportation and lodging for
businessmen.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
