<DOCNO> AP880314-0252 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-88 1339EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s w BC-APN--AirlineTurmoil Adv27-1stAdd   03-14 0876</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Airline Turmoil, Adv 27-1st Add,0901</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv27</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 27</NOTE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON: for businessmen.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The name of UAL Inc., was changed to Allegis Corp., to broaden
its appeal, but the moniker never caught on among Wall Street
investors. It also served to highlight claims by the pilots that
Ferris was siphoning money and attention from the airline.
   One evening last June, the company's board of directors demanded
Ferris' resignation. The pilots claimed responsibility.
   Although Ferris' fall may have been the result of a variety of
forces, most industry analysts agree that his empire began to fail
when the pilots union launched a $4.5 billion takeover bid, the
first effort by a union to buy an entire airline.
   ``Anyone who thinks that the pilots union or the machinists
today are the underdogs in one of these battles is clearly
mistaken,'' says Clark Onstad, a vice president for Texas Air.
   Indeed, pilots at many airlines have regained the momentum.
Their salaries are on the upswing. The dual wage scales _ a lower
one for newly hired pilots _ imposed by American Airlines in 1983
and widely copied by other carriers is showing signs of erosion.
New contracts call for a more rapid merging of the two scales.
   The Air Line Pilots Association, caught unprepared and
disorganized by the Continental bankruptcy, has vowed never to be
left so vulnerable again. Stiff increases in dues for its 40,000
members have brought $40 million into a war chest that continues to
grow.
   The unions also say they will continue to take their fights into
airline board rooms, citing their successes at United, Pan Am and
at TWA where the pilots formed an unusual alliance with corporate
raider Carl Icahn two years ago to fend off Lorenzo's Texas Air.
   Ironically, that set the stage for Lorenzo to buy Eastern, where
labor war remains rife. Nevertheless, declares ALPA president Henry
Duffy, ``Labor unions will continue to increase their Wall Street
connections.''
   ``Certainly in this day and age you won't get (salary or work
rule) givebacks,'' says Robert Joedicke, airline analyst for
Shearson Lehman Bros. But he adds quickly that he wouldn't ``put
the unions in the catbird seat'' just yet.
   Nowhere is that more true than at Texas Air, the Houston-based
airline whose Continental and Eastern subsidiaries account for 20
percent of the industry's market and which has led the trend toward
lower airline fares.
   Lorenzo made his mark in 1972 when he bought debt-ridden Texas
International and turned it around by unleashing ``peanut fares''
when business was slow. His low-fare strategy continued with New
York Air in 1981 and with the newly emerged Continental two years
later.
   But to play out the strategy, Lorenzo had to cut costs, a direct
attack on labor.
   ``Does Frank like unions? That's not the issue,'' says Onstad,
Lorenzo's point man in Washington. ``The issue is how does
management get the flexibility to deal in a deregulated environment
that Frank is dealing with.''
   Onstad says that some members of the machinists union,
especially ground workers who haul baggage, are earning salaries _
an average of $43,000 a year with fringes _ that are way too high.
   When Continental emerged with a non-union work force in 1983 it
had cut its pilots' pay in half overnight. Continental workers in
1986 earned on average $28,200 a year, the lowest in the industry,
and better than a third lower than its chief competitors.
   Mechanics at Continental earn $16 an hour base salary, $4 an
hour lower than new contracts agreed to at United and USAir,
according to the machinist union.
   In the third quarter of last year, Continental's labor costs
were 22 percent of total operating costs, compared to about 35
percent industrywide.
   But Texas Air executives argue that low costs are needed if the
airline is to survive and continue to provide the low fares that
have opened air travel to millions of people.
   Texas Air Corp., lost $466 million last year and its executives
put much of the blame on costs related to absorbing People Express
and the labor unrest at Eastern, where losses were $182 million.
   Eastern president Philip Bakes has said he wants $490 million in
labor concessions at the struggling airline. Union leaders
countered that they have given back too much already and accuse
Lorenzo of trying to dismember the airline.
   Jack Bavis, the pilot's leader at Eastern, says that since
Lorenzo bought the airline he has:
   _Sold Eastern's valuable computer reservation system to Texas
Air.
   _Cleared the way for Continental to fly Eastern's profitable
Latin America routes if Lorenzo chooses to.
   _Sold six Eastern Airbus A-300s and a McDonnell Douglas DC-10 to
Continental.
   _Tried to spin-off Eastern's moneymaking Northeast air shuttle
operation under a separate subsidiary.
   ``He's taking the crown jewels, spinning them off and making
them part of Texas Air,'' says Charlie Bryan, the chief of the
International Association of Machinists at Eastern.
   Onstad suggests the Eastern negotations have industrywide
implications.
   ``We are now the last of the low-cost operators. People focus
all of their attention on Texas Air,'' Onstad says. ``If the unions
can defeat us, low fares go away and the pressure on wages at other
airlines go away.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV for Sunday, March 27</NOTE>
