<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-88 1351EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--ConductorRattle Adv27   03-14 1066</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Conductor Rattle, Adv 27,1106</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv27</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 27</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ Five years after he became conductor of the City
of Birmingham Symphony Orchestra at age 25, Simon Rattle thought it
could become Britain's best. At 33, he hasn't changed his mind.
Rattle, who is attracting a lot of attention in the world of music,
is now bringing the orchestra to America to show it off in 11
cities.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's Simon Rattle, who has become known as
one of the world's most exciting young conductors, is introducing
his City of Birmingham Symphony Orchestra to American audiences for
the first time.
   The orchestra, which Rattle believes is ``well on the way'' to
becoming Britain's finest, will tour 11 U.S. cities from March 29
to April 17.
   Rattle has made his mark in the music world without joining the
baton-wielding jet set or accepting a top job with a prestigious
orchestra. In fact, he regularly turns down offers to appear as
guest conductor.
   The 33-year-old native of Liverpool, England, prefers to
concentrate on his job as conductor of the Birmingham orchestra and
his work as principal guest of the Los Angeles Philharmonic.
   The curly haired, bright-eyed Rattle took over the Birmingham
orchestra in 1980, at age 25. He plans to stay a while, already
making plans for the orchestra into the next century.
   Before he went to Birmingham, Rattle was the No. 2 conductor
with the Royal Liverpool Philharmonic and the BBC Scottish Symphony
and did a lot of guest conducting. ``In some ways,'' he says, ``I
was following a more conventional career pattern than I seem to be
now.''
   Rattle is not without his fans in the United States.
   In the words of critic Andrew Porter in the New Yorker magazine,
Rattle is considered a first-rate conductor who ``inspires players
and elates audiences.''
   Just before Rattle conducted the Los Angeles Philharmonic in his
1985 New York debut, critic Nicholas Kenyon wrote in The New York
Times: ``The biggest surprise about this debut by the most
brilliantly successful conductor of the younger generation in
Britain _ the perception, power and clarity of whose work has been
acclaimed internationally _ is not the age at which it is occurring
but the fact that it did not happen long ago. Mr. Rattle has been
invited to the Metropolitan Opera and he has been invited to the
New York Philharmonic. He has turned both down.''
   During a recent stopover in New York, Rattle was asked if an
offer from a prestigious orchestra would lure him away from
Birmingham.
   ``I've been given enough offers that haven't,'' he answers,
declining to elaborate. It is known that in 1984 he rejected an
invitation from the Los Angeles Philharmonic to become its music
director.
   ``The work in Birmingham is so satisfying,'' he says. ``And it
is also unfinished. Now we're planning a festival. Starting in
1991, we'll do spring festivals, each year concentrating on the
music of one decade of 20th century music.
   ``In 2000 we'll just about have caught up with ourselves. In
1999, when we're dealing with the music of the '90s, we will surely
be playing music by people who now are schoolchildren.''
   Rattle said in 1985 that he thought the Birmingham Symphony
could become the best in Britain.
   ``I think they're well on the way,'' he says now.
   ``My wife tells me I always refer to the City of Birmingham
Symphony Orchestra as `us,' which is true,'' he says. ``We consider
that we've been able to grow together. They play beautifully as a
unit. There's a degree of listening to each other as an ensemble,
like chamber music playing, that is unique in Britain.''
   Though he has made a lot of music documentaries for television,
surveying trends or about a particular composer's work, Rattle says
he isn't a TV ``natural'' like Andre Previn.
   ``Andre created an extraordinary new audience in England for
music. He can talk to the camera as though it was his best friend.
It's something I admire enormously. I can't do that.''
   Rattle's father briefly led a jazz band. While he appreciates
jazz, the younger Rattle knew from the time he entered the Royal
Academy of Music at age 16 that he would conduct. He thought he'd
have to be an instrumentalist _ he was a percussionist _ first,
whose conducting career would only be beginning ``about now.''
   Conducting happened sooner because Rattle won a conetst. ``I
went in simply because if you got in the final 10, there was a
chance to work with the Bournemouth Symphony,'' he says. ``I was 19
and I'd never conducted a professional orchestra.
   ``I still think I only won because it never occurred to me that
I might win and I had no anxiety. The final piece I conducted was
Strauss' `Don Juan,' which takes 17 minutes. There were 20 minutes
to rehearse it. At that age, it was probably just as well. I didn't
have time to get up the noses of the musicians.''
   Studying conducting, Rattle says, he learned that ``there's as
much connection with what your baton does to the orchestra as to
what a violinist's bow does to the strings. All motions a conductor
makes affect the orchestra, even if you don't want them to.
   ``The reason a conductor begins to get halfway competent around
50 or 60 is that he probably has had as much time in front of an
orchestra then as the average 20-year-old violinist has had playing
his instrument.
   ``At a certain point, to be able to communicate what you know,
you have to know your musicians. That's the reason I went down the
road of working very hard with one orchestra.''
   One of the reasons Rattle limits his guest conducting is that he
and his American wife, soprano Elise Ross, and 4-year-old son
Alexander, known as Sasha, like to spend time together.
   ``I'm not one of those musicians who wants to live a life which
is entirely the musician part,'' he says. ``I'd like to be able to
explore the richness of life. There is enough else going on in the
world to put music in perspective.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV for Sunday, March 27</NOTE>
