<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-88 1353EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--TVWeek Adv27   03-14 0865</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--TV Week, Adv 27,0884</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv27</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 27</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the time came for President Lincoln's
secretary of war to point out Gen. Robert E. Lee's route into
Pennsylvania, he had to seek help from a private.
   ``We were filming a scene and we couldn't find the place on the
map,'' says Sam Waterston, who portrays Abraham Lincoln in the NBC
miniseries ``Gore Vidal's Lincoln.'' ``The only person who knew the
route was a private.''
   The private was one of the Civil War re-enactors who served as
Union and Confederate soldiers for the four-hour adaptation of
Vidal's book about life inside the White House.
   `They were just an enormous resource in helping the rest of us,
who were just pretending, to feel authentic,'' says Waterston. ``I
remember riding down a street and there were small groups of Union
soldiers along the way. They came to attention as I passed. They
did it according to Civil War drill.
   ``They were immensely supportive of the rest of us. They saved
us more than once when we needed information, like with Lee's
route.''
   ``Lincoln,'' which will be televised on Sunday and Monday, also
stars Mary Tyler Moore as Mary Todd Lincoln, John Houseman as Gen.
Winfield Scott, Richard Mulligan as Secretary of State William
Seward, John McMartin as Ohio Sen. Salmon P. Chase, who hopes to
become president, and Deborah Adair as Chase's overly ambitious
daughter, Kate.
   In an ironic twist on history, the Washington scenes were filmed
in Richmond, Va., the capital of the Confederacy. The Confederate
Home for Needy Women, built as a replica of the original White
House, was used as the executive mansion. Petersburg, where Lee put
up his last defense before surrendering at Appomattox, was also
used for some Washington scenes.
   ``The side benefit of that was that everyone had an enormous
interest in the Civil War,'' Waterston says. ``One man came up to
me and said, `If you were the man you're pretending to be I'd want
to shoot you.' We got into quite a discussion.''
   Waterston says he had not seen any Lincoln portrayals in a long
time and had purposely avoided looking at any.
   ``Henry Fonda seems to me to be the closest to what I imagine he
was really like,'' Waterston says. Fonda appeared in ``Young Mr.
Lincoln'' in 1939. ``But I didn't see anything. The danger is that
you'll be influenced. In college a friend was doing `Richard III'
and made the fatal mistake of seeing Laurence Olivier's film about
five days before we opened. He couldn't put it out of his head.''
   Waterston says he read a lot of books on Lincoln, including one
by William Safire, one-time speech writer for President Richard M.
Nixon.
   ``If Safire meddles with the facts, he tells you how,''
Waterston says. ``If he's interpreting, he tells you the opposing
views so you don't have to read 17 different books to get all the
viewpoints.''
   Waterston says when he read Vidal's book he thought it would
make good television. ``It's the Civil War as seen from the White
House, which is different from the usual way of looking in from the
outside. It shows how Lincoln responded to the pressure of events.
I think what's most extraordinary was that he was not perfectly
attuned to every situation.
   ``But when the chips were down he was up to the occasion. That's
what people have found remarkable about him _ how could a man of
his background find the skills to manage a war on a scale that no
one had ever imagined. His law partner once described him as a man
who read less and thought more than anyone he had ever known.''
   Waterston also spent time trying to understand the man. ``Edwin
Stanton called him `the Illinois gorilla,''' he says. ``It
certainly takes a breadth of mind to hire that same man as your
secretary of war.''
   Waterston, who is somewhat Lincolnesque in build and looks, says
he has wanted to portray Lincoln for a long time.
   ``There ought to be some reward for looking like this,'' he
says. ``I thought he was a fascinating man. You can't help but be
in awe of this combination of high principle and amazing public
skills.''
   It was Waterston's third opportunity to work with Mary Tyler
Moore. Previously, they were in ``Finnegan Begin Again'' and ``Just
Between Friends.'' He says he found her portrayal of Mrs. Lincoln
as a woman on the edge ``very bold and interesting.''
   Waterson is currently starring with Robert Prosky in the New
York play ``A Walk in the Woods.'' Playwright Lee Blessing based it
on a real incident in which two arms negotiators, one American and
one Soviet, worked out a deal during a walk in the woods in Geneva,
Switzerland.
   This is one of the rare TV appearances for Waterston, who was
nominated for an Academy Award for ``The Killing Fields,'' although
he did star in a series six years ago, ``Q.E.D.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV for Sunday, March 27</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880314-0259 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-88 1354EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--TheaterWeek Adv27   03-14 0852</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Theater Week, Adv 27,0876</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv27</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 27</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carole Shorenstein Hays put her own money, some
$850,000, where her convictions were and brought ``Fences'' to
Broadway. Tony awards, a Pulitzer Prize and a lucrative film sale
were her reward.
   Smart money was against the play, Hays' first solo producing
venture.
   ``Listen kid, it ain't commercial,'' Hays deadpans, mimicking
the advice she got from seasoned theater professionals. They
cautioned against bringing to New York the August Wilson drama
about the upheavals of a black family during the late 1950s.
   ``It was important for me to do `Fences' because I believed in
it,'' the producer said the other day, between coos to her infant
son, Wally, in a Fifth Avenue hotel suite. ``It was very important
for me to send out the word to young emerging American playwrights
that Broadway is a place where their dreams could be fulfilled. You
don't have to go to London or Hollywood.''
   Besides ``Fences,'' Wally, born Aug. 16, was Hays' other big
production last year.
   When Hays, wearing a maternity evening gown, clambered to the
stage of the Mark Hellinger Theater last June to accept a Tony as
producer of the best play of the season, she exclaimed, ``I think
I'm going to give birth right now.''
   She didn't. Little Walter Hays actually arrived some two months
later, but, according to Hays, ``He knows `Fences' inside and out.''
   The baby made his Broadway stage debut _ at age 8 weeks _ in the
show. Wrapped in a blanket, he was carried on stage by James Earl
Jones, who usually cradles a doll. Wally had to be kept covered,
though. He was playing a little black girl.
   ``I don't believe I did that,'' Hays laughs. ``I'm a real stage
mother.''
   Hays first saw ``Fences'' in January 1986 at Chicago's Goodman
Theater, while it was making the circuit of various regional
theaters. By intermission, she knew she wanted to produce the play.
   She met with director Lloyd Richards, who had first done the
show at the Yale Repertory Theater in Connecticut, with author
Wilson and Jones.
   ``It was all very simple,'' she recalls. ``I said, `I want to do
this. It will be done. I have a theater in San Francisco.'''
   Hays actually runs three theaters there _ the Curran, the Golden
Gate and the Orpheum _ all owned by her family. Her father is
Walter H. Shorenstein, a California real estate mogul. Three years
ago, Forbes magazine estimated the family fortune at some $300
million.
   Hays always was stage-struck. Theater-going was the big family
activity. She remembers as a child putting on her party dress and
white gloves and going to the theater.
   When her family got into theater real estate, Hays got into the
theater business.
   ``I started at the bottom of the top,'' she recalls, learning
what it takes to put on a play. Until ``Fences,'' though, she had
never produced a show on her own.
   ``I think the easiest thing is to find other investors,'' Hays
says. ``You can twist arms. I always sold the most Camp Fire Girl
cookies and Girl Scout cookies.
   ``That's the point of my being `Fence's' sole investor. It was
about doing it right and having that control. I think when you
produce you must be a benevolent dictator. You must have the power
to make a decision, to say `no' or `yes.'''
   Before New York, Hays staged ``Fences'' at one of her theaters
in San Francisco and the reviews were mixed. Changes needed to be
made, particularly in clarifying the play's final scene, and Hays
saw that they were.
   ``It was a tryout and we went through the process of trying
different things,'' she recalls. ``Ultimately, it worked, but it
could have gone the other way.''
   Now the future of ``Fences'' seems secure. The play, now
starring Billy Dee Williams, has started its second year at
Broadway's 46th Street Theater. Its fortunes were boosted last
April after the drama won the Pulitzer Prize, last June when it won
four Tony awards and then later in the year when Paramount Pictures
paid some $500,000 for the film rights as a possible vehicle for
the super hot Eddie Murphy.
   ``I never did the play strictly as a commercial venture,'' Hays
says. ``I'm a Broadway baby. I believe in Broadway as being the
pinnacle of American theater.
   ``The first day of rehearsals for `Fences' I said to everyone,
`We do not know what's going to happen to this play, but we know
that we will all do our very, very best,''' she recalls. ```And I
want all of you to know that as a producer, you have my word that
this show isn't going to open and close. No matter what. We're
going to try and keep it running.'''
   So far, Hays hasn't had any trouble keeping her promise.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV for Sunday, March 27</NOTE>
</DOC>
