<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>At the Movies: ``Au Revoir Les Enfants,'' ``The Family''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Hollywood's pursuit of the here-and-now has created a glossy,
mostly superficial quality to the product coming out of the major
studios. Nowadays it's European filmmakers who indulge in
remembrance of things past.
   Two commendable examples are candidates for this year's Academy
Award as best foreign language film: ``Au Revoir Les Enfants'' from
France and ``The Family'' from Italy.
   Louis Malle, after working for a decade in the United States,
returned to his homeland for the most personal film in his
distinguished career, ``Au Revoir Les Enfants'' (``Goodbye,
Children''). He wrote and directed the film from his own bitter
memories as a schoolboy in occupied France during World War II.
   The story begins with a tearful 12-year-old, Julien Quentin,
leaving his mother in Paris to attend a Catholic boys school in
Fontainebleau. There he encounters the taunts of the older boys,
the privations of wartime and the strict discipline of the priests.
Julien forms a grudging friendship with a bright, aloof fellow
student, Jean Bonnet, whose background is a mystery.
   Jean, it turns out, is a Jew whose identity is hidden by the
sympathetic priests. But Jean is betrayed by someone inside the
school, and both he, two other boys and the head priest are taken
off to concentration camps.
   A brief synopsis cannot convey the rich texture Malle
contributes to the melancholy tale, nor the deep humanity. He is
fortunate in his choice of two gifted young performers: Gaspard
Manesse (Julien) and Raphael Fejto (Jean).
   In ``The Family,'' Ettore Scola traces the 80-year history of a
Roman family through the recollections of the central figure,
Carlo. The entire film takes place within the family's apartment,
with views of the hallway signifying the change of eras.
   The turbulent events from 1906 to 1986 provide the backdrop for
the family history. The central theme is Carlo's divided affection
between the sister he marries and the sister he really loves.
   Scola is the master of such wide-sweeping stories, and his
depiction of the temperament and humor of the Italians is
delightful. He chose three actors to depict Carlo at different
ages: young Emmanuele Lamaro, the rising star Andrea Occhipinto as
Carlo from 20 to 40, and Vittorio Gassman thereafter. All three are
superb.
   ``Au Revoir Les Enfants,'' an Orion Classics release, is rated
PG and runs 103 minutes. In French with English subtitles.
   ``The Family'' is a Vestron Pictures release, rated PG, running
time: 127 minutes. In Italian with English subtitles.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
