<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--Beuys Adv25-27   03-14 0705</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Beuys, Adv 25-27,0728</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv25-27</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, March 25-27 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Artists: Animal Fat and Felt Do Sculpture Make</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENNETH JAUTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joseph Beuys, West Germany's answer to the late
pop artist Andy Warhol, once said the Berlin Wall should be raised
10 centimeters for aesthetic reasons. The comment did little to
endear him to his countrymen.
   For most of his career, Beuys was better known in the United
States than at home. But now, two years after his death, Germans
have suddenly become fans of the avant-garde artist.
   Prices for his works are skyrocketing. Critics are singing his
praises. And record numbers of visitors are flocking to see the
first-ever major exhibition of his sketches and sculptures in West
Germany at one of the nation's leading museums.
   In East Berlin, a smaller exhibit of Beuys' early drawings also
is attracting crowds to the communist capital.
   The overhaul of Beuys' reputation has been speedy. Less than a
year ago, cleaners at the Duesseldorf Art Academy accidentally
threw out a Beuys sculpture made of wood, butter and animal fat.
The cleaners thought the creation was, literally, garbage.
   ``I often wonder what Beuys himself would think of all this,''
said a bemused Heiner Bastian, who served as the artist's assistant
for 12 years. ``He was used to criticizing society, but not to
being toasted by it.''
   Beuys specialized in sculptures made out of everyday items or
cast-off objects: empty boxes and tin cans, scraps of wood, stones,
shoes, blackboards or pieces of furniture. Felt and fat were his
favorite materials.
   In one creation, a single egg sits atop a wooden bench. In
another, a pair of battered boots dangles on a string above two
empty crates.
   A 1977 sculpture entitled ``In Memory of My Youth in the
Mountains'' consists of three large, white boulders inscribed with
the same words of the title.
   ``Beuys believed art had to be puzzling to be good, and there is
no denying that he is puzzling,'' said Bastian, who organized the
120-piece exhibition in West Berlin's Martin-Gropius-Bau museum.
   The 10-week show, which opened Feb. 20, drew an unexpected 9,000
visitors in its first five days, an unofficial record for an
exhibit in West Germany.
   With his jaunty and battered felt hat, vest and rumpled
trenchcoat, Beuys never looked like he fit in among the prosperous
and serious West Germans.
   His sense of humor was also atypically German. He was fired from
his job as administrator at the Duesseldorf Art Academy in 1972,
after announcing he would hire only applicants who had failed a
formal art program.
   He was dismissed by an angry Johannes Rau, then the economics
minister for the state of North Rhine-Westphalia, Beuys' birthplace
and lifelong home.
   But Rau and other politicians have since changed their tune.
   Now the North Rhine-Westphalian governor, Rau traveled to East
Berlin last month to open the city's first Beuys exhibition and
lavish praise on his former employee.
   Meanwhile, Volker Hassemer, West Berlin's culture chief, claimed
Beuys for Berliners.
   ``It is only fitting that the best-known contemporary German
artist be shown first in Berlin,'' Hassemer told reporters at the
Bueys exhibit's gala opening.
   Bastian is at a loss to explain the boost in Bueys' popularity,
and says it caught him by surprise.
   ``Throughout the history of art, there have been artists who
have become popular only after their deaths,'' he said. ``That has
been particularly true for modern art. No one can say why this is
so.''
   In a recent issue of Der Spiegel, West Germany's largest news
weekly, the entire letters column was devoted to Beuys. Opinion was
running decidedly against the artist.
   ``You recently ran pictures of Beuys works,'' wrote Immo
Kayser-Eichberg, a lawyer from the town of Meerbusch. ``You do not
seriously consider these things works of art, do you?''
   Visitors to the West Berlin Beuys exhibition were more tactful.
   ``No I do not understand it,'' said Ulrike Nagel, gazing at a
Beuys object that appeared to be little more than several empty
blackboards scattered on the floor. ``But that does not mean I do
not automatically dislike it.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, March 25-27</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
