<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-88 2021EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews Adv00   03-14 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, Adv 00,0458</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``One Mind'' (Global Pacific Records) _ Joaquin Lievano
   
   Joaquin Lievano gives special thanks to Zen Master Rama on the
back of ``One Mind,'' his new record. If you buy this record, you
may wish to enlist Mr. Rama's assistance in learning the patience
you'll need to get through it.
   ``One Mind'' is simple-minded. It starts at the beginning and
never wanders far beyond, winding back and forth upon itself with
no apparent direction.
   Lievano plays a variety of instruments, including guitars,
synthesizers and drums. He is assisted by Steve Smith on drums,
Steve Kindler on violin and Issac Epps on hand percussion. The
musicianship is proficient and the production is excellent. The
players turn in a nice riff here or a soft phrase there and, if you
like this sort of technical mastery of the soul, the record
delivers. For this reviewer, though, the overall effect was less
than zero.
   This record has its roots in the 1970s. It is derivative of
Chick Corea's ``Return to Forever'' and Kindler's playing sounds
suspiciously like that of Jean Luc Ponty, who rocketed out of
France in the '70s on a bow and an electric violin and has been
laying down the same tracks ever since.
   With apologies to Mr. Rama, an ancient Greek philospher once
said, ``You can't step in the same river twice.'' But Joaquin
Lievano is sure trying.
   _ By James Reindl, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``If My Heart Had Windows'' (MCA) _ Patty Loveless
   
   Patty Loveless' new album consists of 10 songs, and the writing
credit is different on each. But Loveless' singing and the
production of Emory Gordy Jr. and Tony Brown make the album into a
cohesive set that's as country as grits.
   ``If My Heart Had Windows'' includes a honky-tonk waltz (the
title cut, by Dallas Frazier); country swing (Hank Williams' ``I
Can't Get You Off of My Mind''); and plenty of ballads. Loveless'
full-throated alto really hits its stride on Side 2, climaxing on
John and Johanna Hall's ``Fly Away,'' which lives up to its name
with a soaring chorus reminiscent of the Halls' defunct pop group,
Orleans.
   The arrangements, built around the solid rhythm section of
Leland Sklar and Eddie Bayers, include such nice touches as a steel
and fiddle playing in unison on the break of ``I Can't Get You Off
of My Mind.'' The material occasionally sags, but most of the album
contains strong and honest performances.
   By Steven Wine, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
