<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Fashion:MiniSurvey     03-14 0137</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Fashion: Mini Survey,0139</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>FASHION: Mini Survey</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The mini is not for the many, according to a survey published in
a newsletter for marketers.
   The especially short, thigh-high miniskirt is appropriate only
for ``the young, the skinny and the bold when they're at play,''
according to the Langer Report.
   Its findings were based on a study of women 15 to 64 years old,
conducted in Los Angeles, New York, Dallas and Kansas City during
November and December 1987.
   ``It is for a small minority of women, a minority of the time,''
said Judith Langer, publisher and co-editor of the report, which
says the ``thigh-high micro-mini is seen by women as tacky _ worn
to attract male attention, but not respect.''
   Langer Associates Inc. is a New York-based market research firm.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
