<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wholesale prices dipped 0.2 percent in
Feburary as both energy and food costs declined, including a
dramatic 70 percent tumble in the price of lettuce, the government
said.
   The decline reported Friday in the Labor Department's Producer
Price Index partially erased a 0.4 percent increase in January.
Analysts said it provided further evidence that inflation remains
tame.
   The producer index does not show two categories in which price
increases have been the most pronounced _ services and imported
goods.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said retail sales edged up 0.6
percent in February, bolstered by strong demand for autos, but
economists worried that sales in January were much weaker than
previously believed.
   Instead of a 0.5 percent rise in sales, the Commerce Department
said Friday sales actually fell 0.2 percent during January, showing
the consumer sector is weaker than previously believed.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Koppers Co. sued Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
and British investor Brian Beazer, accusing them of violating
securities laws in trying to acquire the Pittsburgh-based chemicals
and construction company.
   Koppers said Friday it was attempting to break up ``an ongoing
illegal scheme ... to acquire control of Koppers in blatant
violation of the disclosure requirements'' of securities laws.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New York Stock Exchange's 5-week-old
``collar'' on computerized trading appears to be an effective
therapy for easing volatility in the post-crash market and luring
back frightened investors, analysts say.
   But the restriction also makes the market less attractive to
investors who thrive on risk, which could theoretically drive them
overseas.
   Some market experts argue that the restriction would do little
to squelch another panic.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The General Services Administration has
extended by one month the deadline for bids on a new,
multibillion-dollar government telephone system to give US Sprint
Communications Co. more time to draft its proposal.
   The GSA said it was reluctantly extending the deadline to April
29, but said it was doing so to ensure the fullest possible
competition for the contract, one of the biggest ever let by the
government.

</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission said
PaineWebber Inc. voluntarily has agreed to repay customers an
amount the SEC claims were overcharges in the sale of Treasury bond
coupons.
   The SEC did not disclose on Friday the amount of the repayment
or of the alleged overcharge by the brokerage house.
   The SEC alleged the overcharges occurred between Jan. 1, 1984
and July 31, 1985.
</TEXT>
