<DOCNO> AP880314-0294 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-88 0755EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     03-14 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Down As Pound Surges On; Gold Firmer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against all major currencies in
early European trading today as the British pound continued a
weeklong surge with the Conservative government split on whether to
rein in sterling.
   Gold prices rose.
   Some traders said the pound was helping to depress the dollar.
   The pound jumped more than half a cent to $1.8590, compared with
$1.8535 late Friday. The pound has risen 8 cents from a week ago.
   Sterling has been rising on expectations the government will
announce substantial tax cuts in its annual spring budget Tuesday,
and was boosted further by the government split.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher last week rejected state
intervention to depress the pound, either by selling sterling or
lowering interest rates _ thus overruling Chancellor of the
Exchequer Nigel Lawson.
   A strong pound hurts British exports. But Mrs. Thatcher believes
lowering interest rates to make the pound less attractive to
foreign investors will encourage borrowing and fuel inflation.
   After years of low-deficit budgets, Britain is heading for a
balanced budget, or even a surplus of revenue over expenditure, for
the first time in nearly 20 years.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar closed at 127.23 yen, down 0.57 yen from Friday.
Later, in London the dollar slipped further to 126.55 yen.
   Tokyo dealers said the dollar was depressed partly by
pessimistic expectations for U.S. January trade figures to be
released Thursday.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Friday's
rates, included: 1.6575 West German marks, down from 1.6615; 1.3665
Swiss francs, down from 1.3720; 5.6325 French francs, down from
5.6515; 1.8624 Dutch guilders, down from 1.8680; 1.228.40 Italian
lire, down from 1.232.55; and 1.2552 Canadian dollars, down from
1.2553.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $441.80 a troy ounce,
compared with late Friday's $440.50. At mid-morning today, the
city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of
$441.90.
   In Zurich, the noon bid price was $441.85 dollars, up from $441
late Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold closed at a $444.81 bid, up $1.27
from Saturday's closing price.
   Silver was quoted in London on Monday at a bid price of $6.23 a
troy ounce, down from $6.36 late Friday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
