<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-88 1024EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Herbicide 1stLd-Writethru   03-14 0711</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Herbicide, 1st Ld-Writethru,0732</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs penultimate graf to delete incorrect close-quote marks.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency says it
will not launch a special study of a widely used herbicide
suspected of causing cancer among farmers because other research
has not confirmed the suspicion.
   A major commercial user, however, said it won't put the chemical
back in its lineup until the cancer picture is clarified, and a
scientist with an environmental group called the EPA's decision
``outrageous.''
   The herbicide is 2,4-D, short for dichlorophenoxyacetic acid. A
1986 study said it was the fourth most widely used pesticide in the
nation, with more than 39 million pounds of active ingredient sold
the previous year.
   The great bulk of that is believed to be used for broadleaf weed
control in wheat fields, though 2,4-D also is widely used on
highway rights of way, on lawns and in forests.
   Following several scientific reports associating certain cancers
with farming or exposure to various _ and sometimes unspecified _
herbicides, the National Cancer Institute in 1986 found that
farmers in Kansas who used 2,4-D more than 20 times a year, mixing
their own formulations, had an eight times greater chance than
normal of getting a specific cancer called non-Hodgkin's lymphoma,
a cancer of the lymph system.
   Home and garden users did not face concentrations large enough
to cause concern, the study said.
   The herbicide aroused suspicion because it can be contaminated
with small amounts of chemicals related to the dioxins, though
there are no U.S. reports, and only one abroad, of contamination
with the most toxic form of dioxin.
   The contaminants of 2,4-D generally have only about 1 percent of
the cancer-causing power of the most toxic dioxin.
   In all the controversy over dioxin, a cancer called soft-tissue
sarcoma has been at the center of the issue _ and this cancer
sometimes was found in the early 2,4-D reports.
   EPA frequently puts suspicious pesticides into what it calls
``special review,'' a way of bringing the chemical to the head of
the line. The agency may call for additional studies by the
manufacturer and the reviews may end up with new use restrictions
or an outright ban.
   In this case, EPA has decided not to begin such a review.
Spokesman Al Heier confirmed trade press reports of the decision,
describing the decision as a ``tough call.''
   Animal studies, he said, ``do not suggest that it's a
carcinogen,'' and ``I think there are quite a few (human)
epidemiology studies'' that also fail to confirm the cancer-causing
ability of 2,4-D.
   It is extremely rare for a chemical to cause cancer in humans
but not in laboratory animals. The best example is arsenic.
   Officials to whom Heier referred more detailed questions did not
immediately return telephone calls. The agency plans a news
conference on Thursday to discuss its decision.
   One study of farm and forest workers in New Zealand found
elevated incidence of non-Hodgkins lymphoma and another cancer
called multiple myeloma, but did not examine exposure to
pesticides. A followup study, however, found no excess risk of
cancer as a result of exposure to chemicals of the 2,4-D class.
   Chemlawn Services Inc. stopped using 2,4-D after the National
Cancer Institute results were announced.
   The company acted ``out of concern for our employees,'' of whom
2,500 to 3,000 probably were using 2,4-D on 80 days a year, said
spokesman Steve Hardymon in Columbus, Ohio.
   It has arranged a study of employees by the institute, and will
not decide whether to resume use of 2,4-D until results are
reported, probably late next year, though EPA's decision ``probably
is right,'' said Hardymon.
   ``I think it's outrageous,'' Diane Baxter, staff scientist of
the National Coalition Against the Misuse of Pesticides, said of
the EPA's decision.
   She was particularly critical of the weight given to animal
studies that showed no effect. ``We only do animal studies when we
don't have human studies,'' but in this case a good study of humans
_ the Kansas farmers _ was outweighed by animal studies, she said.
   She said ``2,4,5-T was banned mostly because of birth defects
(among humans) in the Pacific Northwest ... and that is not
anywhere near as hard to refute as the study NCI did.''
</TEXT>
