<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Federated 3rdLd-Writethru   03-14 0658</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Federated, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0683</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 1-3 with four grafs to focus on sweetened offer.
SUBS 12th graf to conform and 19th graf to delete redundant
reference to Cincinnati.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Campeau Extends Tender Offer For Federated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federated Department Stores Inc. said today that
R.H. Macy & Co. has sweetened its friendly takeover bid, while
Campeau Corp. announced an extension until midnight Friday of its
competing $6.18 billion tender offer.
   Cincinnati-based Federated said its board of directors was
meeting here today to consider a proposal from Macy ``to revise and
improve the terms upon which Macy's would acquire Federated.''
   Federated spokesman Jim Sluzewski said he could not provide
details of the revision. Macy currently has a definitive $6.1
billion agreement to acquire Federated.
   Meanwhile, Campeau said it extended its hostile offer to buy
70.5 million of Federated's stock at $75 a share from Tuesday until
Friday to take pressure off a federal judge who was scheduled to
hear arguments today on the takeover battle.
   The extension gives Federated and Macy more time to work on a
sweetened deal.
   Shortly after Campeau's move was announced, Federated urged its
shareholders to hold onto their stock.
   On Sunday, Federated had ``reluctantly'' advised stockholders to
tender their shares under Campeau's two-tier buyout offer although
it was against merging with the Toronto developer.
   The unusual recommendation had been intended to ensure that
Federated shareholders get the higher price offered under the first
stage of Campeau's offer.
   Campeau said it would pay $75 a share in cash for 80 percent of
Federated's stock while the remaining 20 percent would be acquired
later for $44 cash per share in a subsequent merger, giving the
deal an aggregate value of $68 per share.
   In early trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Federated stock
rose $1.37{ to $67.37{.
   Federated's board said Sunday shareholders should tender their
stock to Campeau ``to insure that they are not relegated to the $44
back end'' in the event the Campeau bid were successful and their
shares were not tendered by the deadline.
   Federated noted that shareholders could withdraw shares tendered
to Campeau if the Campeau deadline were extended.
   Macy has sought a federal court injunction to extend Campeau's
Tuesday expiration. Macy contended Campeau's current offer, which
was amended from an earlier $68 per share bid for all Federated
shares, essentially is a new offer and under federal law must
remain open past its scheduled expiration.
   A hearing was set for today on the dispute, and Campeau also
planned to ask the court to strike down Federated's ``poison
pill,'' or shareholder-rights plan, which makes an unfriendly
takeover prohibitively expensive.
   Macy has offered $74.50 per share in cash for 80 percent of
Federated's stock in an bid that expires April 4. Macy plans to
swap shares in a new company, Macy's-Federated Inc., for the
remaining 20 percent of Federated shares.
   Federated said its board met Friday and unanimously reaffirmed
that the definitive merger agreement with Macy was superior to the
Campeau bid.
   Federated also said Sunday its directors and corporate
management have insisted their stock options and restricted shares
be converted to cash on the same basis as other shareholders in the
Macy-Federated merger agreement.
   A filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission revealed
last week that some 500 Federated executives would receive all cash
for their stock in the proposed Macy acquisition, while other
shareholders would get cash for only 80 percent of their shares.
   ``Senior management has taken this steop to avoid any possible
implication that they would be treated better than the company's
stockholders generally,'' Federated said in a news release.
   Federated owns department store chains including Bloomingdale's,
Burdine's, Filene's, Foley's, Rich's and Bullock's.
   Macy has nearly 100 department and specialty stores, while
Campeau owns Allied Stores Corp.
   Campeau said today it expects to obtain all the necessary
financing to complete a buyout by the March 18 expiration date.
</TEXT>
