<1ST_LINE>r f BC-RigCount     03-14 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Rig Count,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rig Count Drops By 32 To Total 946</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of oil and gas rigs working in the
United States decreased by 32 this week to total 946, Baker Hughes
Inc. announced.
   The total reflects the number of rigs actively exploring for oil
as of last Friday, not the number rigs producing oil. The previous
week, the count had decreased by five to 978.
   ``In a normal year, the low comes in late March or early April,
and then begins a gradual increase from that point,'' said Ike
Kerridge, a Baker Hughes economist who compiles the count. ``It is
not unusual for it to be coming down in March.''
   Kerridge said companies usually accelerate their exploration
spending as the year progresses. A year ago, the rig count stood at
761, Baker Hughes said.
   Houston-based Baker Hughes, an oil toolmaker, tallies the number
of working rigs and the count is the widely-watched industry index
of drilling activity.
   Hughes Tool Co., which merged this year with Baker International
Corp. of Orange, Calif., has kept track of the number of working
rigs since 1940.
   The rig count reached a peak of 4,500 active rigs in December
1981 _ the height of the oil boom. But as oil prices plunged to
less than $10 per 42-gallon barrel in the summer of 1986, the count
fell to 663, the lowest since Hughes began compiling figures.
   Among the major oil producing states, Oklahoma lost 14 rigs,
Ohio lost seven, New Mexico lost five, Colorado and Pennsylvania
each lost three, and Michigan and Wyoming lost one apiece.
   Kansas gained three rigs, Louisiana gained two and Texas gained
one. The states of California and North Dakota showed no change.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
