<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Unemployment     03-14 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Unemployment,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Billion New Jobs by 2030 Would Provide Full Employment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Close to two billion new jobs would have to be
created by 2030 if the goal of full employment were to be attained
worldwide, according to a survey published Monday by the
International Labor Office.
   Citing data from the ILO's new statistical yearbook, the survey
suggested that this goal was out of reach at current levels of
creating new employment.
   It said that globally an average 47 million new jobs are needed
each year over the next four decades to cope with the population
growth and absorb the ``armies of unemployed and underemployed.''
   The yearbook, covering data from almost 100 nations, said women
and young people continue to fare worst, but that the women's share
of the workforce increased in many parts of the world.
   However, in some developed countries, including Belgium, Italy,
and Greece, jobless rates of women were more than double than those
of men.
   The picture looked grimmest for young people. In Spain, more
than half of all teenagers and almost half of those between 20 and
25 were unmployed in 1986, and in France the rates were 27.5 and 16
percent. No statistics were available for African countries where
the problem is believed to be most serious in the Third World.
   The statistics list a decline of unemployment in 31 countries
between 1985 and 1986. Improvement was most marked in Latin
American and Caribbean countries although they still have some of
the highest unemployment rates in the world.
   Rates dropped from 12.1 percent to 8.7 percent in Chile; from
21.8 percent to 18.9 percent in Puerto Rico; from 11.8 percent to
8.2 percent in Peru; and from 14 percent to 10.3 percent in
Venezuela.
   The trend was also downward in the United States, from 7.1 to
6.9 percent. The hardest hit European country was Spain, but the
rate also declined slightly from 21.9 percent to 21.5 percent. By
contrast, Ireland's rate was up from 17.8 percent to 18.2 percent.
   Switzerland, with a rate of 0.8 percent, ranked at the bottom of
the survey. China and Norway, at 2 percent, and Japan, at 2.8
percent, also reported almost full employment.
</TEXT>
