<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Ply-Gem-WolverineMerger     03-14 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Ply-Gem-Wolverine Merger,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Makers of Home Improvement Products Reach Merger Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ply-Gem Industries Inc. and Wolverine
Technologies Monday announced a merger agreement involving a
$60.8-million tender offer by Ply-Gem, a New York maker of home
improvement products.
   Ply-Gem secured financing from Manufacturers Hanover for the
$18.50-a-share offer for Wolverine's 3,285,000 shares of common
stock, said Diane Cady, a Ply-Gem spokeswoman reached in New York.
   Wolverine is a major manufacturer of vinyl siding and windows.
   Gregory C. Smith will continue as chairman and chief executive
officer and James K. Cassedy as president of Dearborn-based
Wolverine, which will be a wholly owned Ply-Gem subsidiary, the
companies said in a joint announcement.
   ``The merger with Wolverine in combination with Ply-Gem's 1986
acquisitions of Veriform Inc. and Great Lakes Window Inc. will make
Ply-Gem the leading company in the vinyl siding and vinyl window
market today,'' said Jeffrey Silverman, Ply-Gem chairman and
president.
   Ply-Gem, a maker and distributor of home improvement specialty
products such as vinyl siding and windows, decorator paneling and
fire-retardant lumber, reported 1987 revenues of $313 million.
Wolverine had revenues of $111 million for 1987.
   By midday, following the morning announcement, Ply-Gem stock was
at $13 a share, up 12{ cents on the American Stock Exchange, and
Wolverine stock was at $18.12, up 50 cents on the New York Stock
Exchange.
</TEXT>
