<1ST_LINE>r f BC-MooreMcCormack     03-14 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Moore McCormack,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moore McCormack Rejects Southdown Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moore McCormack Resources Inc. said
Monday its board rejected as inadequate a sweetened $450 million
bid from Southdown Inc. and authorized the sale of a Moore
McCormack subsidiary as a move to enchance shareholder value.
   Last week Southdown, a Houston-based cement and energy company,
increased its tender offer for all of Moore McCormack's outstanding
common stock to $35 per share from its previous offer of $31 per
share. The initial offer valued the company at about $391 million.
   Moore McCormack called the latest bid ``inadequate and not in
the best interests'' of the company and its shareholders.
   ``The board of directors of Moore McCormack continues to believe
that remaining independent would be a superior alternative over the
long-range term,'' the company said in a statement.
   Moore McCormack's board authorized the sale of Moore McCormack
Energy Inc., the company's oil and gas subsidiary.
   The company said it is ``continuing to explore and investigate
the variety of ... transactions intended to enhance securityholder
values, other than a significant acquisition by the company.''
   Southdown said its tender offer was conditional upon the valid
tender of a majority of Moore McCormack common stock, the
invalidation of Moore McCormack's ``poison pill'' anti-takeover
defense and the acquisition of sufficient financing.
   Southdown produces and sells cement and ready-mixed concrete and
is active in oil and gas production. Moore McCormack, of Stamford,
produces building materials and is involved in oil and gas
exploration and production, mainly in Texas and Louisiana.
</TEXT>
