<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     03-14 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0325</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices marked time in quiet trading today
as traders looked ahead to a potentially volatile week.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 1.49 to 2,036.47 by
2 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 4 to 3 in the overall tally
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 619 up, 841 down and
439 unchanged.
   Analysts said traders were reluctant to take big positions in
advance of the government's report Thursday on the nation's trade
balance for January.
   The trade deficit narrowed in the last two months of 1987, but
some analysts expect the January data to show a modest increase in
the gap between exports and imports.
   This week's trade report will come just ahead of a quarterly
``triple witching hour'' involving a group of expiring options and
futures on stock indexes.
   The past couple of witching hours have been relatively
uneventful with the adoption of new procedures designed to spread
out the impact of last-minute maneuvering by computer program
traders.
   Nevertheless, analysts say uncertainty about how it will go this
time has lent an added element of uncertainty to a marketplace
still haunted by memories of the crash last fall.
   Grolier Inc. led the active list, up 8[ at 24. Hachette S.A. of
France made a $21-a-share offer to acquire the company.
   J.P. Stevens climbed 5\ to 61. The company agreed to be acquired
for $61.50 a share by an investor group.
   Homestake Mining fell 1[ to 15[. Mesa L.P. withdrew a
$20-a-share takeover bid that Homestake had opposed.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks lost
.01 to 149.44. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .61 at 296.70.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 87.53 million shares with two
hours to go.
</TEXT>
