<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Mesa-Homestake Bjt   03-14 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mesa-Homestake, Bjt,0504</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mesa Withdraws Cash Offer for Homestake</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMARILLO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mesa Limited Partnership's second foray
into the gold industry fell short Monday when the group, controlled
by oilman T. Boone Pickens, withdrew its $1.88 billion cash offer
for Homestake Mining Co.
   Mesa released a statement saying it retracted its offer to
obtain the entire equity interest in Homestake, a leading gold
producer, with a negotiated transaction for a price of $20 per
share in cash.
   Mesa spokesman David H. Batchelder said the San Francisco-based
Homestake had rejected Mesa's bid. But he offered no explanation
for Mesa's move.
   The partnership made a cash offer on Feb. 29 for the 93 million
outstanding common shares of Homestake. Mesa already controlled
about 3.8 percent of Homestake's stock.
   The Mesa statement said its offer was rejected March 7 by the
board of directors of Homestake as ``inadequate and not in the best
interests of Homestake and its shareholders.''
   Homestake had 1987 earnings of $146.4 million, two-thirds coming
from Homestake's sale of its interests in an Australian mining
operation.
   The company's stock traded between $18 and $24 a share before
the Oct. 19 stock market plunge. When Pickens, Mesa general
partner, announced his offer, Homestake stock shot up $3.50 to
about $18.50 per share. Late in Monday's session, it stood at
$15.12{ per share, down $1.12{ on the New York Stock Excange.
   ``The Street didn't seem to be that excited about his going
after Homestake,'' said Bob Hill, vice president for the A.G.
Edwards investment firm in Amarillo.
   Wall Street analysts said they did not perceive Pickens' pursuit
of Homestake as a good buy.
   ``Obviously, he did or he wouldn't have gone after them,'' Hill
said of Pickens.
   Homestake Vice President Richard W. Stumbo took the bid
seriously.
   ``You always take him seriously,'' Stumbo said, adding he did
not know if Mesa's withdrawal was the end of its takeover efforts.
   Homestake holds interests in oil and natural gas and mines
uranium, silver and gold, as does Newmont Mining Corp., another
major gold producer targeted in an earlier, unsuccessful hostile
takeover bid by Pickens.
   New York-based Newmont was approached last year by Ivanhoe
Partners, a group led by Pickens, which made a $2 billion hostile
bid for control of the company.
   A Delaware court blocked the move in October when it upheld a
``market sweep'' in which Newmont's biggest shareholder, Britain's
Consolidated Gold Fields PLC, grabbed enough shares in a two-day
buying spree to raise its holdings to nearly 50 percent of Newmont
and thwart the hostile bid.
   Pickens' reputation as a corporate raider was made with
high-profile bids for several major oil companies in the early
1980s, including Gulf Corp., Phillips Petroleum Co. and Unocal Corp.
   Mesa launched hostile takeover attempts, then pocketed millions
of dollars in profits when some of the target companies either were
bought out by a higher bidder or repurchased their own stock.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880314-0314 </DOCNO>
