<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   03-14 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grains, Soybeans Close Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices soared on the Chicago
Board of Trade Monday as fears about increased soybean acreage
eased. Grain futures also closed higher.
   Prices for delivery of new-crop soybeans _ those to be harvested
this fall as opposed to those harvested last fall _ posted the
greatest gains in reaction to talk about estimates issued Monday
morning by Sparks Commodities, a private analytical firm based in
Memphis, Tenn.
   Sparks reportedly pegged 1988 U.S. soybean plantings at 57.5
million acres, just slightly above last year's 57.4 million. The
report followed an estimate of 60 million acres made last week by
Refco Inc., a large commodities trading firm.
   Sparks would not comment on the figures, which it supplies only
to its subscribers.
   ``That's not the gospel, but it's the closest thing we've got
for the time being,'' Victor Lespinasse, a trader for Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc., said of the reported Sparks estimate.
   Sparks also reportedly predicted 1988 corn plantings at 66.8
million acres compared to last year's 65.7 million. The estimate
was seen as slightly bullish for corn prices.
   The Agriculture Department will release its first crop acreage
estimates on March 31.
   At the close, wheat was 1 cent to 4 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in March at $2.93{ a bushel; corn was { cent
to 2{ cents higher with March at $1.97{ a bushel; oats were } cent
to 2 cents higher with March at $1.89{ a bushel; soybeans were 5
cents to 12 cents higher with March at $6.12\ a bushel.
</TEXT>
