<1ST_LINE>r f BC-UnitedArtists     03-14 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-United Artists,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>United Artists Sets Up New Movie Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Artists Communications Inc. announced
that is has formed Corsair Pictures, a new motion picture company
based in New York.
   Denver-based United Artists, one of the nation's biggest movie
operators with about 2,050 motion picture screens, said Monday that
Corsair will develop a slate of quality films made with low and
moderate budgets of $3 million to $10 million each.
   The new company, to be privately financed by United Artists,
will be headed by Frank Perry, a film producer and director. Perry,
who won an Academy Award nomination for best director for ``David
and Lisa,'' will be president and chief executive officer of
Corsair.
   Perry said he envisions Corsair producing three or four feature
films in its first year, although that could vary depending on the
number of quality projects and filmmakers available. ``Corsair will
be governed by quality and economic logic, not quantity,'' he said.
   Last week, United Artists and United Cable Television Corp.
agreed to combine their operations into a $3.8 billion concern that
would rank as one of the nation's biggest cable TV companies.
   United Artists has about 800,000 cable subscribers, while United
Cable has around 1.1 million.
   United Artists also announced Monday that its Taurus
Entertainment Co., a film marketing and distribution group, will
report to Perry in the future. Perry will also oversee the
company's recently acquired interest in ``Think Entertainment,'' a
movie production company founded and run by actress-producer
Shelley Duvall.
   Perry's producing and directing credits include ``Last Summer,''
``Diary of a Mad Housewife,'' ``Play It As It Lays,'' ``Rancho
Deluxe,'' ``Mommie Dearest,'' ``Compromising Positions'' and
``Hello Again.''
</TEXT>
