<DOCNO> AP880314-0318 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-88 1606EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Texaco-Husky     03-14 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Texaco-Husky,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Husky Wants Control Of Texaco's Canadian Operation, Report Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Husky Oil Ltd. of Canada is considering offering
Texaco Inc. a cash infusion of at least $1 billion to help persuade
Texaco to sell Husky a majority interest in Texaco Canada Ltd.,
according to a published report.
   A Texaco spokeswoman declined comment on the report carried in
Monday's editions of the Wall Street Journal. Officials at Husky,
based in Calgary, Alberta, did not return phone calls.
   The Journal said Robert Blair, co-chairman of Husky, said in an
interview he remains very interested in acquiring the Texaco unit
and will step up his efforts in a trip to New York this week.
   Blair added that Husky would be willing to pay $2.4 billion to
$2.7 billion for Texaco's 78 percent interest in the Toronto-based
unit of Texaco, the Journal said.
   The estimated purchase price does not include the possible $1
billion cash infusion from Husky, the Journal said. It was not
immediately clear what form a cash infusion might take.
   Blair told the Journal he hopes to present Texaco a ``mutually
attractive plan'' under which the two Canadian companies would
merge under Husky's control. He added that Texaco would have to
sell enough of its interest to give Husky a stake of at least 51
percent.
   Blair said his recent phone messages have not been answered by
James Kinnear, Texaco's chief executive.
   Texaco is planning to sell about $3 billion in assets as part of
its plan to emerge from Chapter 11 protection by late next month.
   Texaco filed for protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of
federal bankruptcy law last April to forestall enforcement of a
$10.3 billion damages judgment for interfering with Pennzoil Co.'s
acquisition of an interest in Getty Oil Co. in 1984. Texaco settled
the dispute in December by agreeing to pay Pennzoil $3 billion.
</TEXT>
