<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-88 1711EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Copper-7IUD 1stLd-Writethru   03-14 0510</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Copper-7 IUD, 1st Ld-Writethru,0522</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Documents: Company May Have Misled Doctors About IUD</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS new 2nd graf on stock market reaction.</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eds: a version on general news wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Internal documents indicate that G.D.
Searle & Co. may have misled doctors and a federal regulatory
agency about safety characteristics of its Copper-7 contraceptive,
according to an attorney representing a woman who claims the device
made her sterile.
   Wall Street reacted Monday by knocking the stock of Monsanto
Co., Searle's parent, down $3.12{ a share to $83.37{.
   According to the documents, Searle apparently hid complaints
about the Copper-7 from the U.S. Food and Drug Administration, the
attorney said.
   An FDA task force recommended that a federal grand jury
investigate whether any laws were broken by Searle's allegedly
misleading reports on animal studies for a number of products,
including the Copper-7. No charges were filed.
   The Searle documents, produced for a trial set to start May 16
in St. Paul, became public last week on order of U.S. District
Judge Robert Renner. The judge rejected Searle's arguments that the
memorandums be kept confidential to protect trade secrets.
   Michael Ciresi, a Minneapolis attorney who represent Esther
Kociemba, a Melrose woman who claims to have been made infertile by
the Copper-7, said: ``These documents can be characterized as the
tip of the iceberg. Once all the documents are disclosed (to the
public), they will collectively establish without a doubt that the
Copper-7 causes (infection) and Searle knew about it, but did not
disclose it to doctors or to women.''
   Nationally, there have been 17 trials involving Searle's
Copper-7, 14 of them decided in the company's favor.
   Kociemba's case ``will be the first case tried against Searle
where the jury will be presented with evidence from Searle's files
showing what Searle knew about the hazards of the IUD, when they
knew about them and what they did about them _ which was to conceal
the information,'' Ciresi said.
   Paul Strain of Baltimore, an attorney for Searle, said, ``We are
confident when a jury hears all the evidence, reviews all the
documents and, most importantly, hears from the doctors that they
will conclude the Copper-7 is a good IUD that does not cause
infection.''
   He said that documents not yet released and defense testimony
will show that the company did not mislead anyone.
   A major issue in the suit will be whether the Copper-7 tail
string was a single strand of polypropylene incapable of
transporting infection-causing bacteria into the uterus, as Searle
contends, or if it was made up of many tiny strands that could act
as a tunnel for bacteria, as Ciresi contends.
   One of the Searle documents quotes a company official saying for
the first time that the Copper-7 string is a ``bundle of fused
micro-filaments.''
   The Copper-7 was a popular intrauterine device from 1974 to
1988, when Searle withdrew it from the market citing litigation
costs. Many American women continue to use Copper-7 IUDs and Searle
recently resumed manufacturing the device in order to fill foreign
orders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880314-0324 </DOCNO>
