<1ST_LINE>r f AM-AT&T-Supremacists     03-14 0157</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AT&T-Supremacists,0164</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AT&T Urging Rejection Of White Supremacist Resolution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Telephone & Telegraph Co. is urging
shareholders to reject a resolution from a white supremacist
organization calling on the company to phase out its affirmative
action program.
   The resolution is included in the proxy materials for the
company's annual meeting, to be held in Denver on April 20.
   The National Alliance of Arlington, Va., argues that affirmative
action programs ``may contribute towards discrimination against
white people'' and ``may contribute to a decline in the quality of
a company's work force.''
   AT&T responds that affirmative action plans are necessary to
qualify for government business, are a ``sound and fair business
practice'' and have improved employee morale and performance,
spokeswoman LuAnn Gardner said Monday.
   The National Alliance is described in the Encyclopedia of
Associations as an organization dedicated to creating racial and
cultural pride among whites and ``building a new order in American
life.''
</TEXT>
