<DOCNO> AP880314-0328 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-88 1919EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-FirstCity     03-14 0566</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-First City,0584</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First City Optimistic About Closing On Bank Deal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH RENDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investor A. Robert Abboud said Monday he is
confident debt holders of First City Bancorporation of Texas Inc.
will surrender their notes to the bank for less than face value.
   On March 4, more than 71 percent of the Houston-based bank
holding company's 37 million shareholders approved a $1.5 billion
federal bailout plan.
   The plan _ which would be the second largest government bank
bailout _ calls for $970 million in federal assistance, a $500
million infusion of capital raised privately by an investor group
headed by Abboud, and a spinoff of $1.79 billion in book value of
poorly performing assets.
   First City, the fourth-largest bank firm in Texas, grew quickly
during the Texas oil boom, but was hammered by energy and real
estate losses when oil prices plummeted. For 1987, the company
posted a $1.1 billion loss.
   Under a buyout plan that was made a condition of the bailout,
holders of First City's debt securities would be paid less than the
face value of their notes, said Alan Whitney, director of
communications for the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.
   The amounts offered to note holders ranged from 35 cents to 45
cents on the dollar, he said.
   But Abboud, who would head the bank under the plan, told federal
regulators in Washington this weekend that not enough of the note
holders have agreed to sell at those prices. The agreement provides
that 90 percent of the debt holders turn over their notes by a 4
p.m. CST Tuesday deadline.
   During a Monday afternoon news conference in Houston, Abboud
would not say how many debt holders had submitted their notes, but
expressed confidence the deal can be closed by month's end.
   ``There's a high degree of confidence and enthusiasm as
presently structured,'' said Abboud, who was wearing a ``Yes We
Can! First City'' button on his lapel.
   ``I would ask the other debt holders who have not yet tendered
to cooperate with us and submit their securities. We're prepared to
close if conditions are fully satisfied,'' he added.
   Abboud said debt holders are getting more than if the bank were
liquidated.
   ``The offer on the table is basically the offer until Tuesday
afternoon,'' he said. ``There is no intent on anybody's part to
make any material changes in the monetary terms of the offering.''
   Last week, First City bonds were trading well above the prices
being offered under the bailout plan. Analysts said this indicated
that some investors were gambling that federal regulators would
come up with a higher price for the First City debt.
   The investors are betting that the FDIC, in its eagerness to
wrap up the First City deal, will either sweeten the offer or
reduce the percentage of shares that need to be tendered.
   Still other analysts said last week that the FDIC could refuse
to raise the offer for fear of setting a precedent for future bank
bailouts.
   Other options available to the FDIC, the analysts said, include
cancelling the Abboud deal and reopening bidding for the bank, or a
move by the FDIC to itself take over First City, as it did with
Continental Illinois Bank and Trust of Chicago in 1984.
   First City has assets of $11 billion and operates 59 banks in
Texas and one in South Dakota.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880314-0329 </DOCNO>
