<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0013,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Stock Prices Close Higher Ahead Of Budget</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices closed slightly higher in thin
trading Monday in what traders said was cautious optimism ahead of
Tuesday's release of the British budget.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index closed up 7.9
points at 1,819.5. The index had been up by 9.0 points at
mid-afternoon after a Wall Street slightly higher than Friday's
close.
   Volume fell to 337.1 million shares from 688.2 million on Friday.
   Traders said many participants stayed on the sidelines ahead of
Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson's budget speech to
Parliament on Tuesday.
   Economists are forecasting personal tax cuts amounting to 3
billion to 4 billion pounds _ about $5.5 billion to $7.4 billion at
current exxchange rates _ and a fiscal 1989 budget that is balanced
or slightly in surplus.
   Also boosting shares were better-than-expected results from
Glaxo Holdings, the giant pharmaceuticals concern, traders said.
Glaxo announced its pre-tax profit rose 5.6 percent to 397 million
pounds in the six months ended Dec. 31, exceeding market
expectations.
   Glaxo finished up 27 pence at 10.82 pounds a share.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
