<1ST_LINE>u f AM-MediaGeneral     03-14 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Media General,0502</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Media General Again Spurns Sugarman Bid, Files Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newspaper and television station operator
Media General Inc. said Monday it sued unwanted suitor Burt
Sugarman, the Los Angeles-based investor and TV producer, accusing
him of making statements designed to create speculation in Media
General's stock.
   The suit filed in federal court in Richmond, Va., where Media
General is based, seeks an injunction barring Sugarman from such
actions and requiring Sugarman to sell the 10 percent of the
company's stock he has acquired.
   The suit also seeks unspecified monetary damages.
   At the same time, Media General said its board had ``carefully
considered'' Sugarman's $61.50 per share, or $1.58 billion, offer
for the 90 percent of the company he doesn't already own and
decided not to pursue it.
   Sugarman was out of the office and not available for comment, a
receptionist said.
   The suit accuses Sugarman of making ``inaccurate and
incomplete'' statements to the press and in Securities and Exchange
Commission filings `designed to create speculation concerning Media
General stock and to help him in a possible proxy contest.''
   The suit also claims Sugarman has, in effect, begun seeking
proxies through his statements in the press without filing required
SEC documents in advance.
   Media General's stock closed Monday at $47.25, down 37{ cents.
   The suit is the latest salvo in two-week-old tug of war between
Sugarman and the family of Media General's chairman, D. Tennant
Bryan, which controls a majority of the company's voting power.
   If Sugarman succeeds in putting his proposal before
shareholders, the company said, the Tennant family will vote
against it.
   The Tennant family owns 71 percent of the company's Class B
common stock. Although there are only 559,168 Class B shares, they
have the voting power to elect seven of the company's 10 directors.
   Media General has 28 million Class A shares, which have one vote
each and elect three directors.
   Sugarman, who owns 10 percent of the company's Class A stock and
none of the Class B, has argued that the disproportionate voting
rule doesn't apply if a holder of more than 10 percent of the
company's stock proposes a merger.
   Media General says its counsel disagrees.
   Media General, based in Richmond, owns a number of daily
newspapers, including the Richmond (Va.) Times-Dispatch and News
Leader, the Winston-Salem (N.C.) Journal and the Tampa (Fla.)
Tribune, plus 32 weeklies in Southern California and a 40 percent
interest in Garden State Newspapers Inc. that owns 18 dailies and
four weeklies in eight states.
   It also owns television stations, including WCBD-TV in
Charleston, S.C., WJKS-TV in Jacksonville, Fla., and WXFL-TV in
Tampa, Fla.
   Sugarman is making the takeover offer through two companies he
controls _ Barris Industries Inc., the maker of successful
televison programs such as ``The Dating Game'' and ``The Gong
Show,'' and Giant Group Ltd., the parent of Keystone Cement Co. and
Giant Cement Co.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
