<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Federated 3rdLd-Writethru f0252 03-14 0777</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Federated, 3rd Ld - Writethru, f0252,0796</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Macy Boosts Bid For Federated; Campeau To Face Off In Court</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8th graf pvs Sand did...to CLARIFY effect of judge's
order. Picks up 9th graf, Federated stock...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federated Department Stores Inc. on Monday
agreed to a sweetened friendly merger with R.H. Macy & Co., which
upped its initial bid by $200 million in cash to $6.3 billion,
giving it an edge over hostile competitor Campeau Corp.
   Under terms of the amended merger agreement unanimously approved
by the Federated board, Macy will offer $77.35 a share in cash for
80 percent of Federated's stock, up from $74.50 per share for the
same portion in its original offer.
   Macy plans to swap shares in a new company _ Macy's-Federated
Inc. _ and issue convertible debt securities for the remaining 20
percent of Federated shares. The offer expires on April 4.
   Meanwhile, Toronto-based Campeau indicated it had no immediate
intention of revising its rival bid. The company late Monday
extended its $6.18 billion tender offer through Friday in advance
of a court hearing over suits filed by both sides to challenge each
other's bids.
   U.S. District Judge Leonard Sand indicated at the lengthy
evening hearing that he would not rule before Wednesday either on
Macy's request to force Campeau to extend its tender offer past
Friday or on Campeau's challenge to Federated's ``poison pill''
takeover defense.
   Sand said he was seeking an opinion from the Securities and
Exchange Commission on Macy's contention that Campeau's latest
tender offer _ which was revised from a previous, lower bid _
constitutes a brand-new offer that must remain open past its
scheduled expiration. Macy hopes that by forcing Campeau to extend
its offer it will ease the pressure on Federated stockholders to
accept the Canadian company's bid.
   The judge said he would not get the SEC opinion before Wednesday
and would not rule on either suit before then.
   However, Sand stated that both buyout offers would have to
remain in effect for at least three business days after he ruled on
the poison pill issue, effectively extending Campeau's offer
through next week.
   Federated stock closed unchanged at $66 a share on the New York
Stock Exchange.
   In consideration for the sweetened offer from Macy, Federated
granted Macy a ``lockup'' option to purchase its
Bullock's-Bullock's Wilshire and I. Magnin retail divisions if the
merger is not successful. Federated said the divisions would sell
for at least $800 million and $150 million, respectively.
   Campeau has valued those divisions at a total of about $1.25
billion.
   Additionally, Macy granted Federated's board ``sole discretion''
over whether to maintain its ``poison pill,'' or shareholder-rights
plan, which makes unwanted takeovers prohibitively expensive. Under
its previous agreement, Cincinnati-based Federated would have
rescinded the plan in a merger with Macy.
   In recommending shareholders tender their stock to Macy,
Federated called the new offer ``substantially more favorable to
Federated stockholders than Macy's previous offer and the coercive
Campeau two-tier offer.''
   Campeau on Monday extended its hostile offer to buy 70.5 million
of Federated's stock, or 80 percent, at $75 a share from Tuesday
until Friday to take pressure off the federal judge who was to
preside over the courtroom battle.
   Campeau said the remaining 20 percent of Federated stock would
be acquired later for $44 cash per share in a subsequent merger,
giving the deal an aggregate value of $68 per share.
   Shortly after Campeau's move was announced, Federated urged its
shareholders to hold onto their stock, reversing an unusual
recommendation issued Sunday, when Federated ``reluctantly''
advised shareholders to tender their shares.
   Although Federated is opposed to merging with Campeau, the
retailer intended to make sure its shareholders got the higher
price offered in the first stage of Campeau's two-tier buyout bid.
   Federated said later Monday that its board again might advise
shareholders to tender to Campeau ``to avoid the risk of being
relegated'' to the $44-a-share ``backend.''
   If Campeau were to succeed in its bid, Federated vowed to go to
court, and urged shareholders to do the same rather than
``accepting the grossly inadequate price which Campeau has proposed
for its backend merger.''
   Federated owns department store chains including Bloomingdale's,
Burdine's, Filene's, Foley's, Rich's and Bullock's. Campeau has
indicated that if successful in acquiring Federated it planned to
sell Filene's and Foley's to May Department Stores Co. for about
$1.5 billion.
   Macy has nearly 100 department and specialty stores, while
Campeau owns Allied Stores Corp.
   Campeau said it expects to obtain all the necessary financing to
complete its buyout by the March 18 expiration date, but Federated
repeatedly has challenged that claim.
</TEXT>
