<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-88 2324EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-ContinentalAd     03-14 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Continental Ad,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contintenal Cited For Tying IRS Plan to Flying Their Skies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Continental Airlines advertisement designed to
catch readers' attention has caught some flak from the New York
City Consumer Affairs Department.
   The department said Monday it had cited the airline for a March
10 ad in the New York Times that it claims gave the false
impression that the U.S. Internal Revenue Service was involved with
the airline's promotion.
   The ad in question stated: ``Fly Continental to be out of the
country on April 15 and the IRS will allow you an automatic filing
extension.''
   Angelo Aponte, commissioner of Consumer Affairs, said the ad
falsely implied a sponsorship by the IRS and falsely asserted that
consumers must leave the country in order to get the automatic
extension to file.
   Aponte also said the ad failed to give important information
concerning the filing of extensions.
   Bruce Hicks, a spokesman at Continental's Houston headquarters,
said an IRS official indicated last week there were no problems
with the ad and that it was straightforward and accurate.
   ``We're mostly very puzzled that the department would insinuate
itself into an issue where there is no argument,'' Hicks said.
``The IRS has stated that it has no problems whatsoever with the
advertisement.''
   Gary Walker, a spokesman for the consumer affairs department,
said Continental was cited Friday and sent a notice via overnight
mail to its headquarters. Continental was directed to send a
representative to the department on March 25 and pay fines of up to
$500 for each violation.
   Hicks said no one at the airline's headquarters had seen the
notice, but the airline's representatives would attempt to clear up
the issue with the consumer affairs department.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
